<FIRST>r a AM-OfficersShot 1stLd-Writethru a0822 07-25 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Officers Shot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0822,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Angered By Construction Noise Opens Fire on Police, Killing One</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, last graf to CORRECT spelling of spokesman's
name to Bernethy, sted Bernethe.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA FALLS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man angered by construction noise
on Tuesday opened fire on police, killing one officer and wounding
two others before he was caught, officials said.
   The suspect led authorities on a six-hour manhunt before he was
apprehended by a highway patrol helicopter, which plucked him from
the Wichita River, about 125 miles northwest of Dallas, said David
Wells, spokesman of the Texas Department of Public Safety.
   Lt. Walter Tommy Collins, 52, died Tuesday night of cardiac
arrest shortly after undergoing surgery for bullet wounds at
Bethania Regional Hospital, said Sgt. Jim Bernethy, who heads the
homicide unit.
   Officer Steve Pruitt, 38, was in stable condition after
undergoing surgery for a shoulder wound, said Leslie Schaffner.
Officer Don Gossett, 35, who was shot in the leg, was treated and
released.
   The suspect, who has not been identified, was taken to Bethania
Regional and was to undergo surgery for a gunshot wound to the left
shoulder he apparently suffered in the exchange with police, said
Ms. Schaffner.
   The gunman fired a .30-caliber rifle when the officers arrived
at the suspect's trailer home about 11 a.m., officials said. The
confrontation began when the man complained about noise from a
construction crew working at a nearby vacant, six-unit building.
   ``When the first officer arrived on the scene, he tried to tell
the man to put the gun down and he was shot. Two other officers
responded. They also were shot,'' said Pat Yates, Wichita Falls
Police spokeswoman.
   Witness R.J. Logan said he saw the suspect and one officer stand
``toe-to-toe'' and exchange fire. Logan said the officer was hit in
the shoulder and the suspect was wounded in the side.
   Authorities could not immediately confirm Logan's report.
   Bernethy said the suspect could face a capital murder charge and
two attempted capital murder charges.
</TEXT>
