<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Nazis 1stLd-Writethru a0584 07-25 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Nazis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inquiry Recommends Prosecution of Suspected Nazi War Criminals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Home Secretary...' with 9 grafs to UPDATE with
injunction stopping TV showing of war-crimes documentary in middle of transmission.
Pick up 5th pvs, `He said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain has enough evidence to prosecute three
suspected Nazi war criminals, a government inquiry said Monday, but
a decision was postponed until Parliament can debate the issue this
fall.
   The War Crimes Inquiry recommended British courts be given the
power to hear cases of murder and manlaughter committed as war
crimes in Germany or German-occupied territory during World War II.
   After examining 301 allegations against people living in
Britain, it said there was sufficient evidence to prosecute four
people, although one has since died and another is in poor health.
Another 78 cases warrant further investigation, and attempts should
be made to trace 46 others alleged to have fled to Britain after
the war, it said.
   In Scotland, a television program about alleged Nazi war
criminals living in Britain was cut off Monday night after lawyers
acting for one of the men named in the program obtained a court
injunction.
   The program was stopped after 45 minutes of the hour-long
documentary ``Crimes of War'' had been shown. Directors of Scottish
Television (STV) ordered the transmission be stopped because of the
court action.
   Glasgow-based STV is part of Britain's commercial Independent
Television network.
   ``Crimes of War'' was broadcast without interruption last year
by STV and then throughout Britain by the Channel 4 station. STV
says the program helped prompt the government inquiry that resulted
in Monday's report.
   The injunction was granted by Judge Lord Prosser to lawyers
acting for Antanas Gecas at a closed-door hearing in the Scottish
capital of Edinburgh.
   Gecas, a 72-year-old a retired engineer living in Edinburgh, has
filed suit against The Times of London over stories it has printed
about him. No date has been set for a hearing.
   Gecas denies allegations that he took part in the wartime
killings of thousands of Jews in Nazi concentration camps and has
said he only witnessed the slayingsa.
   An STV spokesman released a statement saying: ``On legal advice
we took the program off the air. As far as I know it is the first
time a TV program (in Britain) has ever been halted in transmission
as the result of legal action.''
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd said the House of Commons and the
unelected House of Lords will debate the War Crimes Inquiry report
this fall and ``in the light of views expressed, the government
will take a final decision.''
   He said there would be many practical problems in bringing
criminal prosecutions decades later, including the age and frailty
of witnesses, the difficulties of assembling evidence and of
testifying ``when witnesses' memories are more than 40 years old.''
   But, quoting the report, he said: ``The crimes committed are so
monstrous that they cannot be condoned .... To take no action would
taint the U.K. with the slur of being a haven for war criminals.''
   The inquiry was set up in February 1988 after the government
received a list of alleged war criminals said to be living in
Britain from the Simon Wiesenthal Center, the Los Angeles-based
Nazi hunters. It was conducted by two prominent retired law
officers, Sir Thomas Hetherington and William Chalmers.
   Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean of the Simon Wiesenthal Center, called
the inquiry's report ``an historic victory,'' but said the
government took ``the easy way out'' by not giving Parliament
specific proposals.
   ``The inquiry deals with allegations of horrific killings on a
very large scale, crimes which would constitute violations of the
internationally agreed laws and customs of war,'' Hurd said in the
House of Commons.
   ``The allegations are not about actions committed in the heat of
war. They concern individuals allegedly holding quite senior
positions in paramilitary units in territories occupied by German
forces, whose task was the systematic murder of civilians.''
   Hurd ruled out extradition of suspects for trial in the Soviet
Union where many of the atrocities took place. The inquiry visited
the Soviet Union to interview witnesses.
   Lawmaker Roy Hattersley of the opposition Labor Party welcomed
the report, but urged the government to follow the lead of other
countries, such as Canada and Australia, to allow the prosecution
of all war criminals, not just Nazis.
   Labor lawmaker Peter Archer said suspected war criminals might
now decide to ``disappear for the second time.''
   Hurd said no action would be taken to stop them from leaving
Britain, adding such curtailment of people's movements would be
``unacceptable'' and unfounded.
   Conservative lawmaker Toby Jessel said: ``Isn't the real point
the sheer number of murders? We're not talking of one murder, nor
six, nor 60, nor 600, nor 6,000, nor 60,000, nor 600,000, but 6
million murders, including the murder of about a million children?
What is wrong with the idea of a little bit of justice for that?''
</TEXT>
