<FIRST>r a AM-StoreKillings 3rdLd-Writethru a0726 07-25 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Store Killings, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0726,0828</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oklahoman Arraigned on Charge While Investigation Broadens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to indicate that court appearance was
in Ardmore, gives location of Ardmore in 5th graf. Picks up 6th graf, `Greene's
father...'. ^By LINDA FRANKLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in three states waited to question
an auto mechanic about five killings while he appeared in court
Monday on a murder charge. New Mexico police said they arrested
another man who might be tied to the crimes.
   Ardmore District Attorney Fred Collins filed a first-degree
murder charge Sunday against Michael Frank Greene, 37, of Inola,
but said Monday he didn't want to discuss the charge until he had
heard from officers sent to Raton, N.M., to investigate the man
arrested there.
   Greg Francis Braun, 28, of Garden City, Kan., was charged Monday
in Raton with murder in the shooting death Sunday of a store clerk
in Springer, N.M.
   Authorities also were questioning him about the deaths of two
Kansas women. Those deaths are among those in which Greene is being
questioned, but there was no indication that the two men knew each
other.
   Greene was arrested Sunday in Lawton in the shooting death
Friday of a flower shop employee in Ardmore, about 95 miles south
of Oklahoma City.
   Greene's father said his son wasn't violent and had never liked
weapons, but had been drinking since his marriage broke up. A
former landlord said Greene had been ``ripping everybody off.''
   Authorities in Kansas, Texas and Indiana said after Greene's
arrest that they wanted to question him about slayings in their
states. Police in Pampa, Texas, where Greene's estranged wife
lives, charged him with capital murder in Thursday's shooting of a
photo shop operator.
   Kansas authorities wanted to talk to him about the slayings of
two convenience store clerks Wednesday in Garden City in western
Kansas. Two Indiana motel clerks were killed in March at
Merrillville and Remington.
   All the victims were shot in the head. The Indiana victims also
suffered other wounds.
   Ardmore Assistant Police Chief David Willingham said one of two
survivors of the shootings there identified Greene from photographs
as the man who wounded her and another woman and killed a third.
   Paul Renfrow, an Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigation
spokesman, said ballistics tests conducted on the bullets from the
Ardmore, Garden City and Pampa slayings showed the same .25-caliber
handgun was used in each case.
   A judge denied bond for Greene and set a preliminary hearing for
Sept. 28.
   The investigation took a new twist Monday when police in New
Mexico investigated the slaying of the Springer store clerk during
a robbery.
   Braun was arrested Sunday at a roadblock, driving a car with
Kansas license plates. He was arraigned Monday on an open charge of
murder in the woman's death and ordered held on $1 million bond.
   ``We expect to find evidence that is relevant to at least the
Kansas case, if not more,'' said Lesley Skinner, a deputy district
attorney in Colfax County, N.M.
   ``Right now we're not ruling anybody out,'' police Capt. Stan
Wojdylak of Garden City, Kan., said Monday after sending detectives
to New Mexico.
   ``I was asked last night if he (Greene) was a strong suspect. I
said yes he was. But now you're looking at a different set of
circumstances. We just have to see what happens when we talk to the
person in New Mexico. These are probably our two best leads,''
Wojdylak said.
   ``Just because we made an arrest doesn't mean we're not going to
continue ... following up on each and every lead we can,'' said
Pampa Deputy Police Chief Kenneth Hall.
   In an interview Sunday with The Daily Oklahoman, Greene's
father, Hank, said his son wasn't a criminal.
   ``He would give you the shirt off his back,'' Greene's father
told the newspaper. ``He's never even had a weapon in his house.
He's never liked them. He was always afraid the kids would get
ahold of them. He's never done no physica harm to anyone.''
   The elder Greene said his son started drinking heavily when his
wife filed for divorce recently. She has since moved to Pampa with
her parents.
   ``He loves his wife and kids very much. But when the split-up
happened, he told me he just lost it,'' Greene said.
   Greene has five children from two marriages.
   Greene had operated a car repair shop behind a service station
in Inola until June 30, when station owner Chester Flud said he
kicked Greene out. Inola is about 25 miles east of Tulsa.
   ``He wouldn't pay his bills and he was ripping everybody off and
I just got tired of it,'' Flud said Monday. Flud said Greene didn't
stand behind his work.
   Flud said Greene stayed around Inola for a few days and then
left town.
</TEXT>
