<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     07-25 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineers Study Space Shuttle Valve Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The planned early August launch of
space shuttle Columbia on a secret defense mission is likely to be
delayed at least a day because of a problem with a fuel valve, NASA
officials report.
   Engineers were conducting tests today to determine if the valve
was stuck or if they were receiving a false reading because of some
other problem.
   At the same time, shuttle managers were beginning a two-day
review of the readiness of all aspects of the mission. They planned
to set a firm launch date on Wednesday.
   Columbia had been scheduled to lift off July 31 with a
classified Defense Department payload, but minor technical problems
have forced delays. NASA said last week that Aug. 7 would be the
earliest possible launch date.
   The valve problem was detected early Monday following the brief
launch pad test firing of all three of Columbia's auxiliary power
units. Radio data indicated one of two hydrazine fuel valves
leading to APU No. 2 was stuck open when it should have been closed.
   The APUs provide power for moveable control surfaces such as
wing flaps, the speed brake and the rudder.
   NASA at first said the faulty unit would be replaced, a
procedure that would delay the launch two or three days. But
officials said later they were not certain the valve was stuck open
and they wanted to run some checks to determine what was wrong.
   They said the tests will add a day to Columbia's launch
processing schedule.
   When an APU valve stuck open before last December's launch of
the shuttle Atlantis, the replacement and checkout of the new unit
cost the launch team three days.
   Officials said they might be able to do the job in two days this
time because of the experience gained then.
   When Columbia is launched, its five-man all-military crew is to
deploy a Pentagon payload believed to be an advanced reconnaissance
satellite.
</TEXT>
