<DOCNO> AP890725-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-StolenGaugin     07-25 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stolen Gaugin,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Painting Reported Stolen From Heathrow Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say they are investigating the reported
theft from London's Heathrow airport of a Paul Gaugin watercolor
owned by the Beadlestone Gallery of New York.
   The London newspaper the Daily Mail, said the painting, valued
at more than $1.9 million, was stolen from a cargo hangar.
   It said the watercolor, measuring nine inches by four inches, is
titled ``Tahitienne en Pareo Rouge'' _ Tahitian woman in a red
pareu.
   Gaugin, a Frenchman who was born in 1848, lived and painted in
Tahiti in the South Pacific from 1895 until his death in 1903.
   ``The matter is the subject of an inquiry by the Criminal
Investigation Department at Heathrow,'' Scotland Yard said in a
brief statement that gave few other details.
   The Daily Mail said the painting was one of four that arrived on
a British Airways flight from New York on June 21.
   It said the consignment remained in the British Airways cargo
hangar until the owners arrived to collect them five days later.
   It said each of the pictures was in a separate box but that only
one, containing the Gaugin painting, was missing. The other three
paintings were not identified.
   The paper said the theft was not reported to police until
Sunday. Neither the paper nor Scotland Yard gave any reason for the
gap between the discovery of the theft and the reporting of it to
police.
</TEXT>
