<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-25 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of a personal ad reading
``WANTED: LIVE FLIES suitable for human consumption. Call
Renfield,'' says the message has turned up plenty of people with
pests to spare.
   ``They want to know what makes them suitable for human
consumption, what container we want them in and how much we pay,''
said Ira Domser, drama instructor and director-producer of
``Dracula'' at Western Maryland College.
   In ``Dracula,'' an insane character named Renfield eats flies
and spiders, Domser said.
   Domser admits last week's advertisement in the Carroll County
Times was a publicity ploy. He says he isn't making the actor eat
insects to get into character.
   Still, he may come to regret his ad. The calls are tying up the
box office telephone, giving workers more than their fill of spider
and fly tidbits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Look out for the newest member of the Heu and
Mai Ly family: He's a traffic-stopper.
   The infant entered the world Monday on a busy bridge, blocking
traffic in the heart of downtown.
   The couple was driving to the hospital and ``she said the baby
was coming,'' firefighter Odell Minor said. ``She told him to pull
over and stop the car.''
   A passerby had heard the husband's shouts for help and called
authorities.
   When Minor and fellow emergency medical technician Doran Kemp
arrived, the car was parked at an angle on a bridge over the
Milwaukee River, and the baby was on the car seat.
   ``He was lying quietly and moving, face up. New life,'' Minor
said.
   ``We wrapped him in a little blanket and gave him to his mom so
she could see him.'' He said the boy, who was not immediately
named, and mother were doing fine.
   An ambulance took the two to St. Mary's Hospital, and the
traffic jam cleared.
</TEXT>
