<FIRST>r p AM-DetroitMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0658 07-25 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Mayor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0658,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conyers Files Petitions to Run for Detroit Mayor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT that Conyers has served 13 terms in House.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen-term U.S. Rep. John Conyers filed
petitions Monday to make him eligible to run for mayor against
incumbent Coleman Young, who is seeking an unprecedented fifth term.
   Conyers accused Young of arrogance several weeks ago but avoided
announcing his candidacy then.
   ``I'm asking myself if I'm doing the right thing,'' Conyers said
Monday. ``One is never sure about these great decisions.''
   Conyers, 60, a Democrat, filed his petitions with City Clerk
James Bradley. ``He has more than enough petitions to make him
eligible, and they're still bringing more in,'' said Amelie Allen,
a worker in the clerk's office.
   Candidates have until 4 p.m. Tuesday to become eligible to run
in the non-partisan Sept. 12 primary. Accountant Tom Barrow and
businessman Charles Costa also filed petitions Monday. Young, who
announced his candidacy last week, was expected to file his
petitions later Monday.
   Speculation that Conyers would run increased after he lambasted
Young, saying the mayor ``has an unbroken record of personal and
political mistakes in the last few years.''
   ``It's time for him to go,'' Conyers said two weeks ago.
</TEXT>
