<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra     07-25 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Contra Prosecutors Oppose CIA Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors in the Iran-Contra scandal say the
CIA shouldn't invoke concerns over national security to block the
trial of one of the agency's former station chiefs.
   A federal appeals court judge granted the Justice Department's
request Monday to delay the trial of Joseph Fernandez, charged with
lying to investigators about his assistance to Oliver North's
Contra network.
   Fernandez says that to defend himself he must identify the
locations of three CIA stations and facilities in Latin America and
detail three of the agency's highly sensitive programs in Costa
Rica.
   The Justice Department, at the CIA's request, wants to prevent
the disclosures.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton, presiding over the case in
Alexandria, Va., rejected government proposals to substitute
numbers for the names of CIA stations and to abandon part of one
charge against Fernandez in exchange for dropping references to the
programs. Fernandez's trial was to have begun Monday.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals will decide whether to
allow the Justice Department to formally intervene and whether to
reverse Hilton's rulings.
   The CIA is trying to ``protect a fictional secret'' by objecting
to the release of the classified information, independent counsel
Lawrence Walsh said in a letter to the Justice Department.
   The Fernandez case, he said, will not be able to be tried if the
department blocks disclosure of the names of CIA stations and the
three CIA Costa Rican programs.
   The Classified Information Procedures Act gives Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh the authority to file an affidavit in court
prohibiting the disclosure of classified information. If a judge
deems the material vital, the criminal charges can be dismissed.
   In going to the appeals court, the Justice Department was
avoiding filing the potentially case-killing affidavit.
   Fernandez faces two counts of obstruction and two counts of
making false statements in his responses to the CIA inspector
general's office and the Tower Commission in 1987.
</TEXT>
