<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TritiumRestart     07-25 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tritium Restart,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savannah River: September 1990 is Westinghouse Date</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Secretary James Watkins is unhappy that
the first of the government's three tritium-producing nuclear
reactors won't be restarted until September 1990, long after
expected.
   Department spokesman Phil Keif said Monday that Watkins has
written the civilian contractor, Westinghouse Corp., saying ``he
wasn't very happy'' about such a long period before production
resumes.
   The three reactors at the Savannah River Site in South Carolina
have been shut for more than a year because of safety and
management concerns. During the shutdown, the previous contractor,
Du Pont Corp., withdrew and the government hired Westinghouse.
   The reactors are the sole source of tritium, a short-lived
radioactive gas essential for many nuclear weapons. Because tritium
decays to inert helium, the tritium charge must be renewed from
time to time.
   Defense officials have said some weapons might have to be
cannibalized to keep other weapons in service if tritium production
isn't restarted soon.
   Asked if the September 1990 date was a surprise, Keif said, ``I
think so.''
   ``Westinghouse sent this back in its restart plan. The secretary
wrote back and said he wasn't very happy with that, and we'd have
to get together again'' to see what could be done, Keif said.
   Keif said he didn't know if any new problems were discovered at
the reactors that would require such a delay.
   When the reactors were shut down in spring 1988, officials
expected to restart at least one that summer. The date has been
pushed back several times since then.
</TEXT>
