<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief 780   07-25 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief, 780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Bill Would Limit Grants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Endowment for the Arts would be
forbidden to award tax-paid grants to sponsors of two controversial
photographic exhibitions for five years under legislation approved
by a Senate Appropriations subcommittee.
   The panel Monday also endorsed a House-approved proposal to trim
the endowment's $171.4 million budget next year by $45,000 _ the
exact amount the agency gave for the controversial shows by
photographers Robert Mapplethorpe and Andres Serrano.
   The endowment is an independent federal agency that awards $169
million annually to a wide variety of artists and institutions
orchestras to painters and poets.
   ``Banning funding for specific institutions establishes a
dangerous precedent which goes against the long and widely
respected system of federal support for the arts through a
competitive peer review process,'' said Hugh Southern, acting
chairman of the endowment.
   The NEA gave $30,000 for a national tour of the Mapplethorpe
show, which included homoerotic and sadomasochistic pictures and
several photos of nude children. Serrano received a $15,000 NEA
grant for his work, which includes a widely criticized photograph
of a Christ figure submerged in a container of the artist's urine.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Logging Dispute Unsettled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vermont senator sidetracked subcommittee
action on draft legislation to impose a ceasefire in the battle
over logging in the ancient forests of the Pacific Northwest.
   Sens. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., and Brock Adams, D-Wash., planned
to ask the full Senate Appropriations Committee to approve the
legislation today despite concerns from Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
   Leahy says he's ``deeply disturbed'' that provisions in the bill
might pre-empt the right of environmentalists to appeal timber
sales to the courts.
   Leahy's skepticism dampened the excitement of the bill's
sponsors, who hope to ensure an adequate supply of logs to keep the
region's mills operating over the next 14 months, as well as
protect some of the old-growth forests that are prime habitat for
the northern spotted owl.
   Leahy, who has close ties to environmental groups, said he was
well aware that forest products were ``essential to the economic
health'' of the region, but added the right of appeal was also
vital.
   Hatfield agreed to postpone consideration of the bill until the
full committee meeting.
