<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Bush Supports Lucas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush stands behind William Lucas,
his embattled nominee to be the Justice Department's top civil
rights enforcer.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday that Bush
chose the Detroit lawyer as ``someone who would be a fighter for
civil rights; a black person who understood the black experience.''
   ``We stand behind the candidate,'' Fitzwater said.
   Lucas, the former sheriff of Wayne County, Mich., is opposed by
many civil rights groups who say he lacks experience to be
assistant attorney general for civil rights. They also have
criticized his defense of recent Supreme Court decisions on civil
rights.
   Supporters say that Lucas' stand on civil rights is the same as
that of Bush and Attorney General Dick Thornburgh.
   Several members of the Senate Judiciary Committee, which could
vote on the nomination as early as Thursday, expressed doubts about
Lucas after his testimony at confirmation hearings last week.
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., a prominent black congressman,
withdrew his support for the nominee after the hearing.
   And Monday, Jesse Jackson urged Judiciary Committee Chairman
Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., to reject Lucas as ``unsuitable'' for
the post.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Foley Criticizes Capital Gains Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley says President
Bush's plan to cut the capital gains tax rate is a ``misguided and
unfortunate'' proposal that would benefit the rich and hurt efforts
to cut the deficit.
   In a speech to the National Press Club on Monday, Foley said
more than a third of the total tax break would go to people earning
more than $1 million a year.
   ``The proposal of the president to cut the rate on capital gains
is, I think, misguided and unfortunate'' and would open the door to
tax shelters that ``seriously eroded public confidence in the tax
system,'' the Washington Democrat said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters, ``It is
definitely not a foregone conclusion that we are going to win this.
   ``We are working on it very hard. We think capital gains are
important. But there's still a lot of discussions to take place
over the next few days.''
   As a result of the 1986 tax overhaul, capital gains are taxed at
the same rates as other income: 15 percent, 28 percent and 33
percent. Bush campaigned on a promise of a 15 percent rate for all
capital gains, regardless of a taxpayer's total income.
</TEXT>
