<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>At Least One Dead, Four Injured in B-52 Fire on Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A B-52 bomber caught fire on the ground at
Kelly Air Force Base during a fueling exercise late Monday, killing
one person and injuring at least four others, base officials said.
   The accident occurred about 10:35 p.m., said 1st Lt. Dave Ebner.
   It originally was reported that fuel was being taken out of the
plane for maintenance work at the time of the accident, but base
officials later said the cause was still being investigated.
   The injured were taken to the Air Force's Wilford Hall Medical
Center for treatment, and a seven-member burn team was called to
assist.
   The identities of the victims were withheld pending notification
of family members. All were civilian employees, Ebner said.
   ``I heard four to five large explosions about 11 p.m. and saw
flames leaping 15 to 20 feet in the air,'' said Jim Fisher, a
school teacher who lives near the base.
