<FIRST>r i PM-Ambassador-Bloch     07-25 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ambassador-Bloch,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Ambassador Praises U.S. Diplomat Under Investigation</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Diplomat Spy, Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American diplomat suspected of spying
for the Soviets tried to cut a higher profile than his post
warranted but was well-connected and worked hard, according to a
former U.S. ambassador to Austria.
   Felix S. Bloch, who is in the United States and under FBI
investigation, was known as a ``workaholic'' when he worked at the
U.S. Embassy in Vienna, said the former ambassador, Helene Von Damm.
   Mrs. Von Damm promoted Bloch, then an economic expert at the
embassy, its deputy chief of mission when she took over as
ambassador in 1983. She resigned in June 1985.
   In an interview shown Monday on Austrian public television, Mrs.
Von Damm was asked about Bloch, a fellow Austrian native.
   Bloch was one of six applicants for the position of deputy
chief, and ``for me he was the best qualified,'' she said.
   He ``was already very well-connected, he was established, people
respected him and in Washington he was known as a man who was very
ambitious and hard-working, a kind of workaholic, and I thought he
actually suits me quite well,'' she said.
   But Mrs. Von Damm also said she had some trouble with Bloch.
   ``I was very satisfied with him to begin with,'' she said. ``I
even helped him get a special distinction, but as time went by he
tried time and again to enhance his profile in public, and I had to
rein him in again and again.
   ``I wasn't terribly harried by this at the time, it was a
problem I could cope with. No one is perfect, and other than that
he did very well.''
   She said that only at the time when she sent her letter of
resignation to Washington, ``there were signs that he (Bloch) was
not 100 percent loyal to me.'' She also said she advised Ronald
Lauder, who succeeded her as the U.S. ambassador in Vienna, to look
for someone to replace Bloch.
   Ex-Ambassador Lauder, now campaigning for mayor in New York
City, said Bloch was transferred to Washington from Vienna because
of insubordination.
   Mrs. Von Damm said that as deputy chief of mission Bloch had the
same access to secret documents and information as the ambassador
because ``he had the same top clearance.''
   In reply to a question, she said that Bloch knew the resident
CIA representatives in Vienna.
   If Bloch was a spy ``it would be a great damage'' for the United
States, she added. She spoke in German with an occasional English
phrase.
   Mrs. Von Damm resigned as ambassador following criticism of her
marriage to Vienna hotel owner Peter Guertler. It was her fourth
marriage, and it also ended in divorce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
