<FIRST>r a PM-MajorCon     07-25 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Major Con,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kansas Man Pleads Guilty To Impersonating An Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maj. Gen. Robert Lyons lived a life few
people could imagine.
   The youngest major general in U.S. history, he served with the
Central Intelligence Agency and the National Security Council. He
received two Medals of Honor, the nation's highest military honor,
and was recommended for a third.
   He also was a friend of Elvis Presley's.
   Sound too good to be true? It was.
   Robert Stanley Lyons, 35, pleaded guilty Monday in U.S. District
Court to a charge of falsely impersonating a federal officer.
   Lyons, who did serve in the Army but was discharged as a
private, was charged after a complaint from a woman gave him
$1,000. Lyons had told her he needed the money to pay off some bad
checks and get out of the CIA.
   According to Assistant U.S. Attorney Leon Patton, Lyons liked to
distribute a phony issue of Pentagon Gazette with a picture of
himself on the cover in a general's uniform.
   The issue was billed as ``a special tribute to one whom many
believe is Washington's well-known best-kept secret.'' It claimed
he pulled off one of the greatest feats in U.S. military history by
leading a four-man commando team to Southeast Asia in 1983,
rescuing 285 American prisoners of war and bringing back the
remains of 300 more.
   The bogus magazine carries an article under the byline of Paul
Summers that says, ``I strongly believe that Maj. Gen. Lyons has
left a trail never again to be matched or surpassed.''
   Patton said Lyons ``knew what he was doing and intended to do
it.''
   Lyons said he was trying to get psychological help.
   Sentencing was set for Sept. 2. Lyons faces up to three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
