<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-25 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged to
a record high Tuesday, and the dollar firmed one day after Japan's
prime minister resigned to take responsibility for a major defeat
at the polls.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
193.90 points Monday, added 445.57 points, or 1.31 percent, to
finish at 34,538.90. Roughly 1 billion shares changed hands.
   The dollar, which started at 142.20, closed at 142.35 yen, up
0.40 yen from Monday's close. It fluctuated between 141.98 yen and
142.60 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's firmness followed its similar trend in
New York on Monday, after news that Japan's long-governing Liberal
Democratic Party lost its majority in parliament's upper house.
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno announced the same day he will resign
to take responsibility for the defeat.
   ``The election was a big loss as dealers expected, and even
though Uno will resign, most people feel the political situation
won't change all that much,'' said Osamu Seto, a dealer with Mitsui
Bank.
   Meanwhile, dealers probably won't buy yen, Seto said. The focus
will move more towards interest rates in the United States and the
strength of its recovery, he added.
   An analyst at Okasan Securities Co., who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said housing issues carried the morning's bull market.
   Volume was increasing, he said, but high-tech stocks are weak.
He said there was no particular market-affecting news.
</TEXT>
