<FIRST>r i PM-Solidarity'sTravels     07-25 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solidarity's Travels,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-Profile Solidarity Lawmaker Visits Prague Spring Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity activist Adam Michnik
has used the official passport afforded him after he won a seat in
Poland's parliament to see Alexander Dubcek, leader of the crushed
Prague Spring uprising.
   Michnik and two other members of the the Polish free trade union
movement met with Dubceck for three hours Monday at the former
Communist Party leader's home in Bratislava, said Czechoslovak
activist Petr Uhl said.
   Dubcek and the Solidarity activists agreed that the Soviet-led
1968 invasion that crushed Dubcek's liberal reforms was ``an
unacceptable and illegal act,'' Uhl said. He was reached by
telephone from Vienna.
   Dubcek was ousted in April 1969 and expelled from the party in
June 1970.
   Czechoslovak police watched the Poles, accompanied by Czech
human rights activist Jan Urban, arrive at Dubcek's home but did
not interfere, said Uhl.
   He said police also filmed the Poles and Czechoslovaks arrive at
Urban's Prague home on Saturday for a meeting of activists.
   The meeting centered on the forthcoming 21st anniversary of the
1968 invasion, which is expected to be the focus of more
anti-government protests in Czechoslovakia.
   Uhl said the Solidarity activists spent Sunday night at the
country home of dissident playwright Vaclav Havel, Czechoslovakia's
most prominent human rights campaigner.
   Havel was jailed for eight months earlier this year but released
on parole after unprecedented protests at home and abroad.
   On Saturday, Michnik and the other Solidarity visitors met
Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek, 90-year-old head of Czechoslovakia's
beleaguered Roman Catholic church.
   Michnik, himself a former political prisoner, has also made use
of his new official passport to travel to the Soviet Union.
   Uhl said Michnik had informed Dubcek about his talks in Moscow
and his impressions of recent Soviet reforms, which the former
Czechoslovak leader has praised in public statements since 1987.
   Round-the-clock surveillance of Dubcek was lifted that year when
Mikhail S. Gorbachev visited Czechoslovakia, and Dubcek was
permitted last fall to go to Italy to receive an honorary degree.
   There, he made a series of statements criticizing Prague's
current Communist leaders. He has not been allowed to travel abroad
since.
   Uhl said Michnik planned to return to Poland today.
</TEXT>
