<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Tourists     07-25 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Tourists,0393</SECOND>
<UNK>Japanese Tourists Blaze Trail In Iran, But Red Tape A Problem</UNK>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Japanese tourists are
visiting Iran, the first foreigners to take package tour vacations
in the country since the 1979 Islamic revolution, Iran's official
news agency reported today.
   But the Islamic Republic News Agency quoted the transport
industry magazine Sanat Hamlo Naql as saying ``formalities'' at
Tehran's Mehrabad airport are ``enough to ruin the whole trip.''
   The monthly magazine noted: ``Most of the Japanese questioned
said that just because of the difficulties of entering and exiting
Mehrabad they are not willing to come to Iran ever again.''
   Rigorous security, immigration and customs controls at Mehrebad,
in and out, involve lengthy waits, sometimes lasting several hours
at an airport not renowned for its services.
   IRNA quoted Mehdi Hashemi, head of the state-run Foundation for
the Disabled's hotel and travel agencies division, as saying: We
have problems at the airport and we're trying to solve them.
   ``These problems show that the officials in charge do not have
the right picture of a tourist,'' he said.
   ``Tourism is considered very important even to countries which
do not have much need for foreign exchange. But for Iran the
attraction of tourists is obviously more important,'' Hashemi noted.
   The magazine said as many as 500 Japanese, in groups of a few
dozen, have visited Iran since May.
   Since the August cease-fire in the 8-year war with Iraq, Iran
has been seeking to redevelop a once-thriving tourist industry that
collapsed during the 1979 Islamic revolution.
   The IRNA report, monitored in Nicosia, made no mention of
tourists other than Japanese visiting Iran.
   But Tehran has been boosting relations with Third World
countries and the Soviet bloc, while its relations with the West
remain icy.
   IRNA said the Japanese spend $3,500 in hard currency for a
10-day visit. The price includes a $2,000 round-trip ticket from
Tokyo with Iran Air, Iran's national carrier.
   The package tours, organized by the Disabled Foundation's
tourism division, takes the visitors to historical sites in Tehran
as well as the provincial cities of Shiraz, Isfahan, Hamadan and
Bakhtaran.
   ``Iran today is not well-experienced in tourism, but with the
expansion of this operation, there's hope for improvement,'' said
Nasser Moradi, a manager of the tourist organization.
</TEXT>
