<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0521EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FilmAnniversary     07-25 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Film Anniversary,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family, Film Stars Remember Groundbreaking Film</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto CR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET LILLARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KEENE, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Johnston Jr. had tears in his eyes as
he watched his family's story once again on the big screen, 40
years after his chance remark to a famous filmmaker resulted in a
movie about race.
   Johnston sat with his mother, Thyra, and a crowd of nearly 700
people Monday night to watch ``Lost Boundaries'' and remember the
man who inspired it _ his father, Dr. Albert Johnston.
   ``We're all here because a brave man and a patriotic man ...
tried to join a segregated Navy,'' said Keene State College film
professor Lawrence Benaquist, who organized the reunion on the 40th
anniversary of the film's opening in Keene.
   The fair-skinned Johnstons passed for white in Gorham and Keene
in the 1930s and '40s so Johnston could find work as a doctor.
   They kept the secret even from their children until 1941, when
Johnston was refused a Navy commission when naval investigators
found he belonged to a black fraternity in college and had black
ancestry.
   Several years later, Albert Jr. and other University of New
Hampshire students visited Louis de Rochemont, producer of the
``March of Time'' documentary films, at his Newington home to
encourage fairer treatment of minorities in films.
   On his way out, Albert Jr. mentioned the revelation that was to
enthrall de Rochemont. The two subsequently convinced the Johnstons
to let the filmmaker dramatize their story.
   ``We never had any bad repercussions,'' said the 88-year-old
Mrs. Johnston, now of Kaneohe, Hawaii. ``The story has not hurt us
at all.''
   The film won the 1949 Cannes Film Festival award for best script
and was revolutionary for its time, treating its subject in a bold,
documentary-like fashion.
   ``All of us had a certain real conviction about the theme of the
picture and the content of the picture, and I didn't hesitate,''
said Mel Ferrer, who made his screen debut in the film portraying
Dr. Johnston's character.
   At Keene State College's Arts Center, Ferrer and other members
of the cast and crew recalled the difficulties caused by the film's
touchy topic.
   De Rochemont was under contract to MGM at the time he decided to
make ``Lost Boundaries,'' but the major studio balked at the idea
after initial enthusiasm about the project, associate producer
Borden Mace said.
   De Rochemont scraped together the money _ even mortgaging his
house _ to make the film independently, Mace explained. But he said
a desire for authenticity, not financial concerns, prompted the
producer to use unknowns and shoot on location in New Hampshire and
Maine.
   The film was slightly fictionalized, with the names of people
and places altered.
   At first reluctant to see their lives on the screen, the family
was _ and still is _ pleased with the film. Mrs. Johnston said she
wished the film were more widely known.
   ``I think it would help the younger people to know what it was
like then,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0522EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PalestinianPlay     07-25 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palestinian Play,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shakespeare Festival Reaffirms Decision to Cancel Palestinian Play</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producer Joseph Papp reaffirmed his decision to
cancel an appearance by a Palestinian theater company but said he
hoped to present it along with other productions dealing with the
Middle East within a year.
   Papp, producer of the New York Shakespeare Festival, decided
last month to withdraw an offer to the El-Hakawati Palestinian
Theater Company of Jerusalem because of concern about the reactions
of Jewish theatergoers.
   ``I live with my decision and my sensibilities _ particularly
those that relate to national and religious groups living in New
York where my plays are presented,'' Papp said at a news conference
Monday. ``If there had been an overwhelmingly large Arabic
theater-going population living here, I would be just as sensitive
to their beliefs and concerns as I am to Jews.''
   The six-person company was to have performed ``The Story of
Kufur Shamma'' at the Public Theater last week. The play tells of a
40-year search by a Palestinian man for residents of his village
that was decimated by the 1948 Arab-Israeli war.
   Papp met Monday with members of the American-Arab Relations
Committee. Members of the committee said the meeting was cordial,
but issued a statement saying Papp's decision assumed that ``New
York Jews are intolerant and have the power to suppress the First
Amendment rights of others.''
   ``I think there should be a stronger commitment to an open
society,'' M.T. Mehdi, president of the committee, said at the news
conference.
   Papp said there had been no pressure from Jewish groups to
suppress the play, and called his decision a ``personal'' one.
   ``I never objected to the play itself,'' Papp said. ``After I
agreed to present the play, I discovered we were not putting on
anything else (about the Israeli-Palestinian problem) at the same
time.''
   Papp said he would like to present different plays covering a
wide spectrum of views about the Palestinian problem and indicated
he would attempt to do so within 12 months.
   ``In this particular instance, I'll have things that represent
the whole issue of the Palestinian situation and seek those (types
of) plays _ whether they be Palestinian or Israeli plays,'' Papp
said.
   ``The Story of Kufur Shamma'' will still be seen in New York. It
will be presented for seven performances, beginning Wednesday, at
the Dance Theater Workshop, an off-off-Broadway company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0540EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-ChannelAttempt     07-25 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Channel Attempt,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Ditches in English Channel Trying to Recreate First Crossing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot trying to re-enact the first
flight across the English Channel on its 80th anniversary was
forced to ditch her plane just two miles short of the British coast
today.
   Gloria Pullan was commemorating French Aviator Louis Bleriot's
July 25, 1909, flight from Calais, France, to Dover, England, in an
authentic Bleriot XI monoplane, the same type used for his crossing.
   ``I took off from Calais and it was a beautiful flight until I
started losing power,'' she said, clutching her wet British
passport. ``Gradually the aircraft went down and I had to ditch in
the sea about two miles off Dover.
   Ms. Pullan, 36, was rescued by a Royal Air Force helicopter
after being in the water for three minutes.
   She was taken to a field atop the famous White Cliffs of Dover
where a large welcoming party was waiting on the spot where Bleriot
landed.
   ``It was so sad,'' she said. ``I think the aircraft has been
lost. I was enjoying it so much and I would do it again any time. I
am sorry I could not bring the airplane into land for the official
reception.''
   Louis Bleriot, grandson and namesake of the pioneer aviator,
flew in a helicopter alongside Ms. Pullan's plane and saw it crash.
   ``It was very sad seeing the aircraft go into the sea,'' he said
at Dover. ``I believe it sank. I could not see it afterwards.''
   Bleriot's flight was staged in response to a challenge by
English newspaper magnate Lord Northcliffe who offered a prize of
$1,600 to the first person to cross the channel by air.
   Bleriot covered the 22-mile journey across the narrowest part of
the channel in 36 minutes and crash-landed his fragile flying
machine in a field near Dover Castle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
