<DOCNO> AP890725-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0541EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Sakharov-China     07-25 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sakharov-China,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Walk Out of Conference; Ambassador Urges Non-Interference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of international scientists
hoped to get back to work on disarmament after criticism of the
Beijing crackdown by Soviet physicist Andrei Sakharov triggered a
walkout by Chinese delegates.
   The walkout at Monday's opening session of the 39th Pugwash
Conference came after Sakharov condemned the Chinese government's
brutal repression of student protesters.
   ``We cannot forgive or disregard the conduct of the Chinese
government and we must find ways to demonstrate this attitude,''
the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner said. One of the two Chinese
delegates who walked out during the speech later confronted
Sakharov.
   The sensitivity by Chinese leaders over the crackdown,
meanwhile, also was evident Monday in comments made by Han Xu,
China's ambassador to the United States.
   ``At present, the important thing is not to interfere in China's
internal affairs, particularly when it is in difficulty. Do not
make things more difficult,'' Han, 65, said at a luncheon in West
Palm Beach, Fla.
   They were his first public comments ``since those terrible
developments occurred in China,'' he said, adding that it would be
his last as ambassador. The 65-year-old said he soon will retire
and return to Beijing.
   Han said additional economic sanctions against China ``hurt the
United States as much as they hurt China. The only effect on China
that I can think of is that would push back China into the
isolation of the old days.''
   At the conference, M. Innas Ali, a nuclear physicist from
Bangladesh, said Sakharov's confrontation with the Chinese did not
dampen the optimism of most delegates.
   ``Now everybody is moving in the right direction, toward
disarmament,'' he said. ``But we still have to do some constructive
work so this can be realized in practice.''
   About 200 scientists and statesmen from more than 30 countries
are attending the five-day conference, which is being held in the
United States for the first time in 19 years.
   The Pugwash conferences grew out of a 1955 statement by Bertrand
Russell and Albert Einstein urging scientists of all political
persuasions to devise ways to avoid nuclear war. The first
conference was held in 1957 at Pugwash, Nova Scotia.
   Most of the sessions are devoted to technical arms control
issues and are closed to the public.
   The Chinese delegates waited outside the conference room during
Sakharov's 45-minute speech, which was largely devoted to Soviet
economic and environmental problems. Then one of them, Professor
Shi Zhongben of Beijing University, confronted the 68-year-old
human rights activist.
   Trembling with emotion, Shi said Sakharov did not understand
Chinese affairs and had chosen an inappropriate forum for his
criticism.
   ``We can build peace through international cooperation _ not by
interfering in the internal affairs of other countries,'' Shi said.
   Sakharov remained impassive. ``Maybe I don't understand all the
complexities of the situation in China, but I think I was right,''
he said later.
   Despite the incident, Shi and colleague Niu Qiang of the Chinese
People's Association for Peace and Disarmament said they planned to
attend the rest of the conference.
   Two other Chinese delegates kept their seats in another part of
the room, but it was unclear whether they did so deliberately or
failed to notice the departure of Shi and Niu.
   After the Chinese Army violently crushed the pro-democracy
protest in Beijing's Tiananmen Square on June 3-4 _ with estimates
of deaths running from several hundred to as high as 3,000 _ the
new Soviet Congress issued a guarded statement calling it ``an
internal matter.''
   Sakharov, who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb in the
1950s, later spoke out against Soviet human rights abuses and the
war in Afghanistan and was banished to internal exile in the city
of Gorky from 1979 to 1986.
</TEXT>
