<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major currencies in
brisk European trading early today. Gold prices were higher.
   The dollar lost ground in jittery trading overnight and appeared
to be stabilizing in late morning European trading, but many
dealers expected dollar-selling to resume with the opening of the
New York market.
   Dealers said sentiment is gradually turning more bearish against
the dollar.
   ``There are a lot of people who expect a much lower dollar by
the beginning of August,'' said a trader in Rome.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.40 Japanese yen to a closing 142.35
yen. Later, in London, it was unchanged at 142.35 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday:
   _1.8910 West German marks, down from 1.9055
   _1.6290 Swiss francs, down from 1.6455
   _6.4155 French francs, down from 6.4460
   _2.1317 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1350
   _1,375.00 Italian lire, up from 1,371.50
   _1.1875 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1880
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6260 from $1.6185 late
Monday.
   Gold bullion opened in London at a bid price of $373.10 a troy
ounce, up from $372.25 late Monday. London bullion dealers fixed a
recommended gold price Tuesday morning of $72.80.
   In Zurich, the metal rose to $372.75 bid from $371.50 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 42 cents to close at a bid $373.
   Silver bullion edged up in London to $5.22 a troy ounce from
$5.21 bid late Monday.
