<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0488,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 11-14 `On the...dealer said.'' with 4 grafs to CORRECT
name and affiliation of dealer. Pickup 15th (</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Stock Exchange's key index surged to a record
high and the dollar rose against the Japanese yen today, a day
after Japan's prime minister said he would resign to take
responsibility for a major electoral defeat.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
193.90 points Monday, added 445.57 points, or 1.31 percent, today,
closing at 34,538.90. Roughly 1 billion shares changed hands.
   The dollar opened at 142.20 and closed at 142.35 yen, up 0.40
yen from Monday's close of 141.95 yen. t fluctuated between 141.98
yen and 142.60 yen.
   In an election Sunday, Japan's long-governing, pro-business
Liberal Democratic Party lost its majority in parliament's upper
house for the first time in its 34-year history.
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno announced that he would resign to
take responsibility.
   A trader with Yamaichi Securities Co., speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the election was not having a major impact on Tokyo
markets.
   ``Abroad, investors grasp that market fundamentals have not
changed in Japan,'' and this has acted as a spur to active trading
domestically, he said.
   Domestic demand-related issues received particular attention
today. There were large buying orders for housing issues, the
trader said.
   In addition, consumer products issues were bought on news that a
Tokyo court had ruled in favor of Shuwa Corp., a large real estate
firm that is trying to reconstruct the retail market through
several unfriendly mergers.
   Liberal Democratic Party statements that the party would
reconsider the new 3 percent sales tax also spurred buying of such
issues. Voter anger over the 4-month-old tax was seen as a major
factor in the party's election loss.
   On the foreign exchange market, a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo,
who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there was heavy buying of
West German marks with yen today.
   ``Traders feel that selling yen against the dollar is dangerous,
so they are buying European currencies,'' he said.
   Traders have said the market anticipates lower interest rates in
the United States, which would make dollars less attractive.
   Their reluctance to buy yen stems from the continuing political
instability in Japan, the dealer said.
   ``People feel that the political situation in Japan will become
chaotic again. But the longer the chaos lasts, the less important
it will be,'' he said.
</TEXT>
