<HEAD>Animal Activist Acknowledges Ordering Castration Of Donkey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brigitte Bardot has acknowledged ordering the
castration of a donkey she was keeping for a neighbor, but she says
she should be above suspicion because of her concern for animal
welfare.
   Bardot, a former film star who has devoted herself to animal
causes, said in a statement issued Sunday that the donkey Charly
was castrated by a veterinarian under anesthesia.
   She said she agreed to keep Charly for a Lyon businessman, Jean
Pierre Manivet, but the donkey's amorous interest in an elderly
female donkey already on the grounds was so excessive as to
endanger the female.
   Manivet subsequently complained that his donkey was castrated
without his consent.
   Bardot said she tried unsuccessfully to contact Manivet before
ordering the operation.
   ``I think I am above suspicion as to the way I treat and care
for animals, whether they are confided to me or belong to me,'' she
said in a statement.
