<FIRST>r a PM-FloodChannelRescue     07-25 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flood Channel Rescue,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body of Youth Recovered After Dramatic Rescue Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have recovered the body of
a teen-ager who lost his grip on a lifeline in a rain-swollen flood
channel after being struck by debris.
   The body of Peter Alvarado, Jr., 16, was found Monday in Alameda
Arroyo, a flood plain that received the rushing waters of the
Embudo Channel on Sunday.
   Peter and his 14-year-old brother, David, had been skateboarding
in the concrete-lined Northeast Heights flood channel Sunday when a
3-foot-high wall of water from a sudden thunderstorm hit them.
   David was rescued.
   Peter was within a few feet of high ground when a chair carried
by the torrent struck him and knocked him off a lifeline across the
channel. His younger brother and rescuers helplessly watched him
float away.
   The body was found 10 to 12 miles downstream after it was
spotted by people looking over a bridge, according to Anthony
Garcia, a member of the aquatic rescue team for the Bernalillo
County Fire Department.
   ``As a parent you think that your children might be mature
enough to be secure,'' said the boys' father, Peter Alvarado Sr.,
as he watched rescuers recover his son's body. ``There's really no
constraint you can have on a child once they leave your house.''
   He added: ``We're lucky to have one boy who is safe and sound.''
   David was treated for cuts and bruises at St. Joseph Hospital,
city Fire Department spokesman Ernie Watson said.
   The National Weather Service said an inch of rain fell in the
area in less than an hour.
   At least 10 people, including four police officers and four
firefighters, were injured trying to rescue the brothers.
</TEXT>
