<FIRST>r a PM-WrongMan     07-25 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wrong Man,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Refuses to Indict Accused Subway Gunman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury refused to indict a man accused of
shooting three people at a subway stop, and he was freed after
spending 11 days in jail for a crime he denied committing.
   Clemente Jackson, 21, was arrested June 22 by transit police
handing out a composite sketch of the gunman. He denied the crime
but spent 11 days in jail until he was freed on bond.
   The shooting was done June 10 by a man who recognized a group of
young men who apparently had robbed him a day earlier at another
subway stop. He asked them, ``Remember me?'' and then shot three of
them, police have said.
   The three who were wounded, aged 14, 24 and 26, were charged
with robbery; one is still hospitalized.
   Jackson expressed dismay with the ordeal after Monday's grand
jury decision. He said he may sue the city for false arrest.
   ``I can't believe I went through all this. It was like a
nightmare,'' he said.
   Eight relatives and friends testified that Jackson was far from
the scene of the crime.
   Jackson's supporters said prosecutors did a poor job of handling
the case, and some defense witnesses charged their testimony was
limited.
   ``Only because of the public outcry on behalf of this young man
was the grand jury able to hear the evidence,'' said Bonita E.
Zelman, his lawyer.
   Jackson said he was convinced prosecutors knew he was innocent,
but prosecutors said they had acted in good faith.
</TEXT>
