<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0842EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Austria-Bloch     07-25 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Austria-Bloch,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Claims Bloch Confessed To Spying As Swap For Immunity Guarantee</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Diplomat-Spy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported today that senior
diplomat Felix S. Bloch has already confessed to spying for years
for the Soviets in exchange for a guarantee of immunity from
prosecution.
   But the newspaper, Der Standard, quoted ``reliable'' CIA sources
as saying publicity of the case has cast doubt on the deal.
   Bloch, who served as the second-in-command at the U.S. Embassy
in the Austrian capital during much of his stint there from
1980-87, is in the United States under FBI investigation. He has
not been formally charged.
   News reports of the spy probe began Friday.
   The daily, which began publication last fall, said without
further detail that a preliminary investigation of Bloch began in
February 1988 and was completed in March of this year.
   After taking office in January, President Bush appointed Bloch
director of the Office of European Regional Political-Economic
Affairs in the State Department's Bureau of European and Canadian
Affairs.
   The newspaper did not refer to that appointment or explain how
it could have been made if Bloch was already under suspicion.
   Bloch was the highest-ranking U.S. official ever implicated in
an espionage investigation involving the Soviet Union. He was
reportedly filmed by U.S. officials earlier this year passing a
briefcase to a Soviet KGB agent in a European capital.
   By all accounts, the Austrian-born Bloch had access to sensitive
   intelligence material during his career, and officials expressed
concern he could cause serious damage to U.S. interests if he
shared his secrets with foreign powers.
</TEXT>
