<DOCNO> AP890725-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0843EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BlochProfile 1stLd-Writethru a0450 07-25 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bloch Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Describe Suspected Spy as Dull, Dry Diplomat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Diplomat Spy, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 16, In Austria, to CORRECT spelling of Von Damm.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix S. Bloch, suspected of passing secrets
to the Soviets, is described by friends as a dull and dry U.S.
diplomat who badly wanted an ambassador's post.
   Bloch and his family remained under tight surveillance after
media reports placing him at the center of what could be the
biggest State Department espionage case since the 1950s.
   ``Everybody is stunned and depressed,'' said one State
Department official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Friends and colleagues spoke of Bloch as a precise, analytical
man respected for his grasp of European affairs but frustrated at
the pace of his State Department career.
   ``Dry, bureaucratic, competent, ambitious,'' was the description
offered by his friend, Austrian Foreign Minister Alois Mock, who
has known Bloch and his wife, Lucille, for more than 30 years.
   Mock told Austrian reporters that Bloch chafed at serving under
politically appointed ambassadors without becoming ambassador
himself.
   At his condominium near Washington's Embassy Row, neighbors said
Bloch and his wife were reserved and private, though friendly.
   Preston Pitts, a neighbor, said Bloch told him earlier this year
that an ambassador's job might come soon: ``He told me he was
slated to be an ambassador to Central or South America _ I didn't
ask the country. He hoped to be; he was up for it.''
   Pitts said the first sign anything was amiss came nearly a month
ago when FBI agents began a heavy and visible surveillance of Bloch.
   Agents were seen throughout the building and sitting in cars
around it, he said, prompting concern and talk by many residents.
   ``The agents were around here like ants _ they were too
obvious,'' said Pitts. ``I saw him in the hall and said, `Felix,
are you in any danger?' He said, `No.' ... I thought they were here
to protect him.''
   Bloch was filmed by U.S. officials earlier this year passing a
briefcase to a known Soviet KGB agent in Paris, according to
sources. The State Department issued a statement saying it and the
FBI were ``pursuing the inquiry thoroughly in order to identify the
compromised security which has occurred and the appropriate steps.''
   No charges have been filed.
   President Bush described reports of spying by Bloch as ``very
serious.''
   Bloch served in the U.S. Embassy in Vienna from 1980-87, most of
that time holding the No. 2 post in the embassy.
   Bloch returned to Washington in 1987 and became director of the
State Department's office of European regional political-economic
affairs. He was considered a top specialist on the European
Community.
   In Austria, he served under Reagan ambassadorial appointees
Ronald Lauder, and before that, Helene Von Damm, a longtime aide to
Reagan.
   ``I did not like him,'' said Lauder, a candidate for the
Republican nomination for mayor of New York City.
   ``There was something about him that bothered me,'' Lauder said
on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' program. ``The more I got to know
him the more I realized there was something dramatically wrong.''
   However, Lauder said he did not suspect espionage.
   Bloch appeared to be more highly regarded among others. A former
Austrian official, Ernst Eugen Veselsky, called Bloch
``substantially more knowledgeable than others.''
   Bloch was born in Austria and left that country at age 3 with
his Jewish parents. Bloch is a graduate of the University of
Pennsylvania and holds a master's degree from the University of
California at Berkeley.
   He held a variety of State Department jobs, including economic
counselor at the U.S. Embassy in East Berlin in 1974. He later was
an inspector who traveled to various embassies.
   Mock told reporters in Austria that he learned of suspicions
about Bloch three weeks ago and that ``there was an allusion this
might go back to the 1970s.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
