<FIRST>u w PM-DurableGoods     07-25 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Durable Goods,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales of Military Items Power Rise in Durable Goods Orders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods,
powered by a surge in sales of military goods, rose a modest 0.3
percent in June, the government said today.
   The Commerce Department said demand for durable goods, items
expected to last three or more years, totaled a seasonally adjusted
$124.1 billion. The rise followed a large 4.4 percent decline in
May, the steepest in 10 months.
   The modest rebound was unlikely to persuade economists that
durable-goods sales, one of the most interest-rate-sensitive
sectors of the economy because buyers must usually borrow to
purchase them, are breaking out of their recent sluggish pattern.
   Early in June, the Federal Reserve Board nudged interest rates
down slightly, ending a year-long program of fighting inflation
with higher interest rates. The Fed's shift to easier credit likely
will take several months to influence sales, however.
   Excluding the volatile defense category, which swings widely
from month to month, new orders fell 0.7 percent last month
following a decline of 3.9 percent in May.
   Military orders shot up 15.8 percent in June to $8.8 billion
after dropping 11.4 percent in May and plunging 18.3 percent in
April.
   The closely watched category of non-defense capital goods, a
barometer of business investment plans, rose 0.5 percent in June to
$37.5 billion following a 7.7 percent plunge a month earlier.
   The Commerce Department offered these other details of activity
in June:
   _Non-electrical machinery orders rose 3.7 percent to $23.1
billion, reflecting an increase in purchases of steam engines and
turbines.
   _Electrical machinery gained 2.8 percent to $19.2 billion
following a 6.1 percent drop in May.
   _Transportation equipment declined 3.5 percent to $32.3 billion
following a 9.7 percent drop a month earlier. Most of the decline
came in motor vehicles and parts and shipbuilding.
   _Primary metals, including steel, were off 5.0 percent to $12.0
billion following a 1.8 percent decline in May.
   For the first six months of the year, new orders totaled $755.1
billion, 8.2 percent higher than the first half of 1988. The figure
does not take inflation into account.
   Shipments of durable goods fell 1.1 percent to $121.6 billion in
June, following a 0.3 percent decline in May.
</TEXT>
