<FIRST>r i PM-ManitobaFires 2ndLd-Writethru a0496 07-25 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manitoba Fires, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0496,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rain on Huge Canadian Forest Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with thunderstorms today. Pickup
2nd graf `More than...'; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``There's no...' Minor
editing to TRIM</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thundershowers rumbled across Manitoba
and Saskatchewan today, sending light rain on hundreds of forest
fires that have blackened more than 2.2 million acres.
   Canadian officials held out hope that more rain later today
would relieve the fires, which have forced the evacuation of more
than 19,000 people from northern Manitoba.
   Pilots trying to pick up people fleeing the fires have been
frustrated by smoke so thick it turns the sun into a reddish smudge.
   ``There's no sunlight to speak of at all,'' Northern Affairs
Minister Jim Downey said after returning from the sparsely
populated wooded region on Monday. ``It's like dusk in the middle
of the afternoon.''
   Downey had flown with Manitoba Premier Gary Filmon to Thompson,
The Pas and Flin Flon, where evacuatees were being taken.
   Hot, dry winds blew flames perilously close to native
settlements and mining towns and officials said thick smoke
hindered evacuation efforts.
   ``It's sometimes an hour-to-hour situation, waiting for the
smoke to lift to a point where a plane can land,'' said provincial
government spokeswoman Diana Soroka.
   Thompson, a mining city of about 15,000, has taken in more than
3,000 evacuees. It was many miles from the nearest fire Monday, but
the city's airport was temporarily shut down because of the smoke.
   The fire zone begins about 250 miles north of Winnipeg and
stretches about 220 miles from northeastern Saskatchewan to
northwestern Ontario.
   Officials estimated 224 fires were burning in Manitoba on
Monday, but said that might not be accurate because they could not
see the fire for the smoke.
   Soroka said some evacuees were being taken to Brandon and
Winnipeg in the south: ``We're taking them wherever the room is.''
She said people were being evacuated by plane, train and car.
   The province has not yet had to use its powers under the state
of emergency declared Sunday, which include being able to
commandeer private property.
   Military transport planes, helicopters, hoses, pumps, tents, and
other materials have been pouring in from other parts of Canada and
the United States.
   About 1,600 firefighters, 53 helicopters, 11 waterbombers, nine
fixed-wing aircraft and several pieces of heavy equipment, such as
bulldozers, have been thrown into the effort.
   It's estimated $25 million will be spent by the end of the week,
compared with $15 million for the whole season last year.
   But the only thing firefighters can do is hold the lines around
communities _ so far they have been relatively successful. Only a
few houses and lodges have burned, and there have been no reports
of injuries or deaths.
</TEXT>
