<FIRST>u w PM-HomeSales     07-25 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Sales,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Existing Homes Sales Rebounded 5.9 Percent in June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes rebounded 5.9 percent
in June following five months without a gain, a real estate trade
group said today, attributing the rise to a decline in mortgage
rates and falling prices.
   The National Association of Realtors said sales of existing
single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
3.40 million units in June, up from May's rate of 3.21 million
units. It was the first increase in sales since December 1988 and
the largest increase since December 1986, when sales jumped 6.6
percent.
   The group also noted what it described as a small increase in
the median sales price, which was $93,200 in June, up $600 from May
and 3.2 percent from a year earlier.
   ``For the most part, buyers coming into the market in June are
the most vulnerable to rate swings. They're getting in while they
can, buying the most they can. The homes they're buying tend to be
in the moderate price range,'' said Realtors President Ira Gribin.
   According to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., fixed-rate
mortgages peaked at 11.22 percent in late March and have been
falling since, hitting 9.87 percent last week. During June, they
fell from 10.48 percent to 10.07 percent.
   Economist Richard Peach of the Mortgage Bankers Association of
America said he expected sales to recover modestly through the rest
of the year. But, he said sluggish economic and job growth overall
will prevent a strong resurgence.
   Regionally, sales were led by an 18.5 percent jump in the
Midwest to an annual rate of 960,000 units, the highest level since
December. Sales rose 5.2 percent in the West to 610,000 units and
4.1 percent in the South to 1.28 million units.
   In the Northeast, however, sales fell 9.8 percent to a rate of
550,000 units, the lowest since February 1985.
   Economist John A. Tuccillo of the Realtors said Midwestern sales
are being bolstered by relatively low prices, while the rapid rise
in prices in the Northeast over the past several years is
preventing a sales rebound there.
</TEXT>
