<FIRST>u i PM-India 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0485,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Walks Out of Parliament's Upper House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lede to CORRECT spelling of ``en masse.'' Picks up 2nd
pvs, ``The opposition...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demanding Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
resign, opposition members today shouted insults and walked out of
Parliament's upper house a day after opposition lawmakers in the
lower house resigned en masse.
   The opposition is protesting alleged corruption in the Gandhi
government and is insisting that the prime minister step down and
call new elections.
   The demand for Gandhi's resignation stemmed from an auditor's
report that criticized the government for irregularities in the
1986 purchase of artillery from the Swedish firm AB Bofors.
   The opposition alleges that members of the government received
kickbacks.
   The governing Congress Party called today's move by 12
opposition parties ``a stunt and gimmick'' before the general
elections, which Gandhi must call by January.
   The 12 parties control 106 seats in the 544-member lower house,
or Lok Sabha. Gandhi's party has a solid majority in the house and
the opposition departure is not likely to affect parliament's
functioning.
   Opposition leaders said they were giving up their seats hoping
the purchase would become a major issue in the elections.
   The 90 opposition members in the upper house, or Rajya Sabha,
were asked to keep their seats to try to obstruct legislation
passed by the lower house. Formal approval from the Rajya Sabha is
needed before a law can be enacted.
   Before storming out of the 245-member house, opposition members
chanted: ``We want resignation'' as Gandhi watched impassively.
   As the din continued, house Chairman Shankar Dayal Sharma said
``the house cannot be held ransom.'' One opposition member replied:
``The prime minister is holding the country to ransom.''
   Both houses of Parliament have stalled since the Comptroller and
Auditor General's report on the gun deal was put before Parliament
on July 18.
   The $1.4 billion deal to purchase howitzers has been a major
scandal for Gandhi's government because of allegations that Bofors
bribed government officials and senior Congress Party members to
secure the contract.
   Newspapers and opposition politicians say bribes up to at least
$50 million were paid. The allegations have never been proved and a
parliamentary committee investigation the deal last year concluded
there was no evidence of kickbacks.
   The auditor general's report said the arms purchase was flawed
on technical considerations and cost assessment.
   Opposition leaders have previously demanded Gandhi's resignation
on the issue, but the 44-year-old prime minister has repeatedly
said he was not involved in any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
