<FIRST>r a PM-RapeRecant     07-25 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape Recant,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects State's Move to Block New Trial for Gary Dotson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Dotson, who was freed from prison after a
woman recanted testimony that he raped her, isn't barred by the
statute of limitations from getting a new trial, a judge ruled.
   The ruling Monday by Circuit Judge Thomas R. Fitzgerald clears
the way for a hearing on Dotson's request for a new trial to clear
his name in the widely publicized case.
   The judge rejected a state prosecutor's assertion that the
two-year statute of limitations barring tardy prosecution applies
to Dotson's decade-old case. He also rejected the state's argument
that newly developed genetic tests Dotson wants to use in his
defense are irrelevant.
   ``We're going to prove once and for all that he didn't do it,''
Dotson's sister, Laura, said after the hearing. Dotson, 32, who is
in an alcoholism treatment center as a condition of parole, didn't
attend.
   Dotson was sentenced in 1979 to 25 to 50 years in prison for the
1977 rape of Cathleen Crowell, who later married and became
Cathleen Webb. In 1985, Ms. Webb recanted her testimony, saying she
made up the attack because she feared she had become pregnant by
her boyfriend.
   Gov. James R. Thompson granted Dotson clemency, saying his
punishment had been sufficient. But the governor said he did not
believe Ms. Webb's about-face, and has refused to pardon Dotson.
   The judge set a hearing for Aug. 14, at which he is expected to
schedule a hearing to determine if there should be a new trial.
   The defense hopes to use new genetic tests to show that semen
found on Ms. Webb's underwear wasn't Dotson's.
   At Monday's hearing, State's Attorney Gayle Shines argued that
the defense failed to prove the test results have ``a substantial
probability'' of changing the outcome of the original trial, a
requirement for granting a new trial.
   The absense of Dotson's semen does not prove he didn't rape the
woman, she argued.
</TEXT>
