<FIRST>r w PM-SecretService     07-25 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Secret Service,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third White House Guard Placed on Administrative Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third White House guard has been placed on
administrative leave as the Secret Service investigates late-night
tours of the executive mansion given a lobbyist and his friends, a
spokesman said today.
   Secret Service spokesman Rich Adams said the uniformed guard,
whom he refused to identify, worked some of the same shifts as
Officer Reginald deGueldre and another uniformed guard placed on
administrative leave earlier.
   DeGueldre has acknowledged he admitted lobbyist Craig Spence and
his party to the White House for a private after-hours tour of the
West Wing in July 1988. The guard also said he accepted an $8,000
gold Rolex watch from Spence and took several pieces of china from
the White House, according to published reports and court documents.
   DeGueldre has denied doing anything illegal.
   The Washington Times has reported that Spence was a customer of
a homosexual prostitution ring under investigation by U.S. Attorney
Jay Stephens for possible credit card fraud. The Secret Service,
which has jurisdiction over credit card crimes, also is working on
that case.
   The service is also conducting its own internal investigation
into whether uniformed guards violated procedures in admitting
people to the White House, or committed any crimes, such as theft,
Adams said.
</TEXT>
