<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     07-25 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Strike In Abkhazian Capital; Death Toll Rises to 21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike today idled much of the Black Sea
capital in the Abkhazian enclave of Soviet Georgia, and the death
toll from ethnic unrest in the republic rose.
   The strike in Sukhumi came a day after an estimated 18,000
people in Tbilisi, the Georgian capital, demonstrated against the
killing of Georgians by Abkhazians. A Georgian activist said other
strikes have shut down 50 factories in the republic.
   The official Tass news agency reported that all public transit
was halted and half the commercial enterprises were shut down in
Sukhumi, a resort city 880 miles south of Moscow.
   Twenty-one people have died in the violence in Abkhazia and
Georgia since the groups began fighting July 15, Tass quoted
Interior Ministry officials as saying. The death toll stood at 19
on Monday, and the circumstances of the additional fatalities were
not clear.
   Soviet media reports have not specified the nationalities of
each victim.
   Two people were arrested Monday in the Ochamchir section of
Abkhazia on suspicion of having killed a police officer and a cadet
Saturday, the report said.
   Roving bands of armed Georgians and Abkhazians have staged more
than 50 attacks on police and other government installations, in
many cases seizing weapons, according to official reports.
   Authorities have arrested 34 people for allegedly taking part in
the unrest and 221 for violating a region-wide curfew, and they
have seized about 5,000 weapons, Tass reported.
   Speakers at the rally in Tbilisi on Monday demanded independence
for Georgia, one of 15 Soviet republics.
   In Tbilisi today, 30 students were staging a sit-in and three
had started a hunger strike in favor of Georgian secession.
   Zviad Gamsakhurdia, a leader of the Georgian National
Independence Party, said about 50 factories in Georgia were taking
part in a strike and that mass meetings would be held every evening
until protesters' demands were resolved.
   Abkhazians and Georgians blame each other for the ethnic unrest.
Abkhazians, who are a minority in their own region, want greater
economic independence and cultural rights, while Georgians want the
fertile enclave, with its myriad seaside resorts, retained as part
of their Caucasus republic.
   The violence this month broke out after the state university in
Sukhumi set up a new branch that was to teach courses exclusively
in Georgian.
   At least 134 people have died in ethnic unrest during the past
month in the southern Soviet republics of Georgia, Azerbaijan,
Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Tadzhikistan.
   In Novy Uzen in Kazakhstan, where ethnic Kazakhs clashed with
settlers from the Caucasus in mid-June, a curfew was lifted Monday
after more than a month, Tass reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
