<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     07-25 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamils Vow to Set Up Separate State, Indian Embassy Families Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Tamil groups today declared they
will try to establish a separate state in northeastern Sri Lanka.
   The announcement was a rebuff of President Ranasinghe Premadasa,
who on Monday sent three Cabinet ministers to urge the
Tamil-controlled provincial council in Trincomalee to support his
efforts to get Indian troops to leave Sri Lanka.
   At a news conference in the city 150 miles northeast of Colombo,
the groups said they founded a Tamil National Council and will seek
a ``Tamil homeland that shall be fully responsible for the
Tamil-speaking people.''
   India has said its troops, who began arriving July 30, 1987,
cannot leave until they complete their mission of disarming other
Tamil groups and the provincial council in Trincomalee is allowed
to exercise more local autonomy.
   Also today, about 40 wives and children of Indian diplomats left
Sri Lanka to avoid any trouble that might arise this weekend, the
deadline set by Premadasa for the departure of Indian troops.
   About 40 other relatives of Indian diplomats and security
staffers at the high commission, returned to India on Sunday,
according to a spokesman for the high commission, or embassy.
   A shadowy group called the Workers Action Front, believed to
have links with Sinhalese extremists, called for a three-day
protest against the Indian presence starting Wednesday.
   Sinhalese radicals accuse the government of making too many
concessios to Tamil separatists and not doing enough to get the
Indian troops to leave.
   Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Tamils, who make up 18 percent, say the Sinhalese discriminate
against them in jobs, education and use of the Sinhala language.
   Military sources today reported 10 more killings of Sinhalese in
the past two days in Colombo and the Sinhalese heartland of
southern and central Sri Lanka. Ultranationalist Sinhalese from the
People's Liberation Front were blamed for seven of the deaths, and
the three others were front guerrillas killed by security forces.
</TEXT>
