<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia 2ndLd-Writethru   07-25 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0523,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Break Off Over Role of Khmer Rouge in Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with meeting breaking up in disarray.
Pickup 11th pvs, `Sihanouk has...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   LA CELLE-SAINT-CLOUD, France (AP) _ Cambodia's Hanoi-backed
government and three guerrilla factions broke off talks today
without even an agreement on who would take part in an
international peace conference set to begin Sunday.
   ``I'm totally pessimistic,'' said Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
representing one of three rebel groups meeting with Prime Minister
Hun Sen in the talks in a chateau in this suburb southwest of Paris.
   Sihanouk insisted that Cambodia be represented at the conference
opening Sunday by all four factions: his own, another non-communist
group, the communist Khmer Rouge and Prime Minister Hun Sen's
government.
   However, Hun Sen said there should be just two Cambodian
representatives _ Sihanouk and himself.
   A sticking point throughout complicated negotiations has been
the role of the Khmer Rouge in the talks and later in the formation
of a proposed transitional government following the withdrawal of
Vietnamese troops from Cambodia.
   Today's meeting was intended to be a search for common ground
among the Cambodian groups to prepare for the international
conference.
   But Hun Sen said the discussions were at an impasse, and blamed
the presence of the Khmer Rouge, who were represented today by
Khieu Samphan.
   ``It's like a car that reaches the edge of an abyss and cannot
continue its journey,'' Hun Sen said.
   While there were no more talks planned among the leaders, Hun
Sen said he hoped that lower-level contacts would continue, and
that the international peace conference could open Sunday as
planned.
   At his news conference, Hun Sen announced that the Vietnamese
pullout would be complete by Sept. 27.
   ``The final total withdrawal will take place from Sept. 21 to 26
by way of land, river and sea routes,'' he said.
   Previously, Vietnam has promised to have its troops out by Sept.
30.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, to end a three-year
reign of terror by the Khmer Rouge in which hundreds of thousands
of Cambodians were killed.
   There are fears the Khmer Rouge could trigger renewed civil war
if they are given a share of power in an interim government, as
Sihanouk demands.
   Sihanouk has the backing of many Western nations, including the
United States, but there has been increasing international support
for reaching a settlement that does not include the Khmer Rouge.
   U.S. State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Monday
that preventing a return to power of the Khmer Rouge must be a key
element in any settlement.
   In Thailand, Western analysts and Thai military officers said
fighting along the Thai-Cambodian border, where many refugee camps
are located, intensified in recent days.
   The sources said 26 wounded soldiers had been brought to the
International Red Cross hospital at Kap Choeng, compared to an
average number of wounded of a dozen per month.
   Last week, shelling believed to have been conducted by
pro-Vietnamese troops forced the evacuation of nearly 40,000
refugees from a Khmer Rouge border refugee camp known as Site 8.
Most have since returned the sprawling encampment.
</TEXT>
