<FIRST>r i PM-Angola-Plane     07-25 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola-Plane,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Rebels Downed Military Transport Plane, Killing 42</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government news agency ANGOP claimed
today that rebels shot down a military transport plane with 48
aboard, killing 42.
   Spokesman for the rebels in Washington and the U.S. State
Department said they had heard no word of the reported Sunday
attack, and the claim could not be independently verified.
   The plane, a Soviet-built, twin-engine Antonov 26, was carrying
a delegation of regional officials from Luena to Cazombo in eastern
Moxico province Sunday when it was hit in the left engine by a
missile, a military official said.
   The plane crashed about 25 miles west of Cazombo, the official
said.
   An unidentified military source, quoted by the Portuguese news
agency Lusa, said the downing of the plane ``is more than a
cease-fire violation. ... Angola cannot tolerate (the rebels)
continuing to act with impunity.''
   In Washington, spokesmen for State Department and the
U.S.-supported rebels of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola said they had heard no word of the reported
attack.
   Reports of the attack and a spate of other cease-fire violations
come six days before peace talks are to begin in Zaire between the
Marxist government and the rebels.
   The rebels on Sunday attacked and occupied the towns of
Quimbele, and Cuimba in northern Uige province close to the Zairean
border, the Luanda official said.
   Rebel forces on Monday ambushed vehicles in Lunda South
province, killing 16 people, and fired mortars over Kuito, the
provincial capital of Bie, killing two or three people, he added.
   The government delegation in the plane was apparently on its way
to Cazombo as part of a recent national program to explain to
provincial populations the terms of an agreement reached with UNITA
on June 22, the official said.
   Both government forces and UNITA rebels have accused each other
of violating the cease-fire that began June 24 but lasted only one
week.
   The rebels have been fighting Cuban-backed government troops
since shortly after Angola gained independence from Portugal in
1975.
</TEXT>
