<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru a0505 07-25 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0505,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikes Ease, Supreme Soviet to Appeal to Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with new walkouts in Estonia,
details of today's debate in legislature, Vorkuta workers still off jobs;
pickup graf 14 pvs `Tass said...' ^By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikes that swept across Soviet coal fields for
two weeks dwindled today to scattered stoppages, but new walkouts
broke out in Estonia while the country's legislature debated how to
deter future strikes.
   In the Donetsk coal basin, the country's largest, local
officials said most of the Ukranian region's 300,000 strikers
returned to work after they heard the results of their strike
committee's meeting with Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov.
   Ryzhkov sat down Monday with the miners and worked out a
``concrete program of actions for the entire country's coal
industry,'' said Pravda, the Communist Party newspaper.
   In Estonia, workers at ship-building factories and several other
plants struck today to protest recent measures that favor the
native Estonian population of the restive Baltic republic, the
official Soviet news agency Tass said.
   A republic-wide strike committee of non-Estonian workers called
the strike Monday, Tass said. It demanded cancellation of a recent
law promoting the Estonian language and withdrawal of a proposal to
allow only longtime residents to run for local office.
   Lawmakers of the Supreme Soviet, the national legislature, today
debated a statement promising workers the legislature would ``act
decisively and effectively to do everything necessary for the
strengthening of social stability,'' the government newspaper
Izvestia reported.
   Government concessions to strikers have included promises of pay
raises, increased benefits and more economic independence for
mines, as well as shipments of scarce food and clothing.
   Viktor G. Kucherenko head of the legislature's Planning and
Budget Commission, said during a break in the legislative session
on Monday that strike settlements would cost up to $8.6 billion.
   In Voroshilovgrad, which is in the Donetsk basin 550 miles south
of Moscow, about 26,800 workers at 47 out of the region's 93 mines
remained on strike, Tass said.
   The Donetsk strikers were among the last holdouts during the
nationwide coal strike that started July 11 in western Siberia and
spread from the Arctic to Central Asia.
   Last week, the more than 100,000 striking Siberian miners
returned to work after the government promised to meet virtually
all their demands.
   President Mikhail Gorbachev has issued repeated appeals to the
miners, sympathizing with their plight and blaming official trade
union and mining officials for precipitating the strikes by
neglecting miners' needs.
   But he has warned that the strikes could jeopardize his economic
reforms.
   In Vorkuta in the Arctic, the city strike committee ended the
walkout Monday after ``listening with great attention,'' to
Gorbachev's appeals, Tass reported. But strikers warned they would
walk out again if the government did not keep its promises, the
news agency said.
   However, Valery Serdyuk, the city's Communist Party chief, said
none of Vorkuta's mines was working regularly yet. Most miners were
waiting for formal approval by the Soviet Council of Ministers of
their demands, he said in a telephone interview.
   Tass said the strikes in the Donetsk region alone cut coal
production by 1.2 million tons and in the western Siberian Kuznetsk
Coal Basin by at least 1 million tons, according to official
reports.
   Poor transportation is also hurting Donetsk coal supplies, Tass
said, with piles of unshipped coal lying around and often catching
on fire.
   Tass said the strike had not led to any accidents in Donetsk
mines, but 40 percent of the mines' walls badly needed maintenance.
   Gorbachev told the Supreme Soviet on Monday the strikes were the
biggest test so far of his 4-year-old economic reforms and called
for a shakeup of local governing councils, which are frequently
blamed for blocking progress.
   Last week, he appealed for a ``renewal'' of Communist Party
ranks from top to bottom, and his suggestion that local governing
bodies also be transformed could mean sweeping leadership changes.
   Local elections scheduled in the spring throughout the Soviet
Union involve multiple candidates and for the first time offer
serious challenges to entrenched officials.
   Some members of the Supreme Soviet said Monday the elections
should be held earlier. Gorbachev said each of the Soviet Union's
15 republics should decide when and how to hold the elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
