<FIRST>r a PM-ChemicalDerailment     07-25 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Derailment,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Still Out of Homes Because of Tank-Car Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF HOLYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREELAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people remained out of their
homes today while officials prepared to extinguish a burning
railroad chemical tank car that was among 14 cars that derailed
Saturday.
   The fire dwindled enough Monday to allow officials to cut the
original evacuation zone around the derailed freight train by more
than two-thirds, from 15 square miles to 4 square miles.
   Chemicals in the car form hydrochloric acid when burned, but the
acid wasn't endangering people, officials said. The evacuation was
a precautionary move.
   ``A very lazy fire'' continued today in one car, said R. Lindsay
Leckie, spokesman for CSX Transportation Inc., owner of the cars.
Firefighters planned to use an air line to accelerate the blaze and
burn off remaining gases and moisture, then smother it with sodium
bicarbonate powder, he said.
   He said the remaining cars would be removed once the fire is out.
   Meanwhile, it was revealed that the brakeman of the wrecked
train checked himself into a local hospital's substance abuse
program after the derailment.
   The brakeman, whose identity was withheld, entered the hospital
a few hours after giving federally required blood and urine
samples, William Loftus, executive director of the Federal Railroad
Administration, revealed Monday.
   But Loftus emphasized that human error had been ruled out as a
cause of the derailment and the brakeman's actions did nothing to
change that. The precise cause hasn't been determined.
   Loftus refused to divulge the man's name, the hospital he
entered, or the substance he's believed to have used.
   ``The guy's not going to turn himself in if he's clean,'' Loftus
said.
   The evacuated families won't be allowed to go home until the
fire is out and workers have cleaned up the derailed cars, two of
which contain chemicals, said Leckie.
   No accurate count was available of the number of people
evacuated. Unofficial figures ranged from 400 to 2,000, but Leckie
and Tittabawassee Township officials refused to make any estimate.
</TEXT>
