<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1223EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-TV     07-25 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-TV,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Documentary Uses Apparently Pirated U.S. TV Footage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dramatic scene of a lone man stopping a
column of tanks was shown on national TV Tuesday for the first time
as China broadcast the second part of a government documentary on
the crushed pro-democracy movement.
   The Cable News Network's Beijing bureau said it believes China
pirated the sequence from CNN or ABC.
   Terry Frieden, CNN's acting news manager in Beijing, said his
cameraman believed the tank man sequence was taken from CNN or ABC
News footage because of the angle from which it was shot.
   The man who briefly stopped the tanks during the army's attack
on demonstrating students last month eventually was pulled from the
street by friends. The Hong Kong press later identified him as a
19-year-old student, Wang Weilin, and said he was arrested.
   The Chinese documentary, ``A Test of Blood and Fire,'' did not
mention his fate but said he was not shot or crushed by the tanks
at the scene because the soldiers ``showed restraint.''
   John Liu, cameraman for CBS News, said he recognized footage
from CBS and ABC in other parts of the four-part documentary, which
China Central Television began showing Monday. ABC's bureau could
not be reached immediately for comment.
   It was not the first time Chinese TV used foreign footage
apparently intercepted from satellite transmissions. Shortly after
the June 3-4 army crackdown, Chinese TV showed ABC footage of a
Chinese man claiming that 20,000 people were killed, and urged the
public to turn the man in. Two women reported on him the next day,
and he was tried and sentenced to 10 years in prison.
   Tuesday night's half-hour segment of the documentary showed the
period after martial law went into effect May 20 through the bloody
weekend of street fighting.
   Both it and Monday's first part have shown some events out of
sequence, apparently to strengthen the government line that
anti-Communist intellectuals were behind the student protests.
   At important junctures in the second segment, the sound was
turned down or off. The documentary showed students talking to or
shouting at soldiers, but it was impossible to hear what they were
saying.
   And in the brief segment on the military crackdown of June 3-4,
the silent video showed students throwing rocks and bricks at army
vehicles, but the sound of gunfire was missing.
   The documentary also included footage shot by police TV crews
and from cameras mounted along main streets.
   Some previously unseen footage was shot from inside the glassed,
locked entrances to subway stations, where police camera crews,
apparently fearing for their lives on the streets, sought shelter.
The pattern of the station glass could be seen across the picture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
