<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     07-25 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>State of Emergency Extended By Six Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament extended Zimbabwe's state of
emergency for six months Tuesday after the government said it
needed wide-ranging powers to deal with threats from South Africa
and border raids by rebels from Mozambique.
   Home Affairs Minister Moven Mahachi cited sabotage and
infiltration by agents of white-run South Africa as a continuing
threat to national security.
   He said the government expected ``hostile activities'' by South
Africa against its black-governed neighbors to increase after
independence elections in Namibia in November scheduled to end
South African control over the southwest African territory.
   In the past, South Africa has mounted several attacks in
Zimbabwe against facilities of the African National Congress, the
main guerrilla organization fighting the government in Pretoria.
   ``That regime (in South Africa) always blames us whenever there
is an uprising in their country,'' Mahachi told legislators.
   Since the last renewal of the emergency in January, there was a
``marked increase'' in cross-border attacks by rebels in
neighboring Mozambique, he said, as well as what he described as
``counterrevolutionary and anti-social activities'' in Zimbabwe
itself.
   About 80 Zimbabweans were slain by Mozambique National
Resistance rebels who were also blamed for 78 abductions, 14
clashes against troops and 72 armed robberies, Mahachi said.
   Zimbabwe has been under a state of emergency since 1965, when it
was introduced by the government of former Rhodesian prime minister
Ian Smith to crack down on black nationalists.
   The emergency, which has been renewed by parliament every six
months since independence in 1980, allows for detention without
trial.
   On Tuesday, one outspoken legislator was prevented on procedural
grounds from listing 50 alleged abuses of the state of emergency
since 1982.
</TEXT>
