<DOCNO> AP890725-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Relations     07-25 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Relations,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criticized By the West, China Stresses Third World Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Foreign Minister Qian Qichen arrives in
Africa on Wednesday, there will be three high-level Chinese envoys
on a continent that has gotten relatively little attention from
China in the past decade.
   Criticized by the West for its crackdown on student
pro-democracy protesters, China has rediscovered its Third World
identity, temporarily cast aside in the 1980s while the leadership
pursued modernization and riches.
   Qian's trip, his longest journey abroad in 15 months as foreign
minister, will take in six countries and last 18 days. At the same
time, Assistant Minister Yang Fuchang is visiting five west African
countries, also for 18 days, and the deputy head of the Communist
Party's international liaison department is visiting the Congo.
   The nations of Sao Tome and Principe and Ethiopia were among the
first to send government or ruling party delegations to China after
its June 3-4 army attack on student protesters. A trade delegation
from Ghana is in Beijing this week.
   ``China and African countries always show each other sympathy,
understanding and support whether in their common struggle or in
difficult times,'' Premier Li Peng said in a message to the
Organization of African Unity summit meeting in Ethiopia.
   ``The profound friendship and close cooperation existing between
China and Africa can stand the test of storms,'' he said.
   The entire Third World is proving to be a haven of calm for
Chinese foreign relations.
   India's foreign secretary was the first senior foreign envoy to
visit China after the army crackdown. Pakistan, Bolivia and
Malaysia have sent delegations.
   Several Soviet and East European groups also have come, and Vice
Premier Tian Jiyun went to Moscow last week for regular economic
and trade talks in the first trip abroad by any high-level Chinese
leader since the crackdown began.
   But even Soviet parliamentarians registered their opinion about
the crackdown, urging China to show reason and wisdom. Most Third
World countries _ some with their own histories of repressing
dissent _ have been non-judgmental.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency quoted the foreign minister
of Sao Tome and Principe, Carlos Dias da Graca, as expressing
``understanding and support for the measures taken by the Chinese
government'' when he visited in June. China said it was giving the
African nation an interest-free loan, although it did not specify
the amount.
   Africa has been the main recipient of what relatively little
foreign aid China has given. In the first three decades of
communist rule, China sent 150,000 technicians to Africa to help
build more than 500 projects.
   The biggest, a 1,160-mile railroad from the capital of
landlocked Zambia through Tanzania to the coast, cost the lives of
145 Chinese workers before it was completed in 1975.
   China financed a $100 million fertilizer plant in Tanzania, a
gymnasium in Kenya and a parliament hall in Cape Verde. Highways in
Madagascar and a sugar refinery in Togo were built with Chinese
funds.
   In return, China gained a sense of solidarity with other
developing nations at a time when it was isolated from most East
and West bloc countries and feared attack from both.
   China once again feels isolated and beleagued, as illustrated by
a recent commentary in Economic Reference News. U.S. criticism, it
said, ``is not an isolated incident but a component part of an
international political adverse current initiated by some U.S.
Influences in recent years.''
   The commentary said China is the victim of Western plotting to
lure it into ``conducting `reforms' to weaken and even get rid of
the communist leadership.''
   China's new Third World emphasis can be seen not only in its
diplomatic exchanges, but in a noticeable increase of Third World
news on Xinhua and state TV. The evening news carried a four-part
series last week on the Tanzania-Zambia railway, and has begun
running stories on industrial production in African countries.
   The Third World, however, cannot offer the soft loans and
technology China has been counting on to fulfill its goal of
doubling gross national product by the year 2000.
   An upbeat Xinhua news analysis about U.S.-Polish relations may
indicate what Chinese hope will happen to their strained ties with
the West.
   Without mentioning the parallel to China's situation, it noted
the United States and other Western countries imposed economic
sanctions against Poland after it declared martial law in 1981 and
outlawed the independent Solidarity trade union.
   ``The situation began to change,'' it noted, ``after the Polish
authorities' announcement to end martial law in 1983.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
