<FIRST>r a AM-DC10-Crash-Attendants     07-25 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC10-Crash-Attendants,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Credit Courage of Stewardesses Who Survived Fiery Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors of the fiery DC-10 crash
credited flight attendants for maintaining calm and helping
passengers escape from the wreckage.
   Helen Hayes of Denver sat in row nine at the front of the middle
cabin section and said a flight attendant whose name she didn't
know helped prevent panic.
   ``Her voice was very soothing,'' Ms. Hayes said from her
hospital room. ``She prevented the passengers from going into
complete hysteria.''
   Seven of the eight flight attendants on the plane survived the
tumbling crash of the United Airlines jet at the Sioux Gateway
Airport on Wednesday. The three crew members in the cockpit also
survived.
   In all, of the 296 people on the plane, 111 were killed.
   United spokesman Robb Doughty said flight attendants have
landing positions in jump seats which are bolted to bulkheads in
reinforced sections of the cabin. That's deliberate, he said, so
they can aid passengers in getting out of the airplane.
   ``They sit there so they can manage the evacuation through the
doors,'' he said.
   Ms. Hayes said she was sitting near one of the flight attendants
while the plane flew toward Sioux City for an emergency landing and
could see the fear on her face, although she said passengers
further away probably couldn't. She said the flight attendants
issued instructions on what passengers should do right up to the
time the crippled jumbo jet hit the ground.
   ``It must have been very difficult for them to do that,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
