<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees     07-25 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Says Many Vietnamese Injured in Camp Clashes with Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Vietnamese refugees were hurt in weekend
clashes with police at a crowded Hong Kong detention center, the
U.N. refugee agency said Tuesday.
   Only four Vietnamese requested treatment for injuries after the
confrontations, including three who said they were hurt
accidentally, police said.
   One refugee died in unclear circumstances, but not of natural
causes, according to police and Robert van Leeuwen, the U.N. high
commissioner for refugees in Hong Kong.
   The incidents occurred at Sek Kong detention center, a former
military airfield where more than 7,000 Vietnamese asylum-seekers
live in tents. They are among 50,000 Vietnamese who escaped their
communist homeland by boat to seek temporary sanctuary in the
British colony of Hong Kong.
   Police say about 200 Vietnamese hurled stones at their guards
Sunday night when the guards started investigating holes in the
barbed wire fence around the camp. Order was restored but violence
flared again several hours later when police carried out a search
for makeshift weapons.
   The clashes came during reported growing tension in the colony's
detention centers amid indications that Britain and Vietnam are
near agreement on the forced repatriation of those who cannot prove
they fled political persecution.
   ``Preliminary indications are that a considerable number of
people have been injured in the incident,'' van Leeuwen said on the
state radio.
   In the case of the dead refugee, initial findings of an autopsy
showed he did not die of natural causes, according to a police
statement. It said police are investigating the case.
   Police Assistant Commissioner Richard Smallshaw said only four
Vietnamese men requested treatment after the disturbance, including
one requiring hospitalization.
   The other three ``claim they were accidental injuries and were
not the result of police action,'' he told the radio. ``They're
very minor indeed.''
   Van Leeuwen was quoted in the English-language South China
Morning Post as saying women and children apparently were among the
injured. Smallshaw denied that.
   The Vietnamese at Sek Kong are among boat people who must prove
they are political refugees and not economic migrants. Hong Kong
and other Southeast Asian authorities say they cannot cope with an
influx of tens of thousands of Vietnamese who brave storms and
pirates in flimsy boats to escape their homeland in hopes of
winning asylum in countries such as the United States.
</TEXT>
