<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Saudi-Iran Bjt   07-25 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saudi-Iran, Bjt,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mecca Bombings Underline Struggle for Islamic Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bombings in Mecca during the annual
pilgrimage to the holiest city of Islam focused attention once
again on an ideological struggle for leadership of the world's 1
billion Moslems.
   The bombings were a major setback for efforts to end the rift
between Saudi Arabia and Iran, currently the main protagonists in
the centuries-old schism between the Sunnis and Shiites, Islam's
leading sects.
   Two bombs exploded in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, on July 10 during the
hajj, or pilgrimage, to the shrines of Islam, killing a Pakistani
pilgrim and wounding 16 people. A third explosion July 17 caused no
casualties.
   Official Saudi statements did not fix blame, but the bombings
were widely believed to be the work of Iranians.
   Tehran's fundamentalist Shiite regime accused the Saudis of
planting the bombs in an attempt to discredit Iran, and renewed
their demand that custodianship of the holy sites be taken away
from the Saudi royal family.
   Ayatollah Abdolkarim Musavi Ardebili, chief justice of Iran,
declared: ``We want God to give us the strength ... to throw out
the corpse of this tahgut (idolatrous despot) from the House of
God.''
   His statement goes to the heart of the rift between the Sunnis,
who account for 80 percent of Moslems, and the minority Shiites.
The Saudi royal family and most of their 12 million subjects are
Sunnis, and Iran's population of 50 million is overwhelmingly
Shiite.
   Custody of Mecca and Medina is a pillar of the Saudi royal claim
to legitimacy, so Iran's demand has political as well as religious
significance. Two years ago, King Fahd underscored his religious
role by declaring his primary title to be Custodian of the Holy
Places.
   Shiites believe religion and politics cannot be separated and
the hajj must be a forum for political action, such as rallies
against the United States and Israel. That view is anathema to the
Saudis.
   Fahd's hajj and endowments minister, Abdel-Wahab Abdel-Wasei,
accused Iran of seeking ``to fan the flames of sedition in Islamic
ranks'' and said Saudi Arabia was ``determined to resist all
attempts at maneuvers, pressures and provocations.''
   The latest developments appeared to dash hopes in the Persian
Gulf region that the death of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on June 3
signaled the end of Iran's virulent fundamentalism and the
emergence of more moderate policies.
   Conservative Arab states in the area, governed by royal
families, have felt threatened for the past decade by Iran's
efforts to export the revolution that overthrew the late Shah
Mohammad Reza Pahlavi in February 1979.
   Saudi Arabia severed relations with Tehran in April 1988, citing
terrorism and subversion.
   Fahd acted after 402 pilgrims, most of them Iranians, were
killed in clashes with riot police in Mecca on July 31, 1987,
during the hajj. The first two bombings this year occurred on the
second anniversary of the riots, reckoned by the Moslem lunar
calendar.
   Saudi Arabia says the Iranians instigated the riots by defying a
ban on political activity during the pilgrimage. Iran claims the
Saudis massacred its pilgrims.
   The Saudis won Moslem support for limiting pilgrims to 1,000 for
every 1 million of a country's population. The ostensible purpose
was to reduce crowding in the holy cities during major construction
of more facilities, but the clear intent was to curb the Iranians.
   Under the quota system, Iran's usual contingent of about 150,000
pilgrims would be reduced by two-thirds. As a result, Iran
boycotted the hajj in 1988 and this year.
   Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, successor to Khomeini as Iran's
religious leader, accused Saudi Arabia on July 6 of ``blocking the
faithful from performing the hajj, to gratify America and Israel,''
and said Iran ``will not forget these hostilities.''
   Before the hajj bombings, which occurred four days after
Khameini's speech, King Fahd's government had been quietly trying
to promote reconciliation with Iran.
   Arab diplomats said Oman was ``communicating ideas and
conditions'' between Iran and Saudi Arabia and that other Arab
states, notably Kuwait, had made their own efforts.
   According to the diplomats, the Saudis set out three
``irrevocable conditions for coexistence'' with Iran:
noninterference in Saudi internal affairs, a pledge to abandon
political activities during the pilgrimage and acceptance the hajj
quota system.
   Khamenei has said, however: ``We have pledged to God to continue
Imam Khomeini's path ... which is the path of Islam. ... Our main
aim ... is to revive Islam once again and return to Koranic values.
We will not retreat an inch on this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
