<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Rock-Insurance     07-25 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Rock-Insurance,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurance Group Urges Legal Limits on Rock Concert Noise Levels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUCERNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Switzerland's main accident
insurance group called Tuesday for legal limits on noise levels at
rock concerts to protect fans from ear damage.
   In the absence of statutory noise limits, concert organizers
should give away free ear plugs with tickets, the Swiss Accident
Insurance Agency said.
   The proposal that noise levels should not be higher than 100
decibels drew an angry reaction from concert organizers, who said
such measures would prompt rock stars to bypass Switzerland.
   ``It would be the death of rock concerts in Switzerland,'' said
Saemi Hafen of Good News, the country's largest promoter.
   ``It's a typical suggestion from people with nothing better to
do,'' said Hanns Hanneken, editor of the magazine Music Scene.
   The agency said many people suffered ear damage after attending
concerts with noise levels of between 100 and 120 decibels.
   The pain barrier is reached at 125 decibels. Under Swiss law,
workers have to wear earplugs if the noise limit is more than 87
decibels.
</TEXT>
