<FIRST>r a AM-Mirabella     07-25 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mirabella,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Fashion Magazine Settles Down to Hard Work of Making It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new fashion and lifestyle magazine Mirabella
has made its debut, but will this guide for the well-educated woman
be a lasting hit, or will it join the heap of new magazines that
fold in a few years?
   ``It's going very well. I think wonderfully well,'' said Grace
Mirabella, the editor. The first issue in June of 600,000 copies
sold out, but this veteran of the competitive, crowded world of
magazines knows success can be fleeting. ``I'm anxiety-ridden,''
she says.
   The figures for July are that just 70 percent to 75 percent of
the 600,000 copies are expected to sell. But publisher Julie
Lewit-Nirenberg noted that summer is traditionally slow for
magazines and that the first issue sold for $1, compared to the
$2.95 buyers now must fork out.
   She said the number of advertising pages dropped from 123 in
June to 85 in July and 50 in August. But the September issue just
closed for printing with 149 advertising pages.
   Ms. Mirabella says she knows there are pitfalls. ``We have to
keep our eye on the reader we think we have _ where her head is and
how she sees us. ... The reader we have is an intelligent reader,
selective in her view and selective in her eye.''
   Fashion designer Pearl Nipon knows who that reader is. ``I think
it's our customer.'' Mirabella, she says, ``is fabulous. It's so
understandable, it is so today.'' And she intends to continue to
buy advertising in the magazine.
   Patti Cohen, fashion director for Donna Karan, agrees. ``It's
really very exciting. ... I don't think it takes readers from other
magazines. I want to read Mirabella, but I also want to read the
Vogues and the Elles.''
   By targeting a narrowly defined audience of well-educated, older
and affluent women, Mirabella has a chance of surviving in the
crowded fashion magazine market, said Joseph Ostrow, worldwide
media director of Foote, Cone and Belding, an ad agency in New York.
   But a good six months will have to pass before any meaningful
judgment can be passed on the publication, said Nancy Smith, senior
vice president of media services at Young &amp; Rubicam Inc., another
New York ad agency.
   The money and backing of communications magnate Rupert Murdoch
bode well for Mirabella, as does the fact that Ms. Mirabella is the
creative force behind it, Ms. Smith said. ``She is an extremely
talented woman who has demonstrated her strength before.''
   Ms. Mirabella was Vogue's editor-in-chief for 17 years before
she was abruptly dismissed last June by S.I. Newhouse Jr. of Conde
Nast. In November, Murdoch approached her about presiding over a
monthly bearing her name.
   The glossy, oversized publication has some features that can
hardly be considered intelligent reading material. One article in
the June issue describes the favorite lipstick colors of actress
Joan Collins, designer Caroline Herrera and jewelry designer Paloma
Picasso.
   But its tone is more subtle than many other fashion magazines _
both in its fashion coverage and its features. And Ms. Mirabella
and her staff pride themselves on the fact that the monthly is
almost half text.
   ``It's a smart and intelligent magazine for women interested in
style and fashion but like a little more protein in reading
matter,'' Ms. Lewit-Nirenberg said, ``Not just a sugar high.''
</TEXT>
