<FIRST>r a PM-IowaAbortion     07-25 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Abortion,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Group Would Put Abortion Rights in State Constitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iowa Civil Liberties Union says it
is drafting a proposed amendment to Iowa's constitution that would
ensure the right to abortion.
   ``Iowa is a state with a longstanding tradition of respect for
individual rights of privacy,'' ICLU Executive Director Cryss
Farley said in a statement distributed Monday. ``Our constitution
should provide express protection for that concept.''
   Ms. Farley said the ICLU is drafting a proposed amendment ``that
will simply protect the status quo'' in the wake of a U.S. Supreme
Court ruling broadening state powers to restrict abortions.
   ``It is clear that we can no longer rely upon the U.S. Supreme
Court to protect the right of reproductive choice,'' Ms. Farley
said.
   Iowa House Speaker Don Avenson said he doesn't expect the
Legislature to approve abortion restrictions next year.
   The National Organization for Women called Sunday for an
amendment to the United States Constitution guaranteeing women the
right to abortion and birth control. NOW issued its call for a
``Bill of Rights for the 21st Century'' at a convention in
Cincinnati.
   The proposed constitutional amendment in Iowa, which has yet to
be drafted, would require the approval of two successive General
Assemblies before being submitted to a statewide vote.
   ``This will be a moderate proposal aimed at preserving
established privacy rights,'' said ICLU lobbyist Mark Lambert.
</TEXT>
