<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Greece-TV     07-25 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Greece-TV,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Approves First Private TV Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The coalition government said Tuesday it
would grant television licenses for two private networks, breaking
the state's monopoly.
   It was the latest in a series of moves toward pluralism in in a
country where television and radio have been under state control
since their inception.
   Government spokesman Athanassios Kanellopoulos said the licenses
will be given to two publishing consortiums, Tiletypos Corp. and
Antenna-TV, made up of representatives from Greece's diverse and
often partisan press.
   Both stations will transmit locally, not nationally, and the
state will share in about 5 percent of the profits, he added.
   The three state-run TV networks in Greece belong to the Hellenic
Radio and Televison Corp.
   The state monopoly on radio was broken two years ago when the
municipality of Athens set up a station.
   Popular demand and pirate TV stations also led the former
Socialist government to begin allowing in six international
satellite channels, including Cable News Network.
   The center-right New Democracy party, the majority member in the
Conservative-Communist coalition government, had made private TV a
part of its campaign platform for last month's elections.
</TEXT>
