<FIRST>r w AM-CleanWater     07-25 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Water,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors: Congress Needs to Put Money Where Mouth Is</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts by Congress to force communities into
cleanups they can't afford just won't work and are a cheap
substitute for a real environmental policy, a spokesman for the
nation's mayors told senators Tuesday.
   ``You cannot build ... treatment plants with a thousand points
of light,'' John Bullard told a joint session of the Environment
and Public Works subcommittees on environmental protection and on
superfund, ocean and water protection.
   Bullard, mayor of New Bedford, Mass., was representing the
National League of Cities before the subcommittees, which are
considering a variety of clean water legislation.
   Bullard said the federal government must be able to ``walk this
fine line'' between ``punishment and partnership'' if it is to be
serious about environmental issues.
   He said an ``irresistible force'' of public demand for a clean
environment is running up against an ``immovable object'' of scarce
financial resources that threatens ``an impending explosion that
could consume some cities.''
   For example, he said his own city is working under a consent
decree in which it is supposed to spend $560 million on various
clean water projects to meet federal standards.
   The only problem, he said, is that the figure works out to
$5,600 per man, woman and child in the city of 100,000. He said the
city, with a total annual budget of $116 million, is doing good to
handle its $22 million total indebtness and has never built a
project that cost more than $15 million _ that one a dam with help
from the Army Corps of Engineers.
   He pointed out that Congress has authorized $1.2 billion in
federal spending since 1984 on a single section of the Clean Water
Act, yet has actually appropriated only $92.51 million.
   ``It appears to us that the federal government has poorly
managed its own fiscal affairs and cannot seem to put them back in
order,'' he said. ``What is happening now appears to us to be an
attempt to continue business as usual, merely shifting the
financing responsibility to other levels of governmnent. The end
result will be that all our fiscal houses will be in total
disarray.''
   Bullard was among a number of government officials and private
researchers to testify before the two subcommittees. Tuesday's
hearing was not on any one of them, but rather was organized to
enable a variety of public and private groups to present their
general views.
</TEXT>
