<HEAD>Governor Announces Special Session on Abortion Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez, saying the unborn
``deserve our help and protection,'' today called a special
legislative session to address the abortion issue.
   Martinez, who favors more restrictions on abortion, called for
the special session three weeks after the U.S. Supreme Court threw
the issue back to the states in a 5-4 decision on a Missouri case.
   ``The court has given states the opportunity to better balance
the rights of the unborn with those of women, and I believe Florida
should do more to protect unborn children who cannot speak for
themselves,'' Martinez said in a statement.
   ``This is an issue of fundamental rights, and I believe the
unborn deserve our help and our protection.''
   The governor, however, isn't expected to offer specific
legislation for the session, to be held Oct. 10-13.
   The Florida Legislature appears evenly divided on the issue, but
many lawmakers would rather leave the controversial subject alone.
   Senate President Bob Crawford said the abortion issue could
create such bitter feelings among lawmakers that other critical
needs of the state could suffer.
   ``There are many issues that are very important, and we need to
continue working on other issues and not be paralyzed just dealing
with the emotions of this issue,'' Crawford said after the
governor's announcement.
   Earlier this month, Speaker Tom Gustafson named a pro-choice
lawmaker, Elaine Gordon of North Miami, to put together the House's
abortion proposal for a special session
   Ms. Gordon, a Democrat, chairs the House Health Care Committee.
   Current Florida law allows abortons during the first six months
of pregnancy. A woman must have permission from two doctors, based
on health reasons, to acquire an abortion in the last trimester of
pregnancy.
