<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1333EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NewsroomMinorities     07-25 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newsroom Minorities,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>ASNE Head Finds Both Indifference and Commitment at Papers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the American Society of
Newspaper Editors returned to his desk Tuesday both encouraged and
discouraged by his trip to urge executives of two dozen newspapers
to hire more minority people.
   Loren Ghiglione, ASNE president and editor of the Southbridge
(Mass.) News, said he found some papers attached no especial
importance to the question of whether they cover their communities
with a staff composed entirely of white reporters and editors.
   Others, he said, showed a commitment to finding minority
youngsters and bringing them along for years until they are
prepared to join news staffs as fulltime reporters.
   Ghiglione set out July 3 on a Maine-to-California trip during
which he met more than 100 editors and other newspaper executives.
   Before he left, he said feared that the newspaper industry's
commitment to integrating its newsrooms had taken a back seat to
business matters and that the goal was threatened by apathy.
   ASNE surveys have found that 54 percent of newspapers have no
minority news people on their news staffs or at the top. Most of
them are small papers.
   All told, minorities account for 7.5 percent of all newsroom
professionals, the most recent survey found.
   Ghiglione said he found a longterm commitment at some papers. He
cited the Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal, in an area with a significant
Hispanic and Indian population, where editors are determined to
have 40 percent to 45 percent minority staffing by the turn of the
century.
   The Journal not only takes on young minority people as interns,
it keeps in touch with them, takes them back summer after summer,
follows them through college and retains them as interns until they
are prepared to take their place on the paper's staff, Ghiglione
said.
   On the other hand, he said, he sometimes encountered
indifference at other papers.
   ``I guess people were too polite to be angry or hostile,'' he
said, ``but what I sensed at several places was a feeling that,
`While this is a noble cause it is very low priority while we're
trying to get the paper out every day. If a qualified minority
candidate came through the door, we would consider hiring him if we
had an opening but recruitment requires more effort, more time and
more money than we are willing to give.'''
   Ghiglione said he now assigns increased importance to focusing
on junior and senior high school students and encouraging writing
and work on school newspapers.
   He said he intends to follow up his trip with letters and calls
to the owners of groups of newspapers that don't stress minority
hiring.
   ``I'm going to go to the heads of many of the dailies I visited
and ask for their help,'' he said. ``An awful lot of companies have
not put it on their priority list.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0112 </DOCNO>
