<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0562,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinan's Death Sparks Protests; Arab PLO Supporter Claims He
Met Shamir</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 1st graf to UPDATE with Palestinian PLO
supporter saying he met with Shamir. Pickup 2nd graf `In Gaza...'; ADDS
3 grafs of details, background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old Palestinian died today from
wounds suffered in a clash with Israeli soldiers in the occupied
Gaza Strip, and his death reportedly set off tire-burning protests
there.
   Also today, Palestinian lawyer who supports the PLO said he met
recently with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, disputing claims by
the government that Shamir's talks on his peace plan are only with
non-PLO Palestinians.
   The statement by Jamil Tarifi comes amid a growing controversy
over whether Israel is carrying on indirect negotiations with the
PLO, either through its own officials or through the U.S.-PLO
dialogue in Tunis.
   In Gaza, Fawsi Mohammed Elidawil died of injuries suffered in a
clash with soldiers a day earlier in the Egyptian border town of
Rafah.
   The army confirmed his death, which raised to 520 the number of
Palestinians who have died in clashes with Israelis during the
19-month Palestinian uprising. Thirty-eight Israelis have also been
killed.
   As word of the latest death spread today, youths in Rafah set up
roadblocks and burned tires in protest, Arab reporters said. They
said one man was wounded when soldiers opened fire to disperse the
protesters.
   In the West Bank, two Palestinians were shot and wounded in a
clash with soldiers in Ramallah and a third was hit in the face and
chest with 11 rubber-coated metal pellets used by troops to put
down riots, hospital officials said.
   A 36-year-old Palestinian was stabbed by masked youths in the
Balata refugee camp near Nablus as a suspected collaborator with
Israel, Arab reports said. He was reported in serious condition.
   At least 84 Palestinians have been killed as suspected
collaborators by fellow Arabs during the uprising.
   Tarifi told a news conference in Ramallah that he met with
Shamir several days ago, but he did not say exactly when.
   Shamir's spokesmen have issued denials for two days that the
right-wing premier was holding meetings with supporters of the PLO,
following a statement by PLO Chief Yasser Arafat that he approved
talks between his supporters and Israeli officials.
   Israel views the Palestine Liberation Organization as a
terrorist group bent on destroying the Jewish state.
</TEXT>
