<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1324EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Economy     07-25 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reports Orders for Major Goods Up a Modest 0.3 Percent
in June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for big-ticket factory goods rose a
modest 0.3 percent in June, the government said Tuesday in a report
seen as evidence that manufacturing, although sluggish, isn't
crumbling.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable goods _ items
ranging from bicycles to battleships _ advanced to a seasonally
adjusted $124.1 billion last month. That followed a 4.4 percent
decline in May, the sharpest in 10 months.
   ``This is basically in line with the forecast of modest growth
but no recession,'' said economist Michael K. Evans, who heads a
consulting firm in Washington.
   Economist Robert G. Dederick of Northern Trust Co. in Chicago
said the report likely means the Federal Reserve won't be in a rush
to cut interest rates soon.
   ``The report could have triggered action if it was really weak,
but it wasn't. ... It suggests we're continuing to tread water in
manufacturing, but the sector isn't crumbling,'' he said.
   The Fed recently shifted gears after a year-long campaign of
fighting inflation with higher interest rates, allowing two small
declines in short-term rates since early June. Most analysts expect
the central bank to continue nudging rates lower, but slowly and
cautiously.
   Other statistics released Tuesday generally confirmed
economists' views that inflation isn't getting worse and growth is
holding up, although at a lackluster rate.
   Wages, salaries and other benefits paid to American workers rose
4.5 percent in the 12 months ending in June, down just slightly
from the 4.6 percent gain in the 12 months ending in March,
according to the Labor Department's Employment Cost Index.
   In its quarterly report on collective bargaining agreements, the
Labor Department said major contracts signed by labor unions in the
April-June period provided first-year raises of 3.9 percent, up
from 3.2 percent in the first quarter.
   The National Association of Realtors said sales of existing
single-family homes rebounded 5.9 percent in June to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 3.4 million units. It was the first
increase in six months and a sign that falling mortgage rates have
begun to stimulate the depressed housing sector.
   The rebound in durable goods orders was powered by a 15.8
percent jump in military orders to a seasonally adjusted $8.8
billion. The highly volatile category registered drops of 11.4
percent in May and 18.3 percent in April.
   Excluding defense, new orders fell 0.7 percent last month
following a decline of 3.9 percent in May. The June activity was
depressed by softness in auto manufacturing which offset an upturn
at factories producing machinery.
   The closely watched category of non-defense capital goods, a
barometer of business investment plans, rose 0.5 percent in June to
$37.5 billion following a 7.7 percent plunge a month earlier.
   Non-electrical machinery orders rose 3.7 percent to $23.1
billion, reflecting an increase in purchases of steam engines and
turbines.
   Electrical machinery gained 2.8 percent to $19.2 billion
following a 6.1 percent drop in May.
   Transportation equipment declined 3.5 percent to $32.3 billion
following a 9.7 percent drop a month earlier. Most of the decline
came in shipbuilding and in motor vehicles and parts.
   Primary metals, including steel, were off 5 percent to $12
billion following a 1.8 percent decline in May. Evans said much of
the decline represents lower steel prices, rather than less volume.
   For the first six months of the year, new orders for durable
goods totaled $755.1 billion, 8.2 percent higher than the first
half of 1988. The figure does not take inflation into account.
   Shipments of durable goods fell 1.1 percent to $121.6 billion in
June, following a 0.3 percent decline in May.
</TEXT>
