<FIRST>r i AM-Iran     07-25 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Media Calls For Big Voter Turnout In Presidential Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian newspapers called Tuesday for a
big voter turnout in presidential elections Friday to confound the
Islamic republic's critics and ``open a new chapter'' after
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's death.
   All predicted a landslide victory for the only real candidate,
Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, who has emerged as Iran's
strongman since the June 3 death of Khomeini, the revolutionary
patriarch who founded the fundamentalist state.
   Rafsanjani's only challenger is Abass Sheibani, 58, a
French-trained physician and parliament deputy with no national
political base.
   ``It can be said beyond any doubt that Mr. Rafsanjani is the
best choice for the post,'' said the Tehran Times, an
Engligh-language daily that supports Rafsanjani.
   ``He has the qualifications ... and his realistic approach to
domestic, regional and international issues is known to all.''
   The radical Abrar daily said massive participation by Iran's
estimated 25 million voters is vital because ``world oppressors
have been trying to portray the Islamic republic as unstable and
unable to last'' since Khomeini died.
   Jomhuri Islami, another radical daily, stressed that ``each vote
is a bullet fired at the heart of Iran's enemies.''
   The election will be held alongside a national referendum on
proposed constitutional reforms to give the presidency greater
powers and eliminate competing power centers that have paralyzed
government for years. Reforms propose scrapping the post of prime
minister and making the president head of government.
   The Tehran Times said June 28 ``will go down in the history of
the Islamic republic as one of the most important events ...
because the nation will have a president with the power needed to
tackle the issues.''
   Newspapers were so confident Rafsanjani will win that they have
been speculating on the formation of his Cabinet when he succeeds
two-term incumbent Ayatollah Ali Khamanei.
   Khamenei was elected to succeed Khomeini as Iran's supreme
religious leader last month and was to step down when his second
term expired Oct. 5. But elections were advanced three weeks to
speed up the transition of power after Khomeini died.
   Diplomatic sources and Western analysts say Rafsanjani, 55, is
expected to name a team dominated by technocrats and give priority
to reviving Iran's economy after a decade of mismanagement, poor
planning and an eight-year war with Iraq.
   Rafsanjani, leader of Tehran's pragmatist faction, also is
expected to neutralize his radical rivals by giving them positions,
although probably with reduced powers.
   The Tehran Times said Rafsanjani personally will take charge of
the Planning and Budget Ministry in his drive to revitalize a
materials-starved industry operating at only 30 percent to 40
percent of capacity and map out a much-delayed long-term economic
strategy to reduce runaway inflation and unemployment in the
postwar era.
</TEXT>
