<FIRST>r w PM-Bennett-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0551 07-25 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0551,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Not Ready to Call For Tax Increase in Drug War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Bush opposing raising taxes, bonds; picks
up at pvs 4th graf, Most of</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's top lieutenant in the war on
drugs agrees that ``crack is worse than taxes,'' but he isn't ready
to call for a tax increase to pay for the fight. Bush's spokesman
said today the president doesn't support such a boost, either.
   ``Maybe down the road we will,'' William J. Bennett said after a
closed meeting with leaders of the U.S. Conference of Mayors on
Monday. ``But I think there are other choices.''
   Bush pledged during his election campaign that he would not
support new taxes, and press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said today
that the president remains ``opposed to raising taxes for any
purpose.''
   Fitzwater said there were ``practical problems'' with proposals,
suggested by some in Congress, to sell federal bonds to pay for the
drug war.
   He said the president believed that if more money is needed, it
should be obtained through ``the more traditional route'' of a
congressional appropriation or a shift of money from other programs.
   But some mayors who met Monday with Bennett said citizens will
support new taxes if the money is used to fight drugs.
   ``Most of us have had to raise taxes in our local communities
already to deal with the drug problem, so we're not afraid to
recommend that,'' said Houston Mayor Kathryn Whitmire, president of
the conference.
   ``The people are ready to accept an increase in taxes if they
knew that the taxes were going solely to interdict drugs and not
for some social program which they may or may not agree with,''
said New York City Mayor Ed Koch.
   Koch said the slogan ``crack is worse than taxes means that
people will pay to have this monster lifted from their shoulders so
their kids can be protected.''
   The mayors met with Bennett, director of the Office of National
Drug Control Policy, to push a 16-point plan they want included in
the strategy he is to produce by Sept. 5. One point calls for
increased funding for state and local programs.
   Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn called for $3 billion in federal
funds to be distributed to states and cities to fight the drug war,
and he complained that Bennett remained vague on the money issue.
   ``This is a lot of baloney, what's going on here,'' Flynn said
in an interview. ``Unless they're willing to put real dollars on
the line ... they're not sincere in the war on drugs.''
   Flynn said he asked Bennett whether he would support the $3
billion appropriation and was told, ```It depends on what Congress
does.'''
   Bennett agreed that some funds should come from the federal
government, but he would not give a figure.
   ``Mayors always ask for more,'' he said.
   Two California Republicans, Sen. Pete Wilson and Rep. Jerry
Lewis, introduced legislation last week to sell $4 billion worth of
savings bonds to raise money to fight the drug war. Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla., said Monday he was offering a similar bill.
   Despite the differences, Whitmire described the meeting as ``a
very good dialogue.'' Even Washington Mayor Marion Barry, whose
relationship with Bennett has been cool, called it ``a great
meeting.''
   The other mayors at the meeting were: Robert Isaac, Colorado
Springs, Colo.; Joseph Riley, Charleston, S.C.; Richard Berkley,
Kansas City, Mo.; Arthur Holland, Trenton, N.J.; Wilson Goode,
Philadelphia; William Hudnut, Indianapolis; Jerry Abramson,
Louisville; Joseph Paolino, Providence; Jessie Rattley, Newport
News, Va.; Theodore Mann, Newton, Mass.; William Althaus, York,
Pa.; and John Rousakis, Savannah, Ga.
</TEXT>
