<FIRST>r w AM-MilitaryExercise     07-25 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Exercise,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States, Australian Troops to Hold Military Exercises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military troops from the United States and
Australia will hold a month-long exercise, the largest for the two
nations since World War II, in northern Australia next month,
Pentagon officials announced Tuesday.
   During the exercise, dubbed ``Kangaroo 89,'' the U.S. and
Australian armed forces will conduct mock battles in the air, land
and sea over an area the size of western Erope. About 2,300 U.S.
military personnel will join thousands of active and reserve troops
from Australia.
   ```Kangaroo 89' will test both countries _ Australia on how well
it can defend its territory and the United States on its ability to
deploy forces to a distant location and operate once there,''
according to a Pentagon statement.
   U.S. Navy ships and aircraft will conduct anti-submarine,
anti-air and anti-surface warfare training with their Australian
counterparts, the statement said.
   The manuevers, which begin Aug. 1, are part of a series of
exercises between the United States and Australia.
</TEXT>
