<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1353EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Somalia     07-25 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Somalia,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Somali Cabinet Ministers Arrested, Accused of Plotting Against State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunfire broke out in Somalia's capital
near the home of the ousted defense minister who was detained this
week on charges of plotting against the government, sources said
Tuesday.
   Also Tuesday, a human rights group said house-to-house searches
and detentions continued in Mogadishu, the Somali capital, nearly
two weeks after deadly clashes between Moslem worshipers and Somali
soldiers.
   The brief outburst of shooting started Monday, apparently when
soldiers went to search the home of former Defense Minister Aden
Abdullahi Nur, according to a resident who spoke on condition of
anonymity. He did not know if there were casualties.
   Nur was stripped of his defense portfolio in a Cabinet shakeup
this year and remained minister-without-portfolio in the office of
autocratic President Mohamed Siad Barre.
   He and a fellow minister-without-portfolio, Mohammed Abdulleh
Ba'adleh, were arrested Monday and accused of plotting against the
state, according to Mogadishu sources. Ba'adleh had been minister
of interior until the Cabinet shuffle.
   State-run Mogadishu Radio announced Monday the two are accused
of acts which ``threatened the sovereignty, unity and security and
togetherness of the large community of the Somali people.''
   The broadcast, monitored in neighboring Kenya, said prosecutors
are investigating the ministers. The broadcast did not say they
were arrested.
   Nur is a member of Somalia's Ogadeni clan, which reportedly has
been feuding with the govenment in central and southern Somalia.
The Horn of Africa nation's 6 million people all belong to the
Somali tribe, which is divided into half a dozen major clans. Siad
Barre belongs to the Marehan clan.
   It is not clear whether the charges against Nur and Ba'adleh are
related to July 14 riots when security forces opened fire on Moslem
worshipers in Mogadishu. The human rights group Africa Watch said
troops killed as many as 400 civilians. The government put the toll
at 23.
   Africa Watch, in a statement sent by telex to Nairobi, claimed
Tuesday that arrests and house-to-house searches that followed and
in which at least 2,000 people have been arrested continue in
Mogadishu, although on a reduced scale.
   Troops still are enforcing a 9 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew relaxed
from a dawn-to-dusk curfew imposed July 14, residents said.
   The violence erupted after the July 13 arrests of four Moslem
leaders and an unspecified number of civilians, according to Africa
Watch, which has offices in London and Washington. Islam is the
state religion of the impoverished, pastoral nation.
   The claims are difficult to assess as the government has refused
to allow Western journalists into the country since heavy fighting
broke out between government forces and the northern rebel Somali
National Movement in May 1988.
   Siad Barre has ruled Somalia as a one-party state since 1969 and
has battled the northern rebels since 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
