<HEAD>Navy Man Cleared After 4{ Years in Prison Returns to Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GULFPORT, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy man who was cleared of a murder
conviction after 4{ years in prison rejoined the service, praising
his superiors for standing by him while he fought the charges.
   Surrounded by at least 40 friends, James Robert Steele was
restored Monday to his former rank of petty officer in a
re-enlistment ceremony at the Construction Battalion Center in
Gulfport.
   ``We're always glad to have good sailors re-enlist,'' said Capt.
Herb Lewis, the center's commanding officer.
   Steele, 38, was convicted in 1985 of killing 23-month-old
Christina Sinclair, the daughter of his then-girlfriend, Kathy
Sinclair of Long Beach, Miss.
   He spent 4{ years behind bars before the Mississippi Supreme
Court reversed his conviction in April, ruling the evidence was
insufficient.
   The Navy never discharged Steel, but his commission expired in
1986 while he was in prison. In a 10-minute ceremony, Steel was
honorably discharged from his first commission, then re-enlisted
for two more years in the Seabees.
   He was given a good-conduct medal for behavior during the
earlier tour of duty, and officials have promised to restore back
pay that was withheld while he was in prison.
   ``I'm happy that I'm still in the military,'' Steele said. ``I
think them sticking behind me like they did speaks well of the
military.''
   The Navy awaited the outcome of Steele's appeal before ruling on
his status.
   ``The Navy has gone along with the legal system, and justice has
prevailed,'' Lewis said. ``We accept the final outcome.''
   At his trial, prosecutors said Steele killed the girl by
slamming her head against a flat object on Oct. 10, 1984. The child
died 13 days later. Steele maintained the child fell out of bed.
