<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0517 07-25 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0517,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Possibility Of Resignation Raised by Tom Bradley Supporter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Officials testifying ..., with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with Bradley response. Pick up 6th graf pvs, `The change ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony about a doctored bank document
intensified the furor over Mayor Tom Bradley's financial dealings
and prompted a longtime supporter to raise the possibility of the
mayor's resignation.
   Bradley, who was elected this year to a fifth term, faces
criticism for his personal financial affairs, including taking
consulting fees from a bank that had dealings with the city and
serving on the board of a savings and loan.
   Bradley should consider resigning if he is found to have
influenced city decisions to deposit money in Far East National
Bank, Councilwoman Joan Milke Flores, long a supporter of the
mayor, said after a council committee meeting Monday.
   ``If he can't explain away any of this, he is going to have to
assess his effectiveness in running the city,'' Ms. Flores told the
Los Angeles Times. She added, however, that she was not
recommending that Bradley quit.
   Bradley today insisted that he wouldn't resign, and said he
didn't know why the phrase ``per the mayor'' was blotted out on a
worksheet detailing a $2 million investment of city funds.
   Questioned by reporters after a City Hall news conference on
another matter, Bradley said: ``To anyone who has any such
thoughts, I'll be around here four years from now, as mayor of this
city.''
   Officials testifying before the council's budget committee
revealed Monday that the notation ``per the mayor'' was removed
from a bid document from Far East and replaced with that of the
city treasurer, Leonard Rittenberg.
   The change was made to a document dated March 23, one day after
the bank was given $2 million in city deposits without going
through the usual competitive bidding process, the council panel
was told Monday.
   ``Per the mayor'' had been written under a section on the
document reporting the deposits, but was changed to read ``per
Leonard Rittenberg,'' said Edward Corser, head of the chief
administrative office's audit and management division.
   Bradley's name was blacked out with a marking pen, then covered
with typewriter correction fluid and replaced with the treasurer's,
Corser said.
   An audit released by Corser's office last week concluded that
Rittenberg ordered the deposits only a day after Bradley asked the
treasurer about the city's relationship with the bank.
   The audit also found that Rittenberg had tried to cover up the
transaction by creating documents that purported to show other
banks competing for the deposits.
   Bradley refused to comment on the latest developments. Deputy
Mayor Mike Gage denied that Bradley exerted influence on Far East's
behalf.
   Gage said the mayor immediately returned his $18,000 adviser's
fee from Far East after learning from his March 22 conversation
with Rittenberg of the bank's dealings with the city.
   Rittenberg told the committee the original reference to Bradley
on the document was simply a mistake made by one of his
subordinates.
   ``This is a worksheet,'' Rittenberg said of the document.
``Quite often, things are written on them (and) whited out, crossed
out.
   ``Nowhere did I instruct or tell my staff to make those
placements `per the mayor,''' Rittenberg testified.
   Corser testified that the document was altered after Rittenberg
informed aides that Bradley's ties to the bank were being examined
by reporters.
   Bradley's financial dealings with Far East and with Valley
Federal Savings &amp; Loan, which paid him $24,000 a year as a board
member until he resigned earlier this year, are the subject of
investigations by the city attorney, the city controller and
federal banking authorities.
</TEXT>
