<FIRST>r i AM-OAU     07-25 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OAU,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Africans Praise U.S. Congress for Rejecting South African Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary-general of the
Organization of African Unity hailed the U.S. Congress on Tuesday
for objecting to a Washington visit by South Africa's
President-designate F.W. de Klerk.
   In a speech to African leaders at the pan-African organization's
annual summit, Ide Oumarou of Niger noted that 100 congressmen had
written President Bush objecting to de Klerk's scheduled visit
later this year.
   The congressmen said Bush should not entertain de Klerk, who is
expected to succeed President P.W. Botha in September, until
Pretoria improves its human rights record.
   Oumarou said the action ``speaks eloquently of the determination
of the Congress to take a firm stand'' against white-run South
Africa.
   However, he praised the Bush administration for making ``a
decisive contribution for law, peace and security to prevail'' in
South Africa.
   He said the U.S.-brokered agreement providing for Namibia's
independence from South Africa shows the influence Washington can
bring to bear on African issues.
   Oumarou is seeking re-election to a second four-year term as the
organization's secretary-general and faces a stiff challenge from
Salim A. Salim, Tanzania's deputy prime minister and defense
minister.
   Conference sourcese say the rivals appear to be running
neck-to-neck and each has been asked to withdraw in favor of the
one with the most votes if neither achieves the necessary
two-thirds majority after two secret ballots Wednesday.
   The proposed deal reportedly was brokered by Presiden's Mengistu
Haile Mariam of Ethiopia, Moussa Traore of Mali, the organization's
outgoing chairman, and Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. Mubarak on Monday
takes over leadership of the 50-nation organization that was
founded in 1963 and is the world's largest continental body.
   Meanwhile, sources close to the Egyptian delegation said Mubarak
met privately Monday with Sudanese rebel leader Col. John Garang,
whose Sudan People's Liberation Army has been fighting the Khartoum
government for six years in southern Sudan.
   Mubarak stopped in Khartoum en route to Addis Ababa on Sunday
and met with Sudan's new military leader, Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan
Ahmed el-Bashir, who has called for peace talks with the southern
rebels since he ousted an elected civilian government June 30.
   ``It is a very complicated matter and cannot be solved
immediately,'' a source said after Mubarak met Garang. ``The
meeting was part of Egypt's effort to find a solution to the Sudan
problem.''
   Garang has not been seen at the conference, but one of his key
advisers, former Sudanese Foreign Minister Mansour Khalid, has been
circulating extensively among delegates.
   El-Bashir, in a speech to African leaders Tuesday, extended a
unilateral cease-fire for one month and again pledged his best
efforts to settle with the rebels. Garang has not responded
directly, but appears to be tacitly accepting the cease-fire.
</TEXT>
