<HEAD>Doctor Found Dead In Brooklyn Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a 36-year-old doctor was found
Tuesday in a bathroom of the hospital where he worked with three
syringes scattered next to him, police said.
   Dr. William Westerfield, a second-year resident at Methodist
Hospital in Brooklyn, had no visible wounds and an autopsy was
planned to determine the cause of death, according to police
spokesman Vincent Jones.
   The body was found curled in a fetal position on the floor of a
staff bathroom after an employee summoned a maintenence worker to
open the locked door, said hospital spokesman Daniel Rowland. It
was not yet determined what the syringes contained, officials said.
   Westerfield had a wife and two children and lived in Brooklyn,
officials said.
   ``We're still dealing with the shock of it,'' Rowland said.
``The staff knew him to be a caring, competent and qualified
physician.''
