<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1412EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DC-10Crash-Skinner     07-25 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash-Skinner,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Secretary Says DC-10s Are Safe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-DC-10, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nothing in the United Airlines DC-10 crash at
Sioux City, Iowa, indicates that other DC-10s are unsafe or that
anything more now needs to be done to make them safer,
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said Tuesday.
   Skinner defended a declaration by new Federal Aviation
Administration head James Busey that the DC-10 is a safe aircraft
even though the cause of the crash Wednesday that killed 111 people
has not been determined.
   Investigators are focusing on evidence that the triple-jet's
tail engine blew up, disabling its hydraulic steering system, but
they have offered no explanation for the explosive engine failure.
   Transportation Department experts have been made available for
the crash investigation, Skinner told a news conference, ``but
nothing has been indicated to us that we should do anything we're
not doing.''
   He said the decision to affirm that the DC-10 is safe is based
on the aircraft's record. Its manufacturer, Douglas Aircraft, says
DC-10s have flown 745 million passengers 7 billion miles over two
decades. The airliner also has been in some of history's worst air
disasters, blamed on maintenance problems, pilot error or a cargo
door defect that has been corrected.
   Skinner said if the department said nothing about the DC-10, it
might imply that something was wrong.
   Nothing in the plane's record indicates that it is either
inherently unsafe or that ``anything needs to be done that hasn't
been done,'' he said.
   If, however, evidence is uncovered during the National
Transportation Safety Board's investigation of the Iowa crash that
indicates a problem, action will be taken, Skinner said.
   The FAA has the power to ground an airplane, as it did with the
DC-10 after a 1979 Chicago crash that killed 275 people and was
later blamed on a faulty maintenance procedure by American Airlines.
   It also issues ``airworthiness directives'' that require work on
airliners within a set period of time when a problem is found.
   Skinner, in a statement he said was not related to the crash of
the 15-year-old United DC-10, also said the department is
continuing to study how to keep aging airliners free of problems,
including corrosion.
   An industry study is expected within a few weeks that will
recommend mandatory maintenance of DC-10s and other McDonnell
Douglas-manufactured models. A similar study earlier this year
recommended work on Boeing airliners and most recommendatons in the
study were later adopted by the FAA as mandatory.
</TEXT>
