<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1416EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Prisons-Drugs     07-25 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prisons-Drugs,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delaware Governor Urges New Programs to Fight Drug Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delaware Gov. Michael M. Castle called Tuesday
for stepped up education and treatment for substance abusers in
prison as a means of relieving crowded conditions and making
streets safer.
   ``Dealing with the inmates while they are in the institutions
just might be the key to solving the prison crisis, because sooner
or later the overwhelming majority will be released,'' Castle told
the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   He pointed to therapy programs to give inmates a more positive
self-image plus education and prevention programs and efforts to
keep the prisons themselves drug-free.
   Castle's comments came as Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., opened
hearings in advance of drug policy coordinator William Bennett's
scheduled Sept. 5 announcement of a strategy for waging war on drug
abuse.
   Biden said his hearings would explore topics ranging from how to
fund the war on drugs to how to fight it. He said the problem of
imprisoned substance abusers is serious and displayed a number of
means by which drugs have been smuggled behind bars.
   While cameras clicked, Biden took apart a woman's shoe in which
had been hidden what he described as ``a little ol' green pill.''
He also held up a jar of carrot baby food containing an orange bag
with narcotics inside.
   Castle told the panel that the ``drug problem has dealt a blow
to our overall criminal justice system.''
   ``Our courts are clogged with extensive backlogs, prosecution
caseloads have doubled in many jurisdictions, our police find
themselves in many instances outmanned and outgunned in dealing
with drug traffickers,'' he said.
   Castle said he had signed into law a measure that would provide
a minimum penalty of three years in prison for trafficking in no
more than 5 grams of a narcotic substance. He also said he recently
agreed to build a new 600-bed prison.
   But the Delaware governor said the number of arrests is so great
that even before that prison is finished, the state may be planning
to construct a new one.
   ``I am concerned... that we have done too little to consider
alternatives to hard time in maximum security institutions,'' he
said. He said efforts should be made to head off the problems
before they land in court.
   In addition to therapy and drug abuse prevention programs,
Castle called for vocational help and basic education for inmates.
He cited estimates that 75 percent are functionally illiterate when
they enter and the vast majority still are when they leave. ``It is
essential that programs to teach reading and writing to the inmates
be established,'' he said.
   Castle also said sentencing alternative should be expanded.
   ``Certainly big-time dealers must be dealt with in the harshest
way possible,'' he said. ``But we also need effective ways to deal
with the little fish we catch in our nets, and I would argue that
different approaches are necessary.''
   As an example, he said courts ``should not punish the users of
small amounts of drugs as we would those who are major
traffickers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
