<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Ambassadors     07-25 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Ambassadors,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Narrowly Approves Bush Diplomatic Choices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of President Bush's ambassadorial
nominees, accused by Democrats of having no qualifications except
political connections, won narrow approval Tuesday from the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee.
   With Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., joining committee Republicans,
the panel first voted 10-9 to send to the Senate floor the
nomination of Florida real estate developer Joseph Zappala to be
ambassador to Spain.
   Then, by voice votes, it approved the equally controversial
nominations of Florida real estate developer Marvin Sembler to be
ambassador to Australia and Della Newman, a Seattle, Wash., real
estate broker, to be ambassador to New Zealand.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., who led the fight against the
nominees, vowed to continue the battle on the Senate floor.
   ``One looks through this resume wondering why this person has
been appointed to this position,'' Sarbanes said of Zappala.
   ``The answer is to be found in the appendix which lists the
campaign contributions.
   ``If we are going to reduce it to that we should put the office
up for public auction and put the money in the Treasury to reduce
the deficit,'' Sarbanes said.
   In other action the committee routinely gave its approval to the
nomination of former child actress Shirley Temple Black to be
ambassador to Czechoslovakia. She won praise for her performance in
a previous appointment as U.S. ambassador to Ghana.
   It also approved Thomas Melady to be ambassador to the Holy See;
William Howard Taft IV, to be the permanent U.S. representative on
the Council of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization; Keith L.
Brown to be ambassador to Denmark, and Joseph Gildenhorn, a
Washington lawyer and real estate developer, to be ambassador to
Switzerland.
   Gildenhorn and members of his immediate family have given nearly
$225,000 to the Republican National Committee and state GOP
campaigns since 1984.
   The American Academy of Diplomacy gave Gildenhorn, Zappala,
Sembler and Newman ``unqualified'' ratings. Sarbanes said Zappala
and Sembler each gave more than $100,000 to Republican causes and
Newman served as chairman of the Washington state Bush For
President Committee.
   Sarbanes also said 30 of the 44 ambassadors named thus far by
Bush have been political appointees, not career ambassadors.
   ``This 68 percent of political nominations far exceeds such
appointments at a comparable point in previously elected
administrations,'' he said.
   Sending unqualified envoys insults the country involved,
demoralizes the professional foreign service and says to the world,
``America is not serious about diplomacy,'' Sarbanes said. ``Would
one for a moment consider nominating generals and admirals in the
same fashion?''
   Sen. Terry Sanford, D-N.C., noted that although Zappala is being
sent to ``the pre-eminent Spanish-speaking country in the world, he
does not speak Spanish.''
   Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., said Zappala, Sembler and Newman
will bring unique qualifications to their ambassadorships. ``I
believe they are indeed competent people who have achieved a great
deal and are besides close friends of the president,'' he said.
   But Sarbanes said the Senate was given the power to reject
presidential nominees in order to weed out ``cronies'' and ``unfit
characters.''
   ``It matters who ambassadors are,'' he said. ``It is not enough
to send a political appointee and hope he or she won't make
mistakes.''
</TEXT>
