<DOCNO> AP890725-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1455EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     07-25 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Realtors Say Falling Mortgage Rates Help Spur Rebound in Home Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Falling mortgage rates helped spur a 5.9
percent rebound in existing homes sales last month after five
months without a gain, a real estate trade group said Tuesday.
   Analysts said they expected continued improvement but cautioned
that sluggish economic growth likely would prevent anything
stronger than a modest resurgence.
   The National Association of Realtors said sales of existing
single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
3.4 million units in June, up from May's rate of 3.21 million units.
   It was the first increase in sales since December 1988 and the
largest increase since December 1986, when sales jumped 6.6 percent.
   ``Finally the existing home market responded to the decline in
interest rates,'' said economist Richard Peach of the Mortgage
Bankers Association of America, who predicts modest improvement
through the summer.
   According to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., fixed-rate
mortgages during June fell from 10.48 percent to 10.07 percent and
have since edged down to 9.87 percent last week. Analysts expect a
small additional drop.
   However, Peach warned that fewer new jobs and lackluster
economic growth overall will keep existing home sales near 3.4
million units this year, well below last year's nine-year high of
3.59 million units.
   ``We don't think the underlying demand is strong enough to
create much of a surge,'' he said.
   Realtors President Ira Gribin said lower mortgage rates, by
making monthly payments more affordable, spurred cost-conscious
buyers in June to purchase moderately-priced homes.
   Sales in the Midwest, where prices are lowest, showed the
sharpest increase, while sales in the Northeast, where prices are
the highest, declined.
   Midwestern sales rose 18.5 percent to an annual rate of 960,000
units, the highest level since December. Sales increased 5.2
percent in the West to 610,000 units and 4.1 percent in the South
to 1.28 million units.
   In the Northeast, however, sales fell 9.8 percent to a rate of
550,000 units, the lowest level since February 1985.
   Nationally, the median sales price, meaning half the homes sold
for more and half for less, was $93,200 in June, up $600 from May
and 3.3 percent from a year earlier.
   By region, the median price was $149,800 in the Northeast, up
1.7 percent from a year ago; $134,100 in the West, up 5.6 percent;
$84,900 in the South, up 1.2 percent, and $72,100 in the Midwest,
up 3 percent.
   ``The housing market tends to march very closely on a regional
basis with trends in employment growth,'' said economist John
Hagens of the WEFA Group, a Bala Cynwyd, Pa., forecasting firm.
``In the Northeast, employment is stagnating because of high prices
for houses. There aren't very many people unemployed to bring back
to work and it's very difficult to attract employees in from other
parts of the country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
