<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Hungary     07-25 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Hungary,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Discusses Reforms with Hungarian Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Strike, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev met Tuesday with
two Hungarian leaders to discuss reforms aimed at ``creating a
society of free people'' in both countries, the official Tass news
agency reported.
   Gorbachev met at the Kremlin with Karoly Grosz, general
secretary of the Hungarian communist party, and Rezsoe Nyers, who
has described himself as first among equals in the reformist
four-man presidium established in a power shuffle last month.
   The two sides also discussed the withdrawal of Soviet troops
from Hungary, Tass said. In May, the Red Army began the staged
withdrawal of 10,000 of its 62,000 troops stationed in Hungary.
   Grosz and Nyers left Moscow after the Kremlin meeting, Tass
reported.
   The Soviet Union has faced a wave of strikes and ethnic unrest
that accompanied the economic and political reforms launched since
Gorbachev rose to power in March 1985. Next year, Hungary will hold
its first multiparty elections since 1948.
   ``Nyers and Grosz spoke about problems encountered in Hungary
during the search for ways of updating the socio-ecomomic political
model of society,'' Tass said.
   ``Gorbachev noted the active quest in the socialist world for
ways to achieve socialist revival, to launch socialism onto a
drastically higher orbit in the name of creating a society of free
people, masters of their lives and their countries,'' Tass said.
   On Saturday, the first opposition candidate in more than 41
years, 35-year-old pastor, was elected in a local by-election to
Hungary's Communist dominated government.
   Also Tuesday, Hungary's Communist Party was reported to have
asked a British company to help coach communist politicians in the
art of public relations, but the agency later denied any knowledge
of such a plan.
   The party daily Nepszabadsag quoted an official as saying
Hungarian commmunists have asked the Charles Barker Public
Relations Ltd. of London to assist the party in its face-lifting
campaign.
   The agency on Tuesday said it had no knowledge of such a request.
   The party's rating in opinion polls has slipped in the past year
despite its embrace of reforming policies, and it is scrambling to
revamp its image ahead of the expected competitive elections next
year.
</TEXT>
