<FIRST>r w AM-SocialSecurity-King     07-25 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security-King,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Approves King Nomination for Social Security Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee on Tuesday
approved the nomination of Gwendolyn S. King to head the Social
Security Administration, and she promised efforts to improve the
retirement and disability system.
   Mrs. King, whose nomination was approved by voice vote and sent
to the full Senate, promised to ``reach out to the most vulnerable
among those we serve and ensure for them the `security' that is our
mission.''
   A fomer aide to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh when he was
governor of Pennsylvania and to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., Mrs. King
said she would work to create ``a fairer, more efficient and humane
Social Security system.''
   The Social Security Administration, with an annual budget of
$230 billion, currently provides 38.6 million people with monthly
retirement, disability or survivor's benefits.
   As part of a program to streamline and modernize its operations,
the agency pared its workforce by about 20 percent during the
Reagan administration years to about 65,000 employees. Critics have
complained of a drop in the quality of service to the public and of
low employee morale.
   John N. Sturdivant, president of the American Federation of
Government Employees, which represents 55,000 Social Security
employees, said the union did not oppose Mrs. King's nomination and
hoped to work with her to solve ``serious problems.''
   ``By all accounts, both managers and rank and file employees are
rapidly sinking under the burden of an ever-growing workload and
the fact that they cannot service the public as it deserves to be
served,'' he said.
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., expressed confidence Mrs.
King's nomination would be approved and said the new administrator
will take over an agency that has suffered from ``instability in
leadership,'' going through 10 administrators in the last 16 years.
   Moynihan said the new administrator will have to defend Social
Security's trust funds against use for deficit reduction or other
government purposes and also will face low public confidence about
the future of the benefits program.
   ``Social Security is one of the greatest governmental success
stories of the century, but people don't believe it,'' he said.
   Mrs. King currently is an executive vice president of the
Washington government relations firm of Gogol &amp; Associates. She
would replace Dorcas Hardy, who last month announced she would
resign July 31.
   The Finance Committee also approved by voice vote Tuesday the
nominations of Linda M. Combs to be assistant treasury secretary
for management, Thomas J. Duesterberg to be an assistant secretary
of commerce, and Wade F. Horn to be chief of the Children's Bureau
in the Department of Health and Human Services.
</TEXT>
