<FIRST>r a AM-TwinTicket 1stLd-Writethru a0638 07-25 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Twin Ticket, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0638,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twin Candidates May Cause Double Take at the Polls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 5th graf pvs: `Jean-Guy...' to give dates
for election.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people complain that all politicians
are alike, and in the Salem City Council race, they may have a
point.
   Even their own children sometimes have trouble distinguishing
at-large City Council candidate Jean-Guy Martineau from his
identical twin, Ward 5 candidate Jean-Claude Martineau.
   ``People are a bit confused,'' Jean-Guy said Tuesday.
   Jean-Guy, a City Council member for 12 years, holds the Ward 5
seat. He and his brother didn't set out to make voters do a double
take, he said.
   Jean-Guy is one of seven men running for four at-large seats.
Jean-Claude is among three candidates for the Ward 5 seat vacated
by his twin.
   Jean-Claude will be on the primary election ballot Sept. 26. If
he survives that test, he and his brother both will run in the
general election in November.
   City Clerk Josephine Fusco says she sometimes has trouble
identifying the 40-year-old political pair.
   ``They're having a lot of fun with this,'' she said. ``They're
very close. In fact when Jean-Claude came in the other day I had to
hesitate because I wasn't sure what I was going to call him.''
   The brothers wore the same hairdos, crisp white shirts and dark
blue ties Tuesday, sometimes answering questions in unison. But
they also exhibited a little sibling rivalry.
   ``He's a little heavier than me,'' Jean-Guy said.
   ``I think it's the other way around,'' Jean-Claude retorted.
   Jean-Claude, the younger by 10 minutes, was living in Florida
and returned to Salem six months ago. He said he decided to get
into politics partly because his brother's constituents kept
approaching him on the street.
   ``He got all the complaints and I got off free half of the
time,'' Jean-Guy joked.
   Both brothers are Republicans, but they don't claim twin
philosophies.
   ``I think that we're both very conservative,'' Jean-Guy said.
``Jean-Claude is a little bit more compassionate than I am. I'm
more conservative looking at the issues and I try to be more
realistic.''
   Born Jan. 3, 1949, the twins are the youngest of 12 children.
They grew up in Salem and attended St. Joseph High School, where
they got their first taste of politics when Jean-Claude beat out
Jean-Guy for president of the freshman class.
   ``I was always the clown in high school, whereas Jean-Claude was
the more serious one,'' Jean-Guy said.
   After graduation, Jean-Guy enlisted in the Navy. Jean-Claude
entered a Catholic seminary, but after five months, he too, joined
the Navy. When both twins' ships stopped in the Philippines, the
brothers sometimes got into trouble, Jean-Guy recalled.
   ``No one would believe when I told them I wasn't from their
ship. He was a fire control technician and I was in communications
so our rating patches were different and people would think we were
out of uniform,'' he said.
   Now, Jean-Claude works for Standard-Thomson Corp. in Waltham, a
manufacturer of thermostats for cars and airplanes, and Jean-Guy is
an engineer for the Raytheon Missile Division in West Andover.
   Mistakes in identity still happen.
   When Jean-Claude first returned from Florida, he ran a stop sign
while driving in Salem. The policeman let him off, believing he was
council member Jean-Guy.
   ``They should have given him a ticket in my opinion,'' Jean-Guy
said.
   Ms. Fusco, the city clerk, has a plan to cut down on the
confusion if both are elected to the council: ``They'll be assigned
to the same seat every council meeting.''
</TEXT>
