<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Treaties     07-25 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Treaties,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Relations Panel Approves Treaties on Criminal Investigations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee
approved on Tuesday treaties with Mexico, the Bahamas, Canada,
Belgium, Thailand and the Cayman Islands providing for mutual
cooperation in criminal investigations, especially those dealing
with narcotics trafficking.
   The vote sending the treaties to the Senate for ratification was
16-2.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said the treaties are of ``vital
importance'' in forging cooperation to assist the United States in
gathering evidence to prosecute narcotics cases.
   But Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said they should not be approved
by the committee or ratified by the Senate because they might place
Americans in the situation of being prosecuted in foreign courts
without full constitutional protections.
   He also said the United States should not ratify such treaties
with Mexico or the Bahamas because they have top legal officials
suspected of corruption and involvement in protecting drug
trafficking.
   Helms accused the Bush administration of ``a massive coverup''
of information linking these officials to alleged narcotics
corruption.
   But Kerry and other senators said the treaties are supported
fully by the Bush administration as a useful tool in the war on
drugs.
   They said the president and Justice Department retain the
ability to deny frivolous requests by foreign governments and to
protect the constitutional rights of Americans.
</TEXT>
