<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Soviet     07-25 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Soviet,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Historians Praise Soviet Acknowledgment of 1939 Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German historians, long rankled
by the Kremlin's refusal to acknowledge the 1939 non-aggression
pact that carved up Eastern Europe, say Moscow's recognition of
that prelude to World War II could fuel Baltic autonomy movements.
   ``A historical falsehood is finally being erased and truth is
being placed on the table,'' Wolfgang Leonhard, a West German
author and Soviet expert, told the Bonn newspaper Bonner Rundschau.
   Step by step, the Kremlin has moved toward officially conceding
that once-secret protocols to the 1939 agreement that divided
Poland and the Baltic states between Nazi Germany and Josef
Stalin's Soviet Union.
   A week after the non-aggression pact was signed on Aug. 23,
1939, Germany invaded Poland and set off World War II. The Soviets
seized Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia a year later.
   The 1939 agreement, known as the Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact, has
become a major rallying point among activists in the Baltic
republics who are demanding greater autonomy from Moscow.
   On Sunday night, a high-ranking Kremlin official stated he has
no reason to doubt the existence of the secret clauses of the 1939
pact, signed by Vyacheslav Molotov of the Soviet Union and Joachim
von Ribbentrop of Germany.
   ``There was a secret protocol,'' Valentin Falin, head of the
international department of the Communist Party's Central
Committee, said in a discussion on West German television.
   ``As far as the text is known, it is a copy of a copy and the
text corresponds to what was signed in reality,'' Falin said,
referring to a microfilm in West German archives.
   Kremlin officials had once maintained the microfilm may be a
fake, but Soviet historians investigating Baltic claims that their
states were seized illegally traveled to Bonn this year to examine
the West German records.
   Soviet officials who accompanied President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
on his June visit to West Germany also said the microfilm appeared
to be an accurate record.
   West German observers say Falin's statement is significant
because it comes from a high-ranking Communist Party functionary
who has previously adopted a hard line on the issue.
   ``This is a step-by-step retreat by Soviet officials,'' said
Gerhard Simon, an expert on Soviet affairs at the Federal Institute
for Eastern and International Studies in Cologne.
   ``This is nothing revolutionary because we are talking about
historical fact,'' said Reinhard Meyers, a Muenster University
professor.
   ``But this is an official (Soviet) seal of approval on what's
been said for decades'' by historians, said Meyers, who is among
West Germany's leading experts on the World War II era.
   While the deal between Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union has
been in the Western public domain for decades, the official Kremlin
line until recently was that no proof of secret protocols existed.
   ``We have been dealing with this extensively. There have been a
good number of new essays and books'' on the subject, said Simon.
   The Soviet news media have in recent months publicized some of
the West German research efforts.
   Last month, West German officials disclosed that Soviet
historians had inspected a microfilm copy of the secret protocols
and other related documents that have been preserved in the Bonn
Foreign Ministry archives.
   ``The Soviets had to retreat,'' Simon said. ``It became harder
and harder for them to claim there was no secret protocol.''
   The Tuesday editions of the Bonner Rundschau quoted Leonhard,
also a historian, as saying: ``The pressure from reform forces was
apparently so strong that now Falin _ in his important position _
has also decided to make a statement.''
   Simon says the evolution of Moscow's acknowledgement of Stalin's
secret deal with Hitler will likely bolster automony movements in
the Baltic republics.
   ``I think this will help their momentum,'' said Simon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0145 </DOCNO>
