<DOCNO> AP890725-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1532EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Cabinet Bjt   07-25 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Cabinet, Bjt,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Foreign Secretary Underlines Thatcher Stamp on Cabinets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Major, a high school dropout who took over
Tuesday as Britain's foreign secretary, personifies the
transformation of the political establishment wrought by grocer's
daughter Margaret Thatcher.
   The hierarchy of the governing Conservative Party, once the
preserve of bluebloods, is increasingly dominated by ``go-getters''
of Prime Minister Thatcher's decade in power, instinctive
conservatives often from modest backgrounds.
   Mrs. Thatcher, her administration slumping in popularity,
reinforced the grip of the self-made successes of her
free-enterprise revolution in a sweeping shakeup of her 22-member
Cabinet on Monday.
   Major was the most startling beneficiary.
   The 46-year-old son of a trapeze artist was raised in a two-room
apartment in south London's rundown Brixton district. He
leapfrogged from the most junior Cabinet post to one at the top of
a Cabinet that is far different from the one Mrs. Thatcher
appointed when she won power in 1979.
   Like her predecessor, Ted Heath, a carpenter's son, Mrs.
Thatcher at first surrounded herself with upper-class and benign
Conservative Party luminaries. Many held views to the left of her
own, and many also believed she was a temporary phenomenon.
   Just three members of that first 23-member Cabinet, including
Mrs. Thatcher, had been educated at state high schools. The rest
were all graduates of the prestigious all-boys boarding schools,
including six Old Etonians.
   Only two members of the new Cabinet are from the playing fields
of Eton. One, Nicholas Ridley, younger son of a viscount who she
switched to trade and industry secretary from the politically
sensitive environment ministry, is deeply unpopular with
rank-and-file legislators. The other, Lord Belstead, has an
hereditary title and is party leader in the unelected House of
Lords.
   Just over half the Cabinet members are people who, like Mrs.
Thatcher, made their way from state schools, often to one of the
ancient universities, Oxford or Cambridge. Major and Peter Walker,
the secretary of state for Wales, didn't go to college at all.
   They are characters in the mold of Leslie Titmuss, the ambitious
but flawed Tory hero of John Mortimer's book and TV series,
``Paradise Postponed.''
   The shift in the Conservative Party has brought sneers from both
the lower and upper strata in this class-conscious society that
Britain is now governed by garage owners and real estate agents.
   ``Putting new labels on bad wine doesn't improve the taste,''
London's 3 million-circulation Daily Mirror newspaper, an
opposition Labor Party supporter, complained in an editorial
Tuesday. ``This is still a government with an estate-agent
philosophy and an advertising agent mentality.''
   Mass-circulation right-wing newspapers hailed the changes,
particularly the sacking of Transport Secretary Paul Channon, an
impeccably mannered scion of the Guinness brewing family who
inherited a fortune in his 20s.
   His department was accused of bungling bomb warnings in the
aftermath of the Pan Am Flight 103 air disaster over Scotland Dec.
21 and for an inept performance during current waves of public
transportation strikes.
   Also shifted was the well-born party chairman, Peter Brooke, son
of a titled father. He became Northern Ireland Secretary and was
replaced in the key vote-garnering party post by Kenneth Baker, an
essentialy middle-class former education secretary.
   The Daily Express dismissed Ridley, Channon and Brooke as
``patrician figures ... all personalities a million miles away from
the populist, dynamic party Mrs. Thatcher has tried to create.''
   In 1979, Mrs. Thatcher's foreign secretary was in the classic
mold for the job: Lord Carrington, sixth in line to a herditary
baroncy, heir to vast family estates.
   Her next foreign secretary, Francis Pym, also came from the
wealthy landed gentry, and Sir Geoffrey Howe, whom she eased out of
the job this week, comes from a family of Welsh lawyers.
   Major, who says he became a Tory at 13, quit school at 16 to
become a laborer on a construction site because his mother, a
onetime music hall singer, needed the money. After a stint of
volunteer work in Nigeria, he made a career in banking.
   His political vision is essentially pragmatic. A lanky,
bespectacled figure with a classless accent, he once cited being
patient and being average as keys to political succees.
   ``The first requirement of politics is not intellect or stamina,
but patience,'' he said. ``Why should we leave politics to people
who are abnormal or not average?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
