<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1656EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Alcoholic'sHeir 1stLd-Writethru a0653 07-25 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alcoholic's Heir, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0653,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fetal Alcohol Syndrome: Bachelor Father Writes of Son's Illness</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 10th graf, beginning ``Adam,'' to delete redundant reference
to pseudonym.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1971, Michael Dorris became one of the first
bachelors allowed to adopt a child. He also became an unwitting
partner in the child's struggle against fetal alcohol syndrome.
   ``If you grow up with the idea that the world is fair, you can't
accept that these kids never had a chance,'' Dorris, a Dartmouth
professor, said in an interview about his recently published book
on his son's illness.
   After years of research, Dorris came to grips with the fact that
his son's illness was preventable but incurable. He wrote ``The
Broken Cord'' to tell the world about, and perhaps help someone
avoid, a disease passed along by hard-drinking mothers. But it gave
him no surcease from his pain.
   ``It's not been cathartic. One of the problems with this book is
that it does not have an ending,'' said Dorris.
   ``I finished the book when my son was 21, the age of majority
when your child is expected to be independent,'' Dorris said during
a recent stay in Boston. ``But it keeps going on. It's like
constantly opening doors into a dark room.''
   ``Adam,'' the pseudonym he's given his son in the book, now
works four days a week as a dishwasher at a truck stop in New
Hampshire. He lives in a group home and has to be reminded to
bathe, change his clothes, even eat.
   Fetal alcohol syndrome, the nation's third-largest cause of
retardation, was undocumented and unnamed a little more than a
decade ago.
   Nearly 8,000 children a year, or 1 to 3 of every 1,000 born,
have some or all of the syndrome's symptoms. These children, many
born to parents who also have FAS, suffer seizures, have poor
eyesight, balance or hearing. They frequently have curvature of the
spine and too many teeth.
   Their intelligence often is severely impaired; they can't grasp,
retain memories or reason into the future.
   Adam was born on a Sioux reservation to a woman who eventually
died of alcohol poisoning.
   Studies since have revealed that 5 percent to 25 percent of the
children born on some reservations have FAS, and there are
estimates that up to 50 percent of the members of some American
Indian tribes will have been born with it by the year 2000.
   Dorris, whose adoption application was aided by his partial
Indian ancestry, spent two years teaching Adam to tie his
shoelaces. Adam, the eldest of three adopted children, was 5 before
he was toilet-trained.
   ``I've lost my temper a million times and then felt guilty,''
said Dorris, adjunct professor of anthropology at Dartmouth and a
co-founder of the school's Native American studies program. ``But a
very direct anger is at least clear to him _ it's unambiguous.''
   He said the book's original impetus was scientific; he wanted to
document FAS and make the public aware.
   ``Society has to take note that this is a terribly dangerous
problem, he said, noting that the federal government is not
currently funding any FAS-related programs. ``We have to have
education, detox centers and health care for these women.''
   Dorris offers education as an alternative to more drastic
measures that some activists have suggested, such as sterilization
or imprisonment for pregnant women who have previously given birth
to FAS children.
   Dorris said he and his wife, the writer Louise Erdrich _ who in
addition to their three adopted American Indian children have three
biological daughters _ long ago gave up trying to reason with their
son.
   Logic is out of Adam's reach. Dorris confesses that, despite his
training as an anthropologist, he still hopes against rational hope
that his son one day will suddenly see everything clearly.
   ``But it makes no sense; it can't happen,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1712EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Martyr'sRemains     07-25 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Martyr's Remains,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Martyr's 1,600-Year-Old Remains Put to Rest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relics of St. Justin the martyr have been
laid to rest after 1,600 years in which they have been entombed in
the catacombs, secreted away by Italian nobles and displayed in a
Maryland church.
   An urn containing 15 small, brittle bones believed to be St.
Justin's was buried Monday in a shady plot near St. Mary's Roman
Catholic Church.
   ``We've finally put St. Justin to rest,'' said the Rev. John
Murray, who found the bones in a church safe 20 months ago and
conducted the funeral. ``It's not every day that you get to witness
burial of a 1,600-year-old martyr.''
   After he found the relics, Murray pieced together their history,
beginning in Rome in the 4th century A.D., when Justin was beheaded
at age 26.
   Justin was elevated to sainthood soon after his death, and his
remains were buried in the catacombs, the caverns beneath the
Appian Way in Rome used by early Christians.
   Then, in 1757, archaeologists unearthed remains they identified
as St. Justin's, along with what they believed were the remains of
two other martyrs, St Sergius and St. Nazarius, Murray said.
   For the next 110 years, the three sets of relics were cared for
by a series of noble Italian families and bishops. But in 1873,
during a period of civil unrest in Italy, the church sent them to
the Rev. Joseph Wissel in Baltimore for safekeeping.
   Wissell kept the box containing the relics of St. Justin, which
he displayed prominently in the church, and sent the others
elsewhere. During renovations to St. Mary's in the 1960s, priests
put the relics, wrapped in yellowed paper, in a box in the church
safe.
   Murray isn't at all sure the relics will remain in their present
resting place, even though the burial was cleared by the local
church hierarchy.
   ``The Vatican may want me to send the relics back to Rome,''
Murray said. ``If they want me to do that, then we'll dig him up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1551EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PTLTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0659 07-25 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PTL Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>PTL Aides Convicted of Tax Evasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from prosecutor, defense
attorney. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Brown said ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CH2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former PTL aides were convicted
Tuesday of evading $525,000 in income taxes on money they took from
the television ministry to buy condominiums, furs, jewelry and
nearly $100,000 worth of shoes.
   A federal jury deliberated five hours before convicting the
brothers, James and David Taggart, on identical charges: conspiracy
to defraud the government and impede the IRS by willfully evading
income taxes, and filing false tax returns for the years 1984,
1985, 1986 and 1987.
   ``Greed doesn't pay, no matter how rich you are, you've got to
pay your taxes,'' said federal prosecutor David Brown after the
verdict. ``The statement was not about PTL; it was about David
Taggart and James Taggart's obligations to pay their taxes no
matter how much they own and what kind of lifestyle they live.''
   Brown said he wasn't surprised the jury took just five hours.
   ``They didn't need to spend a lot of time looking at the
documents,'' he said. ``A person can omit $200 (in income) on their
tax return but it's hard to miss $1 million.''
   ``They were innocent going in and they are innocent coming
out,'' said defense lawyer Ben Cotten. He said he was to blame for
the guilty verdict, citing ``my ineptitude and two very capable and
competent government counsel backed with unlimited resources.''
   Brown said the case was decided by the defendants' own
testimony, but Cotten said they were forced to testify.
   ``They had to take the stand,'' Cotten said. ``They had to tell
their story. If they hadn't, the jury wouldn't have been able to
believe anything but a series of paper trails.''
   Cotten said the Taggarts' reaction to the verdict was ``a calm,
`where do we go from here?''' The brothers refused comment as they
left the courthouse.
   The Taggarts were charged with evasion after they allegedly
spent nearly $1.2 million in PTL money on personal luxuries such as
condominiums _ including a $640,000 apartment at Trump Tower in New
York, jewlery and designer clothes. Cotten said the money was
approved by the ministry's founder, Jim Bakker.
   In earlier testimony, a representative from a New York City fur
shop said the Taggarts spent about $35,000 on mink coats and other
furs for themselves at her store. And a salesman for a New York
shoe store said the Taggarts spent nearly $100,000 from 1982-86 on
shoes for themselves.
   Other testimony included the pair spent $320,000 in four
purchases at Cartier's jewelry store in New York, including $96,000
on one ring. They also took European vacations with friends and
family, often crossing the Atlantic on a Concord jet.
   Cotten said his clients weren't bitter at their former boss for
refusing to testify. Bakker invoked his right against
self-incrimination when he was called to the stand.
   Bakker and former PTL executive vice president Richard Dortch go
on trial Aug. 28 on charges of wire and mail fraud.
   Both Bakker and his wife, Tammy Faye Bakker, would often plead
for funds on television. Bakker and Dortch were indicted last Dec.
5 on charges of conspiring to defraud their supporters by diverting
more than $4 million to support their lavish lifestyles. If
convicted, each faces more than 120 years in prison and more than
$5 million in fines.
   Bakker quit PTL in March 1987 in a sex and money scandal after
he confessed to a sexual affair with former church secretary
Jessica Hahn.
   The Taggarts joined PTL in the late 1970s as piano players.
Within a few years, David Taggart, 32, was Bakker's top personal
aide. His brother, James, 35, was the interior designer at PTL's
Heritage USA Christian retreat, just south of Charlotte.
   Brown said he would recommend a stiff sentence. Each brother
faces a maximum of 25 years in prison and more than $1 million in
fines. Sentencing was set for Aug. 25.
</TEXT>
