<FIRST>u w AM-Fitzwater-Bloch     07-25 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fitzwater-Bloch,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fitzwater: Bloch On The Brain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House officials had little to say
Tuesday about Felix Bloch, the State Department diplomat being
investigated as a possible spy, but spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
clearly had Bloch on his mind.
   Fielding a question about another matter, Fitzwater said
President Bush has repeatedly ``expressed his outrage'' about
influence-peddling at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development and ``talked to Secretary Bloch on a number of
occasions about remedying the situation.''
   ``Secretary Kemp, I'm sorry,'' Fitzwater quickly added, this
time getting the name of HUD Secretary Jack Kemp right.
   Later, asked about reports that the United States had warned the
Soviets not to spirit Bloch out of the country, Fitzwater said he
did not know of them.
   But noting reports that Bloch was trailed from a relative's home
by both the FBI and Soviet officials, Fitzwater quipped: ``As near
as I can tell, the entire FBI and the Soviet Embassy is living with
the guy. I don't think he's going anywhere unnoticed.''
</TEXT>
