<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Soviet     07-25 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soviet,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Defense Minister Doubts Bush Timetable on Disarmament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov arrived
Tuesday on an historic visit to Britain and said he doesn't believe
an East-West treaty on conventional forces can be forged as quickly
as President Bush hopes.
   Yazov, the first Soviet defense minister to visit a NATO country
since World War II, also said British and French troops based in
West Germany should be included with American troops in a
conventional arms agreement.
   The general spoke at a news conference with Defense Secretary
George Younger after talks with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
and Younger. Later, he met new Foreign Secretary John Major.
   Yazov was pessimistic when asked if a conventional arms treaty
could be agreed as quickly as Bush urged at the May summit of North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Bush challenged Moscow to reach a treaty by next year and carry
it out by 1993. The timetable also has been linked by the West to
talks with the Warsaw Pact on short-range nuclear forces and
nuclear reductions.
   ``Myself, I do not believe that such a deal could be concluded
that quickly,'' Yazov said.
   ``Not all problems are being solved smoothly,'' he said,
although figures decided by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
and Bush are ``very close.''
   In particular, he said troops from European nations of the
Western alliance should not be excluded from a U.S. proposal to
restrict each side to 275,000 troops in East or West Germany.
Britain, France and other nations keep 170,000 troops in West
Germany, he said.
   ``Everything should be taken into account,'' Yazov said through
an interpreter. ``If these matters are solved, then we don't
believe the process of negotiations will take a long time.''
   He said he and Mrs. Thatcher, ``both took note that the Cold War
times are behind us.''
   A senior British official said talks with Yazov will focus on
Moscow's new defensive military strategy and Soviet views of Bush's
disarmament proposals.
   On charges that the new Soviet military doctrine is defensive
while Soviet forces' grouping remains offensive, Yazov told
reporters ``it is impossible to declare (we are) defensive today
and immediately change the organization.''
   The Soviets have pledged to withdraw 10,000 tanks, 8,500
artillery weapons and 820 aircraft from East European countries.
British officials say the withdrawals are on schedule, but they
suspect ammunition may be left behind to improve the capability of
remaining weapons.
   On Wednesday, Yazov will visit a Royal Air Force base in
Scotland to inspect Phantom and Tornado fighters which sweep NATO's
northern air flank for Soviet intrusions and an aircraft carrier,
HMS Invincible.
   His four-day visit is part of increased East-West military
contacts under Gorbachev's policy of reduced confrontation.
   ``This is the beginning of an official, high level
Soviet-British defense relationship,'' a senior British official
said on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
