<FIRST>r i AM-India-Storms     07-25 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Storms,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll From Storm Tops 450</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from a storm that swept
across India and triggered landslides and flash floods has topped
450, police and news reports said Tuesday.
   Police in Bombay, the capital of western Maharashtra state, said
at least 315 people were killed when the storm ripped through the
region Monday.
   Press Trust of India news agency said at least 115 people were
killed in central Andhra Pradesh state and 26 in eastern Orissa
state.
   The storm was caused by a depression over the Bay of Bengal and
moved northwest after crossing the Orissa coast on Sunday, news
reports said.
   At least 200 people were drowned or died in house collapses in
the Raigad district of Maharashtra, according to reports reaching
state police in Bombay.
   A police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said at
least 75 people were reported missing after the storm lashed the
coastal district.
   In Bombay, hundreds of trees felled by the storm blocked roads.
Waist-deep waters were receding but traffic in the usually bustling
city was scarce.
   At least 22 people died in the city, police said, with most of
the victims trapped under houses that collapsed in the rain.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi has ordered relief measures worth
$250,000 for the victims, United News of India news agency said.
</TEXT>
