<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1850EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Fire     07-25 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Fire,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Raise Death Toll in June Rail Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The June 4 fire caused by a gas leak in the Ural
Mountains has killed 645 people, including 181 children, a Soviet
official told the legislature Tuesday.
   Previous Soviet reports cited more than 600 deaths, but did not
give a precise figure.
   Two trains carrying 1,284 passengers and crew members were
engulfed in the inferno caused by a spark from an electrical line.
It ignited a highly flammable mixture of benzine and propane-butane
gas leaking from a pipeline near the city of Ufa about 750 miles
southeast of Moscow.
   The incident is being investigated as a criminal case by the
Soviet prosecutor's office, with results expected in November.
Investigators are focusing on how the pipeline was built and run,
said Vitaly Doguzhiyev, a deputy prime minister heading that state
commission on emergencies.
   The investigation has so far revealed that the pipeline was in
poor condition, in need of repair at several places, and lacking
insulation elsewhere, Tass quoted Doguzhiyev as telling parliament.
   Thirty of the victims have yet to be identified, Tass quoted him
as saying. Of those killed, 213 died in hospitals, 46 of them
children, it said. Another 396 people were treated at hospitals and
released.
   The line has been idle since the accident. Once the case is
closed, Doguzhiyev told parliament, the line will be used to carry
oil rather than gas.
</TEXT>
