<DOCNO> AP890725-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AgentOrange     07-25 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Orange,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Members Introduce $40 Million Agent Orange Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<NOTE>ouse Members Introduce $40 Million Agent</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Orange Bill
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam veterans suffering from cancers and
other ailments presumably linked to exposure to Agent Orange would
receive government compensation under a bill introduced Tuesday in
the House.
   The measure represents the latest round of a struggle between
veterans' advocates, who say the government is ignoring evidence
about the deadly herbicide, and government scientists, who say no
clear cause and effect can be established.
   ``This legislation takes the important breakthrough step in
creating a presumption that certain conditions, if developed in an
individual after exposure, are presumed related to that exposure
and are our country's responsibility _ not a burden of that
conflict to be borne in tragic isolation by the veteran,'' said
Rep. David E. Skaggs, D-Colo., a Marine veteran of Vietnam and one
of 60 co-sponsors of the bill.
   The bill, introduced by Reps. Lane Evans, D-Ill., and Martin
Lancaster, D-N.C., allows veterans to be compensated longer and for
more diseases than a version that has cleared the Senate Veterans'
Affairs Committee.
   Under the House bill, costing about $40 million a year, veterans
with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, soft-tissue sarcoma, melanoma and
basal cell carcinoma would be eligible for permanent disability
benefits. So would their survivors.
   The bill would also establish a presumption of service
connection for any Vietnam veteran with chloracne, a skin
condition, provided it occurred within a year of service.
   The Senate bill, covering only soft tissue sarcoma and
non-Hodgkins lymphoma, would provide benefits until April 15, 1992.
   The House and Senate bills would both require extensive
record-keeping based on health reports and tissue samples from
veterans. Both would ask the National Academy of Sciences to review
scientific studies on Agent Orange exposure every two years, with
the Department of Veterans Affairs making its benefits
determinations based on those reviews.
   Veterans are already allowed to receive outpatient and hospital
care for illnesses presumed to be linked to Agent Orange.
   The Senate passed an Agent Orange bill last year but the measure
never emerged from the House Veterans' Affairs Committee.
   Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., chairman of the House
committee, and the senior minority member, Rep. Bob Stump, R-Ariz.,
sent their colleagues a three-page letter Tuesday calling the newly
introduced bill ``premature at best.''
   They cited an ongoing study by the Centers for Disease Control
on the incidence of selected cancers among Vietnam-era veterans,
due for completion next spring. They also cited a federal court
order to change the criteria used to evaluate Agent Orange studies
and the recent creation of a U.S. Court of Veterans Appeals to
review claims.
   But supporters of the bill say the CDC and VA have dragged their
feet in trying to determine whether a link exists between Agent
Orange exposure and the various afflictions.
   CDC was accused in a House Government Operations subcommittee
hearing two weeks ago of botching or rigging its Agent Orange study
to fail. CDC contends it dropped a massive study of Agent Orange
exposure because there was no way to tell who was exposed.
   About 12 million gallons of the herbicide wre sprayed during the
war to remove the lush foliage that provided ground cover to the
enemy. Agent Orange contains dioxin, one of the most toxic
chemicals known, as well as 2,4,5-T and 2,4-D, also harmful
chemicals.
   An estimated 2.6 million military personnel served within the
borders of South Vietnam. About 250,000 have told VA they believe
they were exposed, and 35,000 have applied for disability benefits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
