<FIRST>r a AM-FloridaAbortion 1stLd-Writethru a0670 07-25 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Announces Special Session on Abortion Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 12th, `First of...' to UPDATE with ACLU
comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez on Tuesday called a
special legislative session for October to consider new
restrictions on abortions.
   ``We're dealing with lives, the unborn,'' Martinez said. ``I
believe that by a better balance of rights we can provide for more
life here in the state of Florida.''
   In a letter to state House and Senate leaders, the governor
called for legislation to block the use of tax money, public
facilities and public employees for abortions, and for tougher
licensing standards for abortion clinics.
   He also urged that the period of pregnancy in which the state
doesn't restrict abortion be shortened, to five months from six
months.
   The cal for a special session to begin Oct. 10 was a reaction to
a U.S. Supreme Court decision three weeks ago that allows states
greater leeway in regulating abortion.
   Martinez would not stop rape or incest victims from getting
abortions, or women whose lives are threatened by a pregnancy.
Women who are in their first 20 weeks of pregnancy would also have
the option of abortion, but not at public expense.
   Martinez didn't propose specific bills. Rather, he offered what
he called guidelines for laws to be drafted by legislators.
   ``I don't believe we ought to have state dollars to engage in
abortion except for the exceptions I've indicated,'' the governor
said.
   Martinez also asked lawmakers to ensure a pregnant woman has the
medical information to make an informed choice about abortion.
   Connie Amidei, an official with the Tallahassee chapter of the
National Organization for Women, tried on at least three occasions
to shout over reporter's questions to challenge the governor on his
position.
   ``The governor is not accessible, he's not talking to us,'' said
Ms. Amidei, who accused Martinez of seeking political gain on the
issue.
   ``First of all, let me say from the beginning I've said the
polls are not an issue here,'' Martinez said.
   The American Civil Liberties Union also condemned Martinez's
call for a special session and the proposal he submitted for
consideration, spokeswoman Robin Blumner said in Miami.
   Florida law allows abortions during the first six months of
pregnancy. A woman must have permission from two doctors, based on
health reasons, to acquire an abortion in the last trimester of
pregnancy.
   Lawmakers are also awaiting a decision from the Florida Supreme
Court on the state's new parental-consent law, which the
Legislature passed in 1988. That law prohibits minors from getting
an abortion without approval from a parent, guardian or judge.
</TEXT>
