<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Flag     07-25 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Flag,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Stands Firm On Flag Desecration Amendment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush remains ``adamant'' in support
of a constitutional amendment to outlaw desecration of the flag,
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday.
   He said the Justice Department has concluded that federal courts
would rule unconstitutional any statutory attempt to circumvent the
recent Supreme Court decision overturning flag desecration laws.
   ``The only way to protect the flag is through a constitutional
amendment,'' said Fitzwater. He said Congress should pass the
Bush-backed amendment if it ``is serious about protecting the
flag.''
   ``The President is adamant in his support of the public demand
to protect the flag. Flag-burning is an affront to America's
patriotic values. It (the flag) should be constitutionally
protected,'' he said.
   Bush has endorsed an amendment saying that ``The Congress and
the states shall have the power to prohibit the physical
desecration of the flag of the United States.''
   Some lawmakers and legal scholars, including House Speaker
Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., have raised concerns about what
constitutes desecration and whether the amendment would weaken the
Bill of Rights. Some lawmakers also say enthusiasm for an amendment
is waning among their constituents.
   However, Fitzwater said he thinks public sentiment is running
strongly in favor of the effort to amend the Constitution.
   One reporter asked Fitzwater why the flag needed special
protection when ``crosses have been burned longer in this country
than flags, and despite those burnings, the Christian faith and
church have survived.''
   ``Regardless of that, we still believe flag-burning should not
be legal,'' Fitzwater replied.
</TEXT>
