<HEAD>Burma Denies British Claim that Opposition Leader's Husband Held</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma on Tuesday denied statements by
British officials that authorities are keeping the British husband
of the country's best-known opposition leader under house arrest
with her.
   In London, Britain's Foreign Office said the Burmese ambassador
was called in and told that Britain could not accept its diplomats
being prevented from seeing the husband, Michael Aris.
   His wife, Aung San Suu Kyi, and her opposition partner Tin Oo
were placed under house arrest by the military goverment on
Thursday. They head the National League for Democracy, the
country's leading opposition group.
   They were arrested a day after pro-democracy protests broke out
in Rangoon, leading to the arrest of 44 people. Even though Ms. Suu
Kyi had canceled her group's rally that day, the government accused
her and her arrested colleague of trying to ``destroy the military
and revive anarchy.''
   A spokesman for the British Foreign Office on Tuesday reiterated
Britain's concern about Aris. Asked whether Britain believed Aris
to be under house arrest at his family's home in Rangoon, the
spokesman said, ``We do believe that to be so.''
   The British spokesman also said British officials visited the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Rangoon concerning Aris.
   The spokesman, commenting on condition of anonymity, said
Britain's charge d'affaires was prevented from seeing Aris, an
Oxford University professor and expert on Tibet, when he arrived at
Rangoon airport Saturday. Other attempts to see him also were
unsuccessful, he said.
   Burmese authorities said Aris was not under detention. ``The ...
report about his detention is not true,'' Foreign Affaires Minister
Ohn Gyaw said at a news conference in Rangoon.
   He said Aris had been permitted to join his wife and son after
arriving in Burma on Saturday. He said Aris was allowed to leave
each morning to study Buddhism at a monastery.
   However, under the terms of the house arrest, relatives may
leave the residence only under ``under surveillance.'' They are
forbidden to make contact with foreign embassies, political parties
or people connected with those parties.
   Ohn Gyaw said the British charge d'affaires was told of Aris'
situation.
   The British foreign office spokesman, however, said he was
unaware of such restrictions.
   He said British officials were continuing to press for access to
Aris.
   Gen. Saw Maung seized power in Burma in September. During the
year, the military killed thousands of people in crackdowns to
crush a nationwide popular movement for democracy.
   Burmese authorities briefly reopened telephone and telex lines
today to let reporters file stories on the government's denial of
the British charges.
   The military government has kept communications lines cut for
most of the time since the renewed pro-democracy protests Wednesday
in Rangoon. Authorities had also opened the lines for a government
news conference Friday.
   A Western diplomat in Bangkok said today that Rangoon was still
heavily policed by thousands of troops who were brought in
Wednesday. He estimated the force at 20,000 soldiers.
   The diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also said
there were credible reports from Rangoon that longtime socialist
strongman Ne Win had ordered the arrests of the opposition leaders.
   ``The thing that gives these credence is that Aung San Suu Kyi
started to name Ne Win in her s Backster at quarterback,
sophomore Eric Smith at fullback and junior Ray Whalen at tailback.
Each back also has solid backups Ault plans to shutttle in and out
of games as needed.
   ``We don't think we'll be hurting any, although we did lose
Foger,'' he said.
   He said coaches were encouraged when the no-name offense managed
to move the ball against the defense in spring drills. The defense,
with a line of players who can each bench press about 400 pounds
each, is expected to be one of the Wolf Pack's mainstays.
   Ault hints that the Wolf Pack will be in the hunt for the title,
although Idaho, Montana and Boise State also will be in the running.
   ``As long as Idaho'd got Friesz, they're in the ballgame,'' he
said, adding that the conference traditionally has been balanced
and anyone can win it. ``In this conference, you'd better be ready
to play every Saturday.''
   In Tuesday's afternoon session, the media were expected to hear
from Larry Kentera at Northern Arizona, Earle Solomonson at Montana
State and Skip Hall at Boise State.
   On Wednesday, first-year coaches Dave Arslanian of Weber State
and John Smith of Idaho will give previews along with Garth Hall at
Idaho State.
