<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-25 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Says It Repulsed Rebel Attack, Killing 180</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government forces repulsed an assault
by Moslem guerrillas west of Kabul and killed 180 of the attackers,
the government said Tuesday.
   In other battles, government troops killed 58 rebels and three
Pakistanis, the officials said.
   The reports were sketchy and impossible to verify independently,
and the government mentioned only three fatalities of its own. The
only date given was fot of Kabul, which reportedly
occurred Saturday.
   In that battle, guerrilla forces commanded by Gulbaddin
Hekmatyar attacked government soldiers at Maidan r the attack wesShahr,
capital of
Wardak province, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi
Amani.
   He said the guerrillas were driven back with many wounded, and
they had to abandon their 180 dead.
   He said a large quantity of arms and ammunition was captured or
destroyed in the attack.
   Hekmatyar is a leading member of the interim government created
to take over Afghanistan if the U.S.-backed rebels topple the
Soviet-supported Marxist government in Kabul.
   In the eastern province of Nangarhar, government troops attacked
and killed 38 rebels, including a Hekmatyar commander, in
retaliation for a guerrilla attack outside Jalalabad that killed
two soldiers, the government said. It said 48 guerrillas were
wounded.vernment also said three Pakistani military personnel were
killed when their jeep was attacked near Surkh Diwar, southeast of
Jalalabad.
   The Afghan government has repeatedly accused Pakistan of
fighting alongside the guerrillas. The most powerful rebel groups
are based in Pakistan, but Pakistan says it is not fighting with
them.
   In Herat province near Iran, the Afghan government said, army
troops ambushed guerrillas, killing six of them while capturing
arms and ammunition.
   In southern Kandahar, near the Pakistani border, a guerrilla
attack killed one soldier, and the military retaliated by killing
14 rebels, the government said.
   In Kabul, three more rockets injured five people, including
three children, a government statement said. A total of at least 45
people have died in rocket attacks in the capital since Saturday.
   The government blames the guerrillas for the attacks. The rebels
have in the past accused the government of attacking its own
capital to throw the blame on them.
</TEXT>
