<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1655EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0641,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Break Down in Advance of Peace Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0698 to restore writethru designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 20th pvs, `Now the ...' to UPDATE with White
House comment. Pickup 21st, `Hun Sen ...' DELETES grafs 22 and 23 `The
conference ... the Cambodians' to TRIM</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   LA CELLE-SAINT-CLOUD, France (AP) _ Cambodian peace talks broke
down Tuesday, five days before an international conference, with an
impasse reported between Prime Minister Hun Sen and the three
factions opposing him.
   Hun Sen refused to combine his Vietnamese-backed government
delegation with resistance representatives at the conference that
begins Sunday, and he refused to agree to participation by the
notorious Khmer Rouge guerrillas in an interim government.
   ``There is no use in meeting again,'' said Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, head of the resistance coalition. ``The disagreement is
total.''
   Hun Sen blamed the Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the guerrilla
factions, for the breakdown in the talks.
   ``We can now ask whether the international conference will open
or not,'' Hun Sen said, adding that the parties were working with
French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas to find a solution.
   ``There are still a few days before the conference and we will
try to find a compromise formula,'' he said.
   The talks at an 18th centry chateau in suburban Paris foundered
mainly on involvement by the Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge, first at
the negotiating table and then in a proposed interim government.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and installed a new
government to end a three-year reign of terror by the Khmer Rouge
in which hundreds of thousands were killed. Hanoi has promised to
finish pulling out its estimated 70,000 troops by the end of
September.
   The Cambodian peace conference is to open Sunday. While no more
top-level meetings were scheduled before then, Hun Sen said he
hoped contacts between the groups would continue.
   The Cambodian prime minister said all issues of agreement
reached during two informal meetings in Jakarta, Indonesia, were
``completely abandoned'' Tuesday. He said the groups were back to
the situation existing a decade ago at the start of the war.
   ``It's like a car that reaches the edge of an abyss and cannot
continue its journey,'' he told a news conference.
   Hun Sen wants two parties representing Cambodia: his government
and Sihanouk's coalition.
   ``To acknowledge that there are two Cambodias is mortal for our
country,'' Sihanouk said. ``We don't want partition.''
   Sihanouk proposed the four parties attend as a single
delegation, a move Hun Sen called ``unacceptable.''
   Under Sihanouk's proposal, the Khmer Rouge would be involved,
but not as a separate entity.
   Hun Sen rejects Khmer Rouge participation in an interim
government, while Sihanouk argues that excluding the most powerful
guerrilla force risks renewed civil war in Cambodia.
   Other points of disagreement were a proposed cease-fire, which
Sihanouk refuses, and the composition of an international
peacekeeping force to monitor the Vietnamese pullout.
   Hun Sen said the final withdrawal will take place Sept. 21-26 by
land, river and sea.
   The breakdown Tuesday came after about four hours of talks
between Hun Sen, Sihanouk, Son Sann, head of the non-communist
Khmer People's National Liberation Front, and Khieu Samphan,
nominal chief of the Khmer Rouge.
   ``Now the problem to resolve is finding a formula to meet at the
international conference,'' said a French Foreign Ministry
spokesman, speaking on condition he not be identified by name. ``We
can always find a formula, maybe not before Sunday.''
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said,
``It's important for the parties to narrow their differences.'' He
said U.S. officials ``will try to help advance that process.''
   Hun Sen stressed his position that the Paris conference must not
be abandoned. ``For our part, we'll try to do everything so that
the conference can take place,'' he said.
   Among the participants lined up for the international
conference, expected to last about a month, are the United States,
Soviet Union, China, France, Britain, Japan, Canada, Vietnam and
the six members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
   Most are to be represented at the opening by their foreign
ministers, with Secretary of State James A. Baker III attending for
the United States.
</TEXT>
