<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     07-25 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Hopes To Settle Contra Situation at Next Week's Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Tuesday
he believes the issue of demobilizing U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels
can be solved at next week's summit meeting of Central American
presidents.
   Ortega also said he will meet with the Nicaragua's political
opposition shortly before the Aug. 5-7 summit in Tela, Honduras.
   ``I have confidence that we can give a definitive answer to this
problem of the Contras (Nicaraguan rebels) during this meeting in
August,'' Ortega said during a news conference at the foreign
correspondents' club in Managua.
   He said dissolving the force of about 11,000 rebels, based in
camps in Honduras, would ``ease the approach to other problems'' in
the region.
   ``While the Contras are in Honduras, the war among Nicaraguans
continues developing,'' Ortega said.
   At a Central American summit conference Feb. 14 in El Salvador,
Ortega promised to move up general elections in Nicaragua to next
Feb. 25 and to adopt rules to ensure the balloting will be fair.
   For their part, the presidents of El Salvador, Honduras,
Guatemala and Costa Rica promised to come up with a plan by May 15
to demobilize the Contras in Honduras, and a summit was scheduled
for that date.
   But the conference was postponed several times before it was set
for August.
   The U.S. Congress in mid-April approved $49 million in
non-lethal aid to the Contras to run until after the Nicaraguan
elections in February.
   Ortega, responding to a reporter's question, said a decision by
the Central American presidents ``to postpone the demobilization of
the Contras until February would be yielding to U.S. pressure, and
it would mean accepting the continuation of the war in Nicaragua.''
   Contra and Sandinista leaders signed a temporary cease-fire in
March 1988, a month after the U.S. Congress decided to discontinue
military aid to the rebels.
   Only sporadic skirmishes have been reported since then.
   Ortega said his Sandinista government has fulfilled all the
promises it made at the El Salvador summit.
   He said it moved up the date for elections, released 1,897
former national guard members, encouraged the Contras to lay down
their weapons and join the political process, allowed the formation
of political parties with minimum requirements, and established a
balanced Supreme Electoral Council to oversee elections. The
imprisoned national guardsmen had served in the regime of President
Anastasio Somoza, which lost a civil war to the Sandinistas in July
1979.
   ``I'm taking this list (of accomplishments) to the meeting in
Honduras,'' Ortega said. ``What's going to be tested is the will of
the governments of Central America and in particular the government
of Honduras.
   ``I have hopes that what will prevail is the will of the
governments of Central America ... above the will of the government
of the United States.''
   Ortega said earlier this month he would meet with the leaders of
Nicaragua's opposition political groups to discuss the electoral
laws adopted by the Sandinista-dominated National Assembly.
   He said Tuesday that the meeting would be held next week, and he
hoped all of Nicaragua's 21 legal parties would participate.
   Opposition leaders say the reformed electoral laws still give
the Sandinistas an unfair advantage and Sandinistas dominate the
Supreme Electoral Council.
   Washington has said it wants to keep the Contras as an intact
force until after the elections to make sure the balloting is free
and fair.
</TEXT>
