<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Dukakis-Book     07-25 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dukakis-Book,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Knew ``I Blew It'' After Debate, New Book Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis knew immediately he had made a
serious error when he responded without emotion to a debate
question about the possibility of his wife being raped and killed.
   ``I blew it,'' Dukakis told an aide as he left the stage after
last October's debate with George Bush, according to a new book
about the 1988 presidential race.
   Dukakis' aides were baffled at his performance, according to the
authors, because he had rehearsed an effective answer to a
soft-on-crime question 13 times during debate preparations.
   The story is recounted in the book by political columnists Jack
Germond and Jules Witcover, titled ``Whose Broad Stripes and Bright
Stars? The Trivial Pursuit of the Presidency 1988.''
   Dukakis' response, widely criticized at the time, was to a
question posed by debate moderator Bernard Shaw of CNN, who asked
if he would favor the death penalty if his own wife, Kitty Dukakis,
were raped and murdered.
   ``No, I don't, Bernard,'' the candidate responded, his voice as
flat as if he were being asked about budget deficits. ``And I think
you know I've opposed the death penalty all of my life. I don't see
any evidence that it's a deterrent, and I think there are better
and more effective ways to deal with violent crime. We've done so
in my own state. ...''
   Dukakis' bloodless answer ``captured the candidate's most
glaring vulnerabilities'' and helped put an end to any chance he
had of defeating Bush, according to the book. It said that as he
walked off the debate stage in Los Angeles, Dukakis said to top
aide John Sasso, ``I blew it.''
   Germond and Witcover write that the three other journalists who
were on the debate panel were told of Shaw's question in advance,
were shocked by it and tried unsuccessfully to talk him into
softening it.
   Advance copies of the book, just published by Warner Books, drew
notice earlier this month for critical comments about Vice
President Dan Quayle that were attributed to Quayle's campaign
aides. President Bush said last week he was offended by Republican
advisers quoted by Germond and Witcover, who called Quayle a
``lightweight'' and described him as having a childlike immaturity.
   The book also describes the Bush campaign's successful focus on
a handful of issues used to create negative feelings among voters
about Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts. Those issues included
Dukakis' veto of a bill requiring students to say the pledge of
allegiance, his support for a law allowing convicted murderers to
be furloughed from prison, and opposition to the death penalty.
   Germond and Witcover said Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater and
media adviser Roger Ailes identified those issues in the spring of
1988 and made plans to use them, despite Bush's later suggestion
that he used them in reaction to intense attacks on him at the
Democratic National Convention in July.
   They quote Ailes as saying, ``It's only a matter of who hits
first and who makes it stick. ... My whole fear was that he
(Dukakis) had bigger negatives on us than we had on him.''
   The book describes Ailes as playing a crucial role in coaching
Bush before a combative, live interview with CBS anchorman Dan
Rather _ a session hailed later by Atwater as a ``defining event''
of the campaign. It said Ailes also suggested Bush's use of
Republican primary opponent Pete DuPont's given first name of
``Pierre'' during a televised debate, a reference that deflated
DuPont's attempt to paint Bush as an elitist.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
