<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-Plane     07-25 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Plane,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angola Says Rebels Shot Down Transport Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday that rebels
shot down a military transport plane, killing 42 of the 48 people
aboard, but the rebels denied it.
   A military official said the Antonov-26 was carrying government
officials and some civilians from Luena to Cazombo in eastern
Moxico province Sunday when a Stinger anti-aircraft missile fired
by UNITA guerrillas hit the left engine.
   He said the twin-engine plane crashed in the bush about 25 miles
west of Cazombo.
   The Washington office of UNITA, the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, issued a statement denying responsibility.
   ``UNITA suspects that a faction of the MPLA (government) not
supportive of the negotiation process is responsible for placing
the blame on UNITA'' it said. ``UNITA remains committed to the
spirit of Gbadolite and will continue to negotiate in good faith.''
   Western diplomats who follow the Angolan situation from Lisbon
said they thought the plane might have been shot down by a UNITA
faction that did not concur with the agreement reached June 22 at
Gbadolite, Zaire.
   ``It looks like the MPLA came out of last week's round of
negotiations well, and some more extreme elements of UNITA could be
trying to up the military pressure to gain more leverage in the
next round,'' one said.
   MPLA stands for Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola,
the Marxist faction that won a civil war after independence from
Portugal in 1975 and has governed Angola since.
   Officials on the Soviet-built plane apparently were bound for
Cazombo as part of a program to explain the truce, the military
informant said.
   Angola's government and the rebels accuse each other of
violating a cease-fire that began two days after the agreement and
lasted only a week.
   The Portuguese news agency Lusa said a woman and a 15-year-old
were among the six survivors of the crash and that the municipal
commissioner of Cazombo was killed.
   It quoted an Angolan military source, not identified, as saying:
``This is more than a cease-fire violation.'' It said reports of
UNITA actions had increased over the weekend.
   Antonov-26 aircraft often are used to transport government
soldiers around Angola, which is twice the size of France.
   Lusa quoted the military source as saying increased rebel
activity might cause the government to postpone the next round of
talks, scheduled for Monday in Zaire.
   Angop, the official Angolan news agency, said rebels attacked
and occupied Quimbele and Cuimba, towns in northern Uige province
near Zaire, last Sunday.
   The military official said UNITA forces ambushed vehicles Monday
in Lunda South province, killing 16 people, and fired mortars at
Kuito, capital of Bie province, killing two or three people.
   Quimbele has been considered a possible northern base for UNITA,
which has a southern stronghold at Jamba.
</TEXT>
