<FIRST>u w AM-VietnamIdentification 1stLd-Writethru a0601 07-25 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam Identification, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says Experts to Go to Hanoi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with mission and more remains to come back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teams of experts will go to Hanoi next
week to work with the Vietnamese in seeking more information about
Americans missing in Vietnam for more than a decade, the Pentagon
announced Tuesday.
   The mission, the seventh to be held, will be made up of members
of the Joint Casualty Resolution Center and the U.S. Army Central
Identification Laboratory, Hawaii. Those groups will work with the
Vietnamese Office for Seeking Missing Persons.
   More than 2,300 American servicemen are listed as missing in
action in Indochina, including more than 1,700 in Vietnam.
   The Pentagon also said the Vietnamese government informed the
United States it would return the remains of 15 people ``which may
be those of Americans'' next week.
   ``These remains were previously reviewed by U.S. and Vietnamese
forensic experts,'' a Pentagon statement said. ``Arrangements have
been ... for subsequent evaluation in an attempt to establish
individual identification.''
   Earlier Tuesday, the Pentagon said the government had identified
the remains of an American serviceman whose body was shipped home
from Vietnam last December.
   The body of Air Force Capt. Albert E. Rodriguez of
Franklinville, N.Y., was among the remains of 38 servicemen sent to
the United States by the Vietnamese. Since December, 25 of them
have been identified and investigations continued on the others.
   Rodriguez had been missing since March 11, 1968.
   ``The U.S. government recognizes and appreciates the increased
efforts of the Vietnamese government which resulted in accounting
for this American,'' the Pentagon said in a statement.
</TEXT>
