<DOCNO> AP890725-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1952EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SpendingBills     07-25 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bills,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Committees Approve Six Appropriations Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional committees approved six bills
Tuesday providing money in the next fiscal year for federal efforts
ranging from AIDS research to enhanced security at Vice President
Dan Quayle's mansion.
   The House Appropriations Committee approved an $18.4 billion
measure for the Treasury, Postal Service and a slew of other
agencies, a $155.2 billion bill for the departments of Health and
Human Services, Labor and Education and a $5.8 billion package for
the departments of commerce, justice, state and the federal
judiciary.
   Across the Capitol, the Senate Appropriations Committee passed
bills containing $44 billion for agriculture programs, $18 billion
for energy and water projects and $10.5 billion for the Interior
Department and for federal cultural programs.
   All six bills, covering operations for fiscal 1990, were
approved on voice votes.
   The day's work was emblematic of lawmakers' stepped-up pace as
they race to complete as much budget business as they can before
their four-week summer recess begins Aug. 5. The 1990 federal
fiscal year begins Oct. 1, and Congress will have only four weeks
of work left until then when it returns in September.
   So far, the full House has approved five of the 13 annual
appropriations bills needed to keep the government functioning,
while the Senate has yet to approve any.
   The treasury-postal service legislation provides $2.3 billion
more than this year's spending level, and just $6 million more than
President Bush sought in the budget he submitted to Congress in
February.
   It contains $2.1 million for security improvements at the vice
president's official residence in Washington.
   On a 29-26 party-line vote, Republicans added an amendment
prohibiting enforcement of Section 89, a provision of the tax code
that forces companies to offer health plans to lower-paid employees
that are equivalent to those given to executives. Businesses have
complained that the law is costly and time-consuming for them.
   The labor-health measure boosts job-training spending by $238
million over this year to nearly $4 billion; builds AIDS spending
by 25 percent to $1.6 billion; devotes $1.6 billion for drug
counseling and education efforts; and provides $180 million for the
homeless, $102 million more than this year.
   The commerce-justice measure would provide $50 million for
reparations to Japanese-Americans who were interred during World
War II. The bill originally contained $20 million for the payments,
but $30 million more was transferred for the fund on a voice vote
from the amount slated to go to the Census Bureau. Under the 1988
law that authorized $1.2 billion in payments to the surviving, $500
million was to be paid next year, but lawmakers cited budget
constraints.
   The agriculture bill increases spending on child nutrition
programs from $498 million in 1989 to $715 million, and ignores a
Bush proposal to cut the agricultural extension service and instead
raises it from $361 million this year to $367 million.
   The energy and water measure provides $225 million for the
superconducting super collider, the research-oriented atom smasher
that the government plans to build in Texas for a total cost of
about $6 billion. The amount is $25 million more than the House has
already voted for. Of the total, $135 million would be to begin
construction and $90 million would be for research and development.
   The bill also includes $9.6 billion for nuclear energy defense
activities and $4.2 billion for water projects.
   The interior legislation increases the National Park Service's
coffers from $734 million this year to $771 million, and holds the
National Endowment for the Arts to $143 million, about $1 million
more than this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
