<FIRST>u w AM-US-Lebanon     07-25 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Lebanon,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Approves Funds For Lebanon; Rejects Warship Escort For Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration announced Tuesday it
would give $2 million in emergency aid to Lebanon but rejected
suggestions that it send naval vessels to protect supply shipments
against the possibility of Syrian attack.
   The emergency assistance was approved by President Bush at the
request of the International Committee for the Red Cross to provide
food and medical supplies for victims of the country's 15-year
civil war.
   The United States is also providing $14 million worth of food
through voluntary organizations to feed about 400,000 Lebanese
affected by the fighting, which is pitting Iraqi-backed Christian
troops against Syrian-backed Moslem and Druse militias.
   Details of the U.S. aid were released by Assistant Secretary of
State for Middle Eastern affairs John Kelly to the House
Subcommittee on Europe and the Middle East.
   Kelly outlined the administration's Lebanon policy after
witnesses from private Lebanese-American organizations described
acute shortages of food and fuel triggered by the civil war's worst
round of fighting which began last March.
   He denied contentions by some of the witnesses that U.S. food
supplies were being diverted by Syrian troops who have mounted a
naval blockade of Christian-controlled ports along the
Mediterranean coast, in retaliation for a Christian blockade of
Moslem-controlled ports.
   In response to a question from the panel's chairman, Rep. Lee
Hamilton, D-Ind., whether the administration had considered an
armed naval escort of the supply ships, Kelly said:
   ``I doubt very seriously that there would be much support in the
Congress for the active involvement of U.S. warships in attempting
to break this blockade. I think this blockade can be eliminated
through persuasion and diplomacy.''
   The thrust of U.S. policy is to lobby in the Arab world,
including in communications with Syria and Iraq, for acceptance of
an Arab League initiative to bring about a ceasefire and a lifting
of the blockades, Kelly said. The six-week effort has failed to
yield results, he conceded.
   ``We are waiting for an Arab League decision, an Arab League
action. There is no U.S. initiative, there is no U.S. separate
plan. These are the people who have a realistic chance of solving
the problem there,'' Kelly said.
</TEXT>
