<FIRST>u w AM-Iran-Contra     07-25 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walsh Decries ``Piecemeal'' Appeals in Fernandez Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The independent counsel in the Iran-Contra
investigation said Tuesday the Justice Department is jeopardizing
the case against a former CIA station chief by making ``piecemeal''
appeals that have delayed the trial.
   In a strongly worded letter to the Justice Department, Lawrence
Walsh also suggested that the CIA is raising unjustified concerns
that scuttled Monday's scheduled starting date in the trial of
Joseph Fernandez.
   The spy agency objects to plans by Fernandez's lawyers to
identify two CIA stations and one CIA facility in Latin America.
   The Justice Department, acting on the CIA's concerns, won a
temporary stay of the trial from a federal appeals court judge in
Richmond, Va.
   ``CIA stations exist in Latin American countries,'' Walsh said
in a letter to the Justice Department. ``This is a well-known fact.
   ``The attorney general must decide whether it is so necessary to
preserve an artificial deniability that he should block the
prosecution of a high-ranking CIA officer,'' Walsh's letter said.
   Walsh said the prospect that such information would be disclosed
by Fernandez at his trial doesn't warrant the Justice Department's
filing of a national security affidavit. Such an affidavit would
bar use of the information in Fernandez's trial and could kill the
case.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, unwilling so far to take the
drastic step of filing an affidavit, instead sought the stay from
the appeals court.
   The independent counsel's office ``is generally unwilling to
interrupt trials in order to take piecemeal ... appeals'' on
matters concerning classified information, said Walsh's letter to
acting deputy attorney general Edward Dennis.
   Walsh said the Justice Department's actions ``inevitably disrupt
the trial, alienate'' the U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va.,
where the Fernandez trial is supposed to take place ``and
jeopardize a successful prosecution.''
   The prosecutor called on the Justice Department to file the
affidavit. Walsh's office could then appeal any rulings regarding
the affidavit.
   Walsh was responding to a letter earlier in the day from Dennis.
   In it, Dennis said Walsh's suggestion that an affidavit be filed
``is premature, and needlessly imperils not only the government's
ability to challenge erroneous rulings relating to classified
information but also the future viability of your prosecution.''
   Dennis said that the prosecutor's office should have appealed
Monday's ruling by U.S. District Court Judge Claude Hilton, who is
presiding in the Fernandez case.
   Hilton rejected proposals by the government to substitute
numbers for the identities of the CIA stations and facilities in
Latin America and to abandon most of one criminal charge against
Fernandez in exchange for dropping references in open court to
three highly sensitive CIA programs.
   Fernandez, the agency's former station chief in Costa Rica, is
accused of four criminal charges focusing on his alleged lies to
Iran-Contra investigators about his assistance to Oliver North's
resupply network for the Nicaraguan rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
