<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Jobs     07-25 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Jobs,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Lauds Achievements of Youths Helped by Jobs Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday lauded the
achievements of a group of young people from poor backgrounds who
succeeded with help from a jobs program the administration wants to
reauthorize and strengthen.
   ``Since 1983 the Job Training Partnership Act has propelled
America's engine, providing education and training for those
lacking in basic skills, or who are economically disadvantaged,''
the president said in a Rose Garden ceremony.
   He presented achievement awards to 12 young adults who had
limited education and skills, and were from economically depressed
home situations. All of them gained training, instruction or
education through the JTPA, a program that provides federal funds
to assist local governments and private industry in giving job
training and employment for such young people as well as dislocated
workers.
   The $2.4 billion jobs program was co-authored by Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., and Vice President Dan Quayle, who as a
Republican senator from Indiana claimed the jobs program as his
chief legislative achievement.
   The program has been criticized for achieving more quick job
placement for those with limited skllls who can be trained quickly,
rather than more complete training for the most needy and unskilled
and directing them into careers.
   To shift the program's focus, the administration is proposing
that instead of spending most of the money on the unemployed, who
might not be unskilled, the focus will shift more to the percentage
of unskilled poor.
   ``There's a general consensus that we can improve this to help
redirect the focus to help those most in need,'' said White House
spokesman Steve Hart.
   The proposed revisions are being considered along with
reauthorization for the jobs program.
   The outstanding achievement awards were instigated by the
Department of Labor to commend those who complete training through
the program and succeed at jobs.
   One of the women honored Tuesday, Purtillia Bryant, 21,
recounted how she had come from a broken home in North Carolina to
Washington. She said she could not get a job and had few skills
from her high school education. ``I was angry about my situation
and had no self-confidence and felt rejected,'' she said.
   She was referred to a Washington program funded by the JTPA, the
Opportunities Industrialization Center, where she has improved her
typing and studied computer science, English and math. She is
working as a Navy clerk-typist and at night for a car rental agency
to save money for college and to eventually go into the computer
technology field.
   Her story shows, Bush said, ``how tomorrow can be brighter than
today.''
   Examples of the efforts the jobs program funds are summer youth
programs and aid for workers laid off by plant closings.
   The administration is proposing to amend the program targeting
the aid to the most needy applicants.
   The amendments are similar to changes that were proposed by
Democrats.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., who is chairman of the Senate panel
that oversees the JTPA, has proposed several revisions saying,
``The vehicle is sound, but some of our neediest citizens have been
left behind.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
