<FIRST>u a AM-Nissan-UAW     07-25 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nissan-UAW,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan, UAW Step Up Campaigns On Eve Of Union Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Company and union leaders made last-minute
campaign pushes Tuesday on the eve of a vote to decide whether
Nissan will be the first Japanese car plant organized by the United
Auto Workers.
   About 2,400 workers at the plant south of Nashville were to
begin voting Wednesday to determine whether the UAW will represent
Nissan Motor Manufacturing Co. U.S.A. employees.
   Nissan claimed by closed-circuit television within the plant
that UAW representation could mean a loss of benefits, while the
union used radio commercials to hammer away at its theme of plant
safety.
   Labor observers say the election could be a make-or-break
situation for the UAW, which has yet to gain a foothold at any
major Japanese plants in the United States, except those affiliated
with American automakers.
   Three years ago, the union lost badly in an effort to organize
the Honda Motor Co. plant in Marysville, Ohio.
   Only 13.5 percent of Tennessee's manufacturing work force is
unionized, and UAW membership has declined 33 percent over the past
decade.
   UAW spokesman Maxey Irwin said Tuesday that the election's
importance has been blown out of proportion.
   ``The significance to us has to do with the problems that Nissan
employees have. They're suffering a very brutal (assembly) line
speed and high injury rate,'' Irwin said.
   ``As far as the national significance, I fail to understand
exactly how a win or a loss for the UAW in Smyrna, Tenn., will
affect an organizing drive in Salina, Kan., or Tyler, Texas, or
Eugene, Ore.''
   The company has disputed the union's claim of safety problems,
although it drew a $5,000 fine from Tennessee authorities for
refusing to show its injury log to a group of workers. The fine is
now under appeal.
   Nissan's in-plant video messages blamed the union for layoffs at
General Motors, and they promised tough bargaining sessions if the
UAW wins.
   ``The next thing that would happen if the union won is that the
company would start dealing with the union and not you about what
your wages, benefits and working conditions would be,'' said an
audio copy of one tape obtained by the Nashville Banner.
   The tape said employees should be concerned about strikes, and
that a strike could hurt workers more than Nissan. Television
reports of strike violence and unsuccessful strikes are included in
the videotape, which the UAW said has not been shown to suspected
union supporters.
   ``This tape is a use of threats to intimidate employees into
voting no,'' said Frank Joyce, union spokesman.
   ``The idea that somehow Nissan is currently in a bargaining
relationship on an individual basis with workers is pretty
absurd,'' Joyce said. ``Nissan employees do not set their own
wages, benefits or working conditions.
   ``If they want to declare in advance that they will be hard to
bargain with, we're used to that.''
   Nissan officials declined to comment on the tape Tuesday.
</TEXT>
