<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1956EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett-Drugs     07-25 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Drugs,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Will be Encouraged to Impose Stiff Drug Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett, who is devising an
anti-drug strategy for the nation, said Tuesday that ``carrots and
sticks'' will be used to encourage states to impose stiff drug
policies.
   ``There will be some carrots and some sticks,'' Bennett, the
director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy, told
reporters at a luncheon.
   ``We will expect states to do certain things if they want
federal funds,'' he said. ``We will expect educational institutions
to finally do certain things if they want education funds.''
   Bennett would not say exactly what the states will be required
to do to keep federal money under the drug strategy that is due
Sept. 5. A draft of the plan is being reviewed by various agencies,
including the National Security Council, he said.
   The focus of the national drug control strategy would be crack,
a cheap and highly addictive form of cocaine, said Bennett.
   ``That's not to say the other drugs aren't important and serious
... but the clearest, most immediate danger to the largest number
of people comes from crack,'' he said.
   ``It's crack that is responsible for the disorder in many of our
cities. It's crack which is endangering the lives of so many
innocent civilians because of the tendency for violence. It's crack
which is appearing with terrible frequency as the drug sought out
by pregnant addicts.''
   While people seem to be turning away from many other drugs, he
said, ``That is not the case with crack. Crack, from all evidence,
is getting worse.''
   Bennett said the strategy will not include any recommendation on
semiautomatic assault-style weapons.
   ``As you know,'' he said, ``the president asked me to think
about that, give him my advice about it. I did that some time ago,
and my advice is between me and the president.''
   In March, at Bennett's urging, the Treasury Department suspended
the import of dozens of styles of the firearms. The department's
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms earlier this month made the
ban permanent for 43 styles, including the popular Chinese-made
AK-47 and the Israeli-made Uzi carbine.
   Last week, Bennett urged the American Legislative Exchange
Council, a gathering of state legislators, to take a number of
steps to combat drug abuse in their home states.
   Specifically, he called on them to ensure certain and prompt
punishment of those convicted of using or trafficking in drugs,
action that will require the states to hire more police, judges and
prosecutors and to build new prisons.
   The legislators, he said, must make sure there are minimum
mandatory sentences for drug trafficking, harsh sentences for
anyone caught selling drugs to children or using children to sell
drugs and hold both casual and heavy drug users accountable for
their drug use, including civil fines of up to $10,000 for those
convicted of possession of small amounts of drugs.
   The states also should employ asset forfeiture laws and should
make parole and probation contingent on frequent, mandatory drug
tests, he said. In addition, they must support sound treatment
programs and demand accountability from the treatment programs to
ensure that they work
   States also, Bennett said, must insist that public employers
take personnel action against employees caught using drugs or under
the influence of drugs while on the job.
   Bennett did not indicate Tuesday which of these steps states
must take to keep federal funds flowing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
