<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     07-25 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians, Christians Clash Across Green Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces exchanged
machine-gun fire across Beirut's dividing Green Line Tuesday during
a lull in artillery battles, and civilians fearing new bombardments
reinforced their shelters.
   Police said a woman was wounded by sniper fire in the Ein
Rummaneh district of Christian east Beirut.
   That raised the casualty toll after 19 weeks of fighting to 453
killed and 1,860 wounded.
   The crackle of machine-gun fire echoing through the capital's
deserted streets kept tension high.
   Families who have not fled the ferocious shelling by both sides
prepared for a new outbreak of heavy artillery exchanges.
   ``I want to be ready when the shelling starts again,'' said
Sunni Moslem gift shop owner Bassem Itani as he filled plastic bags
with sand in the Sanayeh neighborhood of Moslem west Beirut.
   ``Most of the people around here have left. I've no place to go
except my apartment here. My wife and I have decided to stay,'' he
said.
   Itani said the underground shelter in his building was ``well
equipped to protect us. But I'm fortifying the ventilation holes
with sand bags to protect us from shrapnel.''
   Beirut remained a ghost town Tuesday. An estimated 250,000 of
its 1.5 million residents have fled in recent days during ferocious
artillery duels between the Christians and Syrians, who support
Lebanon's Moslem factions.
   Police estimate that 700,000 people from both sectors have fled
since March, when the fighting between the forces led by Christian
leader Gen. Michel Aoun and the Syrian army broke out.
   The usually crowded beaches along the Moslem sector's seaside
boulevard were empty. Elsewhere, frightened Beirut citizens traded
rumors about when the feared artillery battles will resume.
   The Moslem-run Voice of the Nation radio sought to dampen the
fears, saying the rumors were ``baseless and speculative.''
   One of the most common rumors said Aoun set a Tuesday deadline
to resume shelling attacks against the Syrians if a three-member
Arab League mediating committee failed to produce a settlement to
the conflict.
   A spokesman for Aoun denied reports of a deadline.
   ``The general has confidence in the Arab summit committee and in
its sincere efforts to contain the deterioration,'' the spokesman
said on condition of anonymity. He refused to elaborate.
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia, King Hassan II of Morocco and
President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria were charged by an Arab
summit May 26 with finding a settlement to Lebanon's 14-year-old
civil war by November.
   But so far they have not even been able to enforce a cease-fire
called in May.
   Saudi Information Minister Ali al-Shaer told reporters in Jiddah
that Fahd has appealed for all parties in Lebanon to stop fighting
to give peace efforts a chance.
   ``The Arab League committee on Lebanon is doing its utmost to
save the country, but this will not be achieved unless all parties
concerned show their goodwill and sincere cooperation to achieve
peace,'' Shaer quoted the monarch as telling a weekly cabinet
meeting in Jiddah.
   The fighting broke out March 8, two days after Aoun blockaded
illegal ports run by Syrian-backed Moslem militias south of Beirut
in an attempt to restore long-eroded government authority.
   The Syrians and their Moslem allies retaliated by besieging and
shelling the 310-square-mile Christian enclave, home to 1 million
people.
   The Syrians _ who have 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976
Arab League peacekeeping mandate _ and their allies outnumber
Aoun's estimated 20,000 men by about 3-1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
