<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-PLO     07-25 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-PLO,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Gives Assurances He Will Observe Limits On PLO Contacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush gave assurances Tuesday that
Senate restrictions on U.S. contacts with the Palestine Liberation
Organization ``will be taken into account'' as the United States
pursues its dialogue with Yasser Arafat's group.
   But he also emphasized that he considers the restrictions to be
unconstitutional and an infringement on his conduct of U.S.
diplomacy.
   Bush did not explicitly rule out U.S. meetings with Salah
Khalaf, who is second-in-command to PLO chairman Arafat, or other
officials suspected of either plotting or carrying out terrorist
acts against Americans.
   Concern over U.S. dealings with Arafat's aide, known also as Abu
Iyad, prompted the Senate to approve an amendment last week
restricting U.S. contacts with the PLO. Abu Iyad is suspected of
masterminding the murder of 11 Israeli athletes at the Munich
Olympics in 1972 and the slaying of two American diplomats in the
Sudan in 1973.
   The amendment was watered down before its 97-1 passage to ease
requirements for Bush to report to Congress and to scrap a
prohibition on talking to ``accomplices'' in terrorism.
   The lone dissenter was Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who wanted to
tighten the restrictions.
   The State Department, in an unusual move, announced Bush's
position in a statement by spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler. It was
issued after Secretary of State James A. Baker III had talked to
the president and to several senators.
   ``The president strongly believes that legislation that tries to
restrict or manage the conduct of diplomacy is an infringement on
presidential prerogatives and is unconstitutional,'' the statement
said.
   ``While we will continue to view the PLO amendment to the State
Authorization Bill and provisions like it as unconstitutional, he
acknowledges the widespread sentiment in the Congress that produced
this legislation.
   ``Members of Congress should know that this sentiment and
concern will be taken into account as we pursue our policy.''
   The statement also said ``unnamed sources who suggest otherwise
do not speak for the administration.''
   A report Saturday in The Washington Post said administration
officials had refused to bar further meetings with Salah Khalaf.
The newspaper quoted an unidentified department official as saying
the legislation ``doesn't rule out anything.''
   The United States broke its diplomatic isolation of the PLO last
December after Arafat, at the urging of the State Department,
publicly renounced terrorism and said he accepted Israel's right to
exist.
   Several meetings have been held since then in Tunisia. The most
recent sought to weaken PLO resistance to an Israeli plan to hold
elections on the West Bank and in Gaza to chose Palestinians for
negotiations.
   The PLO opposes the plan as a ploy to prevent a Palestinian
state. There is no indication Arafat's group has changed its mind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
