<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-25 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Pop Up From Rockies To Atlantic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developing in warm and humid air were widely
scattered Tuesday from the Rockies to the Atlantic and from the
Great Lakes to the Gulf of Mexico.
   Showers and thunderstorms were most numerous along the Gulf
Coast, from eastern New Mexico to central Kansas, from eastern
Arkansas to Upper Michigan, and from South Carolina to Ohio.
   Thunderstorms east of Albuquerque, N.M., produced three-quarters
of an inch of rain in 45 minutes, the National Weather Service
said. A thunderstorm in southwestern Lower Michigan produced more
than half an inch of rain in the Battle Creek area in 45 minutes,
it said.
   Thunderstorms developing over the middle Atlantic Coast region
moved slowly with the potential for heavy rain on land already
saturated by heavy rain during the past couple of weeks.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered over
Utah and Arizona.
   Temperatures rose to a record 90 degrees at Marquette, Mich.,
and 91 at Portland, Maine.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Monterey, Calif., to 108 at Needles, Calif. Tuesday
morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 32 at Burney, Calif.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from Arizona and the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah through
the southern Plains to the Atlantic Coast states.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast; in the
lower 90s from the eastern two-thirds of Texas to the Atlantic
Coast states and across much of the West; near 100 in southern
Idaho; and above 100 in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
