<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2006EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mauritania-Senegal     07-25 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mauritania-Senegal,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mauritania Rejects Charges By Senegal, Amnesty International</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday rejected
Senegal's accusations that Mauritania is deporting its own black
minority and accused its southern neighbor of refusing to accept
Senegalese sent home from Mauritania.
   In a letter to the U.N. Security Council, Mauritania also
accused Senegal of ``the execution of a premeditated plan against
Mauritania and against Mauritanians living in Senegal whose goods
have been pillaged and who have been victims of massacres and
bodily harm of all kinds.''
   Senegal wrote to the Security Council on Thursday setting out
its charges but not seeking immediate council action.
   Tension between the West African neighbors erupted last April
after a clash along their shared river border. Violence broke out
in both capitals against nationals of the other country. Officials
estimate between 250 to more than 400 people were killed.
   Mauritania's information minister, Mohamed Lemine Ould Ahmed,
issued a separate statement Tuesday denying related allegations by
the human rights organization Amnesty International of torture,
killings and arbitrary arrests by Mauritanian security forces.
   ``Amnesty International accuses us of certain deeds which, in
reality, are the crimes which Senegal has committed and continues
to commit against Mauritanian citizens,'' he said.
   He urged the London-based group to ``concern itself instead with
the situation of thousands of Mauritanians still held hostage in
Senegal in inhuman conditions.''
   Each government blames the other for the violence and for not
protecting the goods and lives of each others' citizens.
   About 20 percent of Mauritania's 2 million people are black,
with the rest mainly Arabs and Berbers. Senegal's population of 6.7
million is almost entirely black.
   After the worst of the violence subsided, Senegal reported black
Mauritanians were arriving in large numbers after being deported
from their native country.
   ``In just a few weeks, the operation in question has affected
some 26,000 individuals, who have been driven from their own
country solely by reason of their ethnic origin and been deported
to Senegal, arriving completely stripped of their property,''
Medoune Fall, Senegal's acting foreign minister, wrote last week in
the letter to the Security Council.
   In reply Tuesday, Mauritania accused Senegal of ``refusing to
accept their own nationals repatriated from Mauritania under the
fallacious pretext that they are Negro-African Mauritanians,
against all the evidence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2008EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-WhoIsaJew     07-25 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Who Is a Jew,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader of US Orthodox Rabbis Condemns Israeli Court Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of Orthodox rabbis from the United
States said Tuesday an Israeli Supreme Court ruling that
non-Orthodox conversions to Judaism are valid was ``a travesty''
that would increase divisions among Jews.
   Members of the Israeli parliament from religious parties
threatened to renew demands for a ``Who is a Jew'' amendment.
   Reform and Conservative leaders, who note that their liberal
branches of Judaism have attracted more adherents in the United
States, described the court ruling as a victory.
   Interior Minister Aryeh Deri said he would issue citizenship
papers as ordered by the court, but would withhold his signature.
   Deri ordered his ministry to produce special stickers for new
identity cards saying information in the ``nationality'' and
``personal status'' sections could not be admitted as evidence by
the Orthodox rabbinical authorities.
   Secular legislators protested his action as a challenge to the
rule of law.
   In a 4-1 decision Monday, a Supreme Court panel upheld current
Israeli law and ordered the Interior Ministry to recognize as Jews
and give citizenship papers to a group of converts from the United
States, Brazil and Argentina.
   Before the court ruling, Deri had refused to issue papers until
Orthodox rabbis had validated the certificates of immigrants
converted by Reform or Conservative rabbis.
   Harry Horowitz, an aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said
Shamir had encouraged talks among rabbis of the three persuasions
toward a compromise conversion formula that would resolve the ``Who
is a Jew'' controversy.
   ``The prime minister wants these discussions to go on so that
these matter will no longer continue to divide or agitate the
Jewish people,'' Horowitz said in an interview.
   Rabbi Max N. Schreier, an Orthodox rabbi from New York, told a
news conference recognizing non-Orthodox converts ``is a travesty.
The fact that a judicial body recognizes something that goes
against the essence of Jewish law is a very disturbing matter.''
   Schreier is president of the Rabbinical Assembly of America,
which represents about 1.5 million Jews.
   The ``Who is a Jew'' argument stems from Orthodox demands that
converts by Reform and Conservative rabbis be excluded from
automatic Israeli citizenship. The Orthodox argue that such
conversions are invalid because they do not strictly conform to
Halacha, or ancient Jewish law.
   Avraham Verdiger, a legislator from Agudat Israel, said his
ultra-Orthodox party might withdraw support from Shamir's
government, which could disturb the balance between the prime
minister's right-wing Likud bloc and the Labor Party, its
center-left coalition partner. Agudat Israel has five seats in the
120-member Knesset.
   Verdiger also said his party would renew its campaign for a
``Who is a Jew'' amendment that would change Israel's Law of Return
and grant automatic citizenship only to Jews converted according to
Halacha _ effectively only to Orthodox converts. The Knesset has
defeated about a dozen such measures.
   Israeli law now defines a Jew as a person who was born of a
Jewish mother or who has converted and does not profess another
faith.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
