<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0661 07-25 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Supporter Describes Meeting With Shamir</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 17-end, `Tarifi said...on Monday' with 12 grafs to
UPDATE casualties, names of other Palestinians and PFLP threat. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-PLO Palestinian lawyer
said Tuesday he had talks with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir,
fueling speculation Israel's government is breaking its own ban on
contact with the outlawed group.
   Lawyer Jamil Tarifi said he was invited to meet Shmuel Goren,
government coordinator for the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
and was taken without advance notice to Shamir's office.
   The meeting occurred ``several days ago,'' Tarifi said,
declining to give the date.
   His name was among those of four Palestinians leaked in Israel
and made public by the Palestine Liberation Organization in Tunis
as having held secret talks with Shamir. The others have denied any
contact.
   When reports first surfaced Monday, Shamir spokesman Avi Pazner
insisted the premier held several meetings only with ``non-PLO
Palestinians.''
   Asked about Tarifi's statements, Pazner said: ``The prime
minister reserves to himself the right not to reveal with whom he
met, neither the content of the talks and especially what the
Palestinian participants said.''
   He added: ``I want to stress what Tarifi says himself, that he
did not get any green light from the PLO and that he is not a PLO
member.''
   But leftist legislator Yossi Sarid told Israel radio Tarifi was
forbidden to run for mayor of Ramallah's El-Bireh suburb because he
was a member of PLO chief Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction.
Tarifi was El-Bireh's deputy mayor from 1976 to 1982.
   At the news conference at his home in Ramallah, the 42-year-old
lawyer described himself as ``a PLO supporter, of course'' but
declined to say whether he has direct contact with PLO leaders.
   But he added, ``Nothing happens in the occupied territories
without the knowledge of the PLO. It is the leadership of the
people.''
   Tarifi's disclosure could further fuel a feud in Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc.
   Earlier this month, Likud hard-liners forced Shamir to accept
conditions for his peace initiative, ruling out many possible
concessions to the Palestinians.
   After the left-leaning Labor party threatened to leave the
governing coalition, Shamir backed off and reaffirmed the original
plan.
   Arafat himself was quoted Monday as saying Israel's government
has opened direct contacts with his group over the peace plan.
   Shamir's plan calls for elections in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip to select Palestinians to open talks with Israel on an
interim settlement to calm the 19-month Palestinian uprising.
   In the latest uprising casualty Tuesday, Arab hospital officials
and the army said 20-year-old Fawsi Mohammed Elidawil died of
gunshot wounds suffered a day earlier, bringing to 520 the toll of
Palestinians killed in clashes with Israelis during the revolt.
Thirty-eight Israelis also have been killed.
   Arab hospital officials said at least 18 Palestinians were shot
and wounded in clashes in the West Bank and Gaza Strip Tuesday.
   In Gaza City, 70-year-old Fatma Mohammed Badwan died of a heart
attack suffered when Israeli soldiers broke into her house in
search of stone-throwers early Tuesday, the hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed the circumstances of the death and said a
military doctor tried to revive the woman.
   The Hebrew daily Maariv on Tuesday quoted Shamir as expressing
fear that disclosure of his meeting with Tarifi could damage
efforts to speak with other Palestinians who ``would be afraid for
their lives.'' Maariv reported Monday that Shamir and Tarifi had
met.
   The other Palestinians named in the Tunis report are Jerusalem
journalist Mahmoud Abu Zuluf, Gaza businessman Mansour Al-Shawwa
and West Bank pharmacist Ezziddin Al-Aryan.
   All are known supporters of the PLO, and Al-Aryan is a member of
the Palestine National Council, the PLO parliament.
   Tarifi said he did not know why PLO officials in Tunis had
published the names of the Palestinians who had held talks with
Shamir.
   Nablus businessman Said Kennaan said Tuesday that the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, an extremist PLO faction led
by George Habash, has warned supporters of Arafat's Fatah wing not
to meet with Israeli officials, Israel TV reported.
   It did not elaborate, and Kennaan could not be reached for
comment.
   Tarifi said Shamir urged Palestinians to accept his elections
plan, even if it did not make clear what the final status of the
territories would be and the PLO has called for ``linkage'' to an
independent state.
   Tarifi also said he told Shamir to deal with the PLO.
   ``The PLO will accept it (the plan) or it will not be acceptable
to the Palestinian people,'' he said he told Shamir.
</TEXT>
