<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-FetalTissue     07-25 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Fetal Tissue,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goverment Minister Issues Code for Fetal Tissue Transplants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Secretary David Mellor said Tuesday he had
approved a code of practice for using fetal tissue in brain cell
transplants and research.
   The guidelines, drafted by doctors, lawyers and moral
philosophers, forbid inducements to pregnant women to have
abortions or to schedule them for the convenience of tissue
transplant teams.
   Only isolated brain cells or fragments of tissue may be used, to
prevent the transfer of personality characteristics between donor
and recipient, the code says.
   Mellor told the House of Commons the government would begin
discussions with medical organizations on establishing a commission
or agency to control the movement of fetal tissue.
   That was suggested in a report that set out the guidelines and
was prepared by a committee under the leadership of the Rev. Dr.
John Polkinghorne, dean of Trinity Hall at Cambridge University.
The committtee was appointed in June 1988 after doctors in
Birmingham announced Britain's first brain cell transplants using
fetal tissue.
   Professor Edward Hitchcock, head of the team, said the
operations had helped patients suffering from Parkinson's disease,
a progressive brain disorder. Members of Hitchcock's team are said
to have performed at least 17 such operations.
   They welcomed the Polkinghorne report, as did Dr. Vivienne
Nathanson, secretary of the ethics committee of the British Medical
Association, which represents most of Britain's 97,000 doctors.
   ``We believe it is important that new techniques are properly
controlled, publicly debated and regularly reviewed,'' she said.
   The Polkinghorne report said fetal tissue may be used in
research and treatment as long as a woman's decision to have an
abortion is clearly separated from any decision to use the tissue.
   It said the Health Department should establish an organization
to control the movement of fetal tissue and eliminate contact
between abortion clinics and institutions where the tissue is used.
   ``There should be no monetary exchange for fetuses or fetal
tissue,'' it said. ``Profit from any dealing in fetal tissue is
unethical.''
   The report proposed that all new research or therapy involving
the fetus or fetal tissue be approved by an ethics committee.
</TEXT>
