<FIRST>r a AM-Wedtech-Wallach     07-25 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wedtech-Wallach,0459</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Prosecutor Uses Closing Arguments to Attack Credibility of Ed Meese
^By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese III was
``at best incompetent and at worst corrupt,'' a prosecutor said
Tuesday at the racketeering trial of Meese's longtime friend, E.
Robert Wallach.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Elliot B. Jacobson attacked the
credibility of Meese, who testified for Wallach, in his closing
arguments after 2{ months of trial.
   Jacobson cited an internal Justice Department review that
faulted Meese for his efforts to help Wallach in an ill-fated,
Mideast oil pipeline proposal and to assist him with the Wedtech
Corp., a now-defunct defense contractor.
   Wallach, a San Francisco personal injury lawyer, was charged in
a 21-count racketeering indictment with extracting almost $2
million in illegal payoffs and payments from Wedtech, including
some $525,000 in alleged bribes to Wallach to influence Meese and
other government officials.
   The other defendants are W. Franklyn Chinn, 47, a former Wedtech
board member and onetime Meese financial adviser, and a business
associate of theirs, R. Kent London.
   Meese testified that Wallach never asked him to give
preferential treatment to Wedtech.
   Wedtech, once a small machine shop, grew into a $100 million
government contractor through a special Small Business
Administration program that set aside contracts without competitive
bidding for minority-controlled companies.
   Evidence at earlier trials has shown that Wedtech continued to
receive the no-bid contracts through a series of bribe schemes even
after it ceased to be a minority-owned company.
   The Wedtech investigation did not result in any criminal charges
against Meese, but Jacobson said: ``As counsel to the president and
as attorney general, Edwin Meese III was at best incompetent and at
worst corrupt.''
   Jacobson said Meese used his testimony as a ``vehicle not only
to vindicate his best friend but also himself.''
   Jacobson said numerous character witnesses who testified about
Wallach's work for good causes did not know, or chose to ignore,
his bad side.
   ``That is the side of Bob Wallach that wanted money and wanted
power and wanted both in the worst way,'' he said. ``Money was the
driving force in Robert Wallach's life.''
   Jacobson also addressed the credibility of the prosecution's
main witnesses, including Mario Moreno, a former Wedtech vice
chairman who has pleaded guilty in the case.
   He said the witnesses were ``crooks'' but that their testimony
was credible because they were at the center of the criminal
conspiracy.
   Jacobson told the jurors not to believe defense arguments that
corrupt Wedtech officials took advantage of the defendants.
   ``These are three sophisticated men. They weren't duped into
anything,'' he said.
   Defense closing arguments were scheduled for Wednesday.
</TEXT>
