<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Silence     07-25 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Silence,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Panel Would Curb Right to Silence in Crime Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The accused's right to silence has been abused in
criminal cases and should be restricted, a government advisory
panel said Tuesday.
   ``It is wrong that offenders _ usually the more intelligent and
serious offenders _ should be able to manipulate the criminal
justice system to their own advantage, either to escape conviction
entirely or to delay and obstruct the judicial process,'' said a
report prepared by the panel.
   Last year, Northern Ireland ruled that courts could draw adverse
inference if a defendant refused to answer questions. The order was
specifically intended to combat terrorism in the province.
   At the time, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
indicated that similar changes were intended in England and Wales.
Scotland has a separate legal system.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd set a deadline of Jan. 25, 1990, for
comments on recommendations by the six-member working panel.
   The report adopts, with reservations, a recommendation made in
1972 by the Criminal Law Revision Committee that juries and
magistrates' courts should be able to draw reasonable inferences
from the accused's silence.
   But the panel also recommended:
   _ Statutory guidelines on factors the court will consider in
drawing inferences from silence.
   _ That failure to answer questions or to mention relevant facts
should not amount to positive evidence of guilt.
   _ Developing a new explanation of rights to be read to suspects.
</TEXT>
