<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2040EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Europarliament     07-25 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europarliament,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spaniard Elected to Presidency of European Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enrique Baron Crespo, a Spanish
Socialist, was elected president of the European Parliament during
the opening session of its five-year term Friday, after the
temporary chairman was greeted by a walkout.
   Baron won 301 of the 475 votes, becoming the first president of
the parliament chosen on the first ballot.
   Before his election, the 180 Socialists and 30 members of Greens
parties in the 518-member chamber walked out in silent protest when
Claude Autant-Lara began to speak.
   Autant-Lara, an 88-year old French movie director, belongs to
France's extreme right-wing National Front. The parliament's rules
stipulate that the oldest legislator preside during the election of
the president.
   Socialists and Greens said a representative of the ``extreme
right-wing forces of division in Europe'' should not open the term
of a parliament that strives for unity among the 12 member nations
of the European Economic Community.
   Baron, who will serve during the first half of the parliament's
term, lost the presidency by five votes in 1986, on the third
ballot, to Lord Plumb, a British Conservative.
   The 45-year old lawyer was Spain's minister for transport,
tourism and communications in 1982-1985. He has been president of
the European Socialist Movement since October 1987.
   Although the parliament is the Common Market's legislature, the
EEC Executive Committee has the real power.
</TEXT>
