<SECOND>AM-Bush-Tennis,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plays Tennis in Oppressive Heat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oppressive heat that has kept many
Washingtonians inside for days did not stop President Bush from
playing tennis Tuesday.
   Bush's enthusiasm to get to the newly resurfaced White House
courts was undisguised as he stopped to chat with two reporters who
spotted him returning to the White House from the Old Executive
Office Building next door.
   He raved about the new surface, indicating it had a bouncy feel.
   Although it was 90 degrees, and the air was thick with a hazy
humidity, the 65-year-old president said he was off for some
doubles with former Swedish Ambassador Wilhelm Wachtmeister, one of
the capital's most accomplished tennis players. They were joined by
presidential assistant Roger Porter, head of the Office of Policy
Development and Michael Boskin, chairman of the Council of Economic
Advisers.
   Bush, who also was out on the courts Sunday, said his partner
would be Wachtmeister.
   Looking forward to a future sports opportunity, Bush expressed
interest when the two reporters told him he was invited to play in
a softball tournament.
