<FIRST>u w AM-Catastrophic 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0768-a0771,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Revises Catastrophic Health Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee voted
Tuesday to cut by half the surtax on older Americans that pays for
Medicare insurance against costs of a catastrophic illness,
shifting some of the cost to both those with lower and those with
higher incomes.
   The panel, responding to a flood of mail from the mainly
higher-income retirees who bear most of the cost of the new
program, also agreed 19-17 to raise the flat premium that all but
the poorest people 65 and older must pay for the coverage.
   In general, couples with income under $25,000 a year would pay
more for coverage; most of those with incomes above that level
would pay less. Those above the $80,000 level would pay more
compared with current law.
   Also included in the committee's amendment was a provision that
allows retirees a once-in-a-lifetime chance to turn down
catastrophic coverage. But to quit that program, they also would
have to give up Part B Medicare, which pays physicians' fees.
   The committee, working on a catchall tax bill, by voice vote
reversed an earlier action that would have repealed what remains of
the consumer interest deduction. That action means about 24 million
couples and individuals will still be able to write off 10 percent
of the interest they pay on automobile, credit card, education and
other loans next year.
   Under the 1986 tax overhaul, the interest writeoff is being
phased out. This year, 20 percent may be deducted; after 1990, no
deduction will be allowed.
   Still awaiting action by the committee is a big political issue:
whether to reduce the tax on capital gains. President Bush wants to
cut the tax rate but Democratic leaders are opposed because they
believe most of the benefit would go to those with incomes over
$100,000 a year.
   There was no indication when the committee would decide that
question.
   Making the decision on how to change the catastrophic program
seemed to be almost as tough. The program became law only a year
ago, but since that time many retirees have complained because
coverage is required of all Medicare beneficiaries and because
higher-income retirees are having to foot the bill for those with
lower incomes.
   Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich., who said his main concern had been
about middle-income retirees, called the committee's compromise a
major gain.
   Rep. Brian Donnelly, D-Mass., who had complained because of the
flat monthly premium that lower-income retirees have to pay for
coverage, said he and others will still attempt to have the entire
program repealed. As for allowing retirees to opt out of coverage,
he said, even after the committee's action ``it's about as
voluntary as a prison sentence.''
   Under present law, most retirees pay a flat premium of $4 a
month for catastrophic coverage, which covers about one-third of
the cost of the program. The remainder is paid by those 65 and
older whose incomes are high enough that they pay at least $150 a
year in federal income tax.
   That remainder pays a 15 percent surtax on top of federal income
tax. The surtax rate is due to climb to 28 percent by 1993.
   The maximum surtax this year is $800 per person, or $1,600 if
both spouses are eligible for Medicare.
   Under the committee's action, the 1989 surtax rate would drop to
7.5 percent of taxes over $150; by 1993 the rate would rise to 14
percent.
   The flat premium for catastrophic coverage, now $4 a month, is
scheduled under current law to rise to $4.90 next year, with
similar increases projected in future years. The committee plan
would increase the 1990 premium by $3.50, $4 in 1991 and $4.10 each
in 1992 and 1993.
   The monthly catastrophic premiums are added to the regular
charges that most retirees pay for Medicare Part B coverage, which
help pay physicians' fees. The regular Part B premium is $27.90
this year and scheduled to rise to $33.40 by 1993.
   To meet requirements for reducing the federal deficit, the
committee voted to delay Medicare reimbursements to doctors and
hospitals by five days at the end of 1990, six days in 1991, three
days in 1992 and one day in 1993. That would produce a budget
saving of $2 billion next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
