<FIRST>r w AM-Hastings     07-25 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings,522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hastings Denies Wrongdoing as Senator Expresses Doubts About Wiretap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., surprised an
impeachment hearing panel Tuesday when he said wiretap charges
against Judge Alcee Hastings were too weak to warrant removing him
from the bench.
   Hastings denied wrongdoing at his Senate impeachment hearing,
emphasizing, ``None whatsoever'' when asked by Sen. Patrick Leahy,
D-Vt., if attorney William Borders had ever offered him money to
fix a case.
   Hastings, 52, Miami, is accused of plotting with Washington
lawyer Borders in 1981 to obtain a $150,000 payoff to place two
convicted racketeers on probation instead of imprisoning them. He
also is charged with perjury and improper disclosure of wiretap
information to Dade County Mayor Steve Clark.
   In a surprising development, Gorton, one of 12 senators on a
panel hearing evidence in the case, said that even if the wiretap
evidence proved to be very damaging it would not amount to enough
to remove Hastings from the U.S. District Court bench.
   In a statement, Gorton said his conclusion did not apply to the
other articles of impeachment against Hastings approved by the
House a year ago and now are being weighed by the Senate. He did
not elaborate when asked later.
   ``Sen. Gorton, as he said, was speaking for himself,'' said Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., noting he would withhold a decision until all
the evidence was presented.
   Most of Hastings' testimony on Tuesday involved the wiretap
count, and Hastings is expected to testify again on the bribery
charges.
   Leahy, however, arrived late and asked flatly if money to fix a
case ever had been offered by Borders, who was convicted of bribery
conspiracy in 1983 and now is refusing to answer questions before
the panel. He is expected to be called again Thursday.
   Leahy stopped asking questions about bribery after being told
Hastings would testify again later. But the judge firmly offered
his denial. The articles of impeachment also accuse Hastings of
lying to a jury at a 1983 trial at which he was acquitted.
   In emotional testimony, Hastings told the senators that he had
not disclosed the wiretap information.
   ``I did not tell Mayor Clark anything about anything anytime on
earth,'' Hastings said. ``... I take great stock in my ability to
keep a secret.''
   Hastings told the panel that when he was confronted by two Miami
reporters concerning rumors that he had disclosed the information
``I was absolutely livid in the way this information was coming to
me.''
   ``It was rife in the courthouse and it was bouncing all over the
place,'' Hastings said in a calm voice. `` ... It is hard for me to
control my rage as I speak now.''
   He acknowledged under questioning from lawmakers that he had not
initially cooperated with the public integrity section of the
Justice Department in its investigation of the wiretap leak.
   He said he already had been in conflict with the public
integrity section in the bribery conspiracy case and that he felt
they had been unfair to him in the past and were likely to do so
again.
</TEXT>
