<FIRST>u w AM-SexSurvey     07-25 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sex Survey,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Refuses Funds for Sex Survey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Appropriations Committee on Tuesday
refused to finance a planned survey of the intimate details of the
sex lives of Americans aimed at helping scientists better
understandhow AIDS spreads.
   The panel slashed $11 million from President Bush's proposed
budget for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, money that would have
paid for the survey.
   The project ``does not appear to be an appropriate use of public
funding,'' the committee said.
   In a report accompanying the $155.2 billion appropriations bill
for the Health and Human Services, Labor and Education departments
and for other agencies, the committee said: ``If such a survey is
necessary, it should be supported with nongovernmental funds.''
   ``The Public Health Service is not to proceed with this study,''
the committee report said.
   The bill is headed for the House floor and then to the Senate.
   The proposal to cancel the survey came from the subcommittee on
labor, health and human services and education, which approved the
cancellation in a closed session. Subcommittee staffers refused to
say who proposed it.
   Plans for the survey have been stalled at the Department of
Health and Human Services, which includes the Public Health
Service, since the Office of Management and Budget raised concerns
in April about a pilot questionnaire designed to preceed the larger
survey of 20,000 Americans.
   In response, HHS Secretary Louis Sullivan directed public health
officials to review the appropriateness of the questions proposed
for the pilot survey. Department officials say that since then the
survey has been through several levels of review and is now
awaiting consideration of James Mason, the assistant secretary for
health.
   The pilot survey that had been submitted to OMB proposed to ask
participants when they last had sex, what they did and whether
their partner was a man or women. It also asked questions about
oral and anal sex and masturbation.
   Backers said the survey was designed to develop a comprehensive
picture of Americans' sexual practices to help public health
officials better understand the spread of AIDS.
   Conservatives have lobbied strongly against the survey, saying
scientists already know that AIDS is spread through sexual contact
and that the government has no business invading the sexual privacy
of Americans.
   James Brown, a spokesman for the Public Health Service, declined
to comment on the House action except to say ``we are reviewing the
situation.''
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said he was ``very disappointed
that this survey may not be done.''
   He noted that a recent General Accounting Office report said
information from the survey was essential for projecting the number
of future AIDS cases and for planning health and hospital care for
the growing number of victims of the disease. The National Academy
of Sciences also said such a survey was necessary for planning AIDS
education efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
