<FIRST>r a AM-SmokerSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0690 07-25 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoker Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6, bgn `Delta officials...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with Delta comment. Picks up 7th graf, `Hendler was...' SUBS 3rd graf to
add comment from Hendler.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Smoker Wins Suit Against Airline for Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASCO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chain-smoking politician fumed when a
smoking ban was announced for his flight just before takeoff, but
the airline got burned in a court judgment.
   Pasco Mayor Ed Hendler sued Delta Air Lines for its last-minute
elimination of a smoking section on a flight he took in March. On
Monday, a judge agreed that Delta owed him a refund of his $389
airfare, plus $10 in filing and court costs.
   ``I was not provided the services I paid for,'' Hendler said in
a small claims court complaint. ``I'm very pleased. I'm tired of
being a second-class citizen because I smoke.''
   Franklin County District Judge H.W. ``Pete'' Felsted ruled that
Hendler was owed the price of his ticket because Delta did not give
him specific notice of the possibility of the change.
   Delta has 14 days to appeal. Jim Lundy, a company spokesman in
Atlanta, said Tuesday the airline is reviewing the case.
   He said federal law requires that every non-smoking passenger is
guaranteed a seat, and a plane's smoking section can shrink,
depending on the demand for non-smoking seats.
   ``In the case of this flight, it appears a no-smoking passenger
showed up very near departure. It became apparent that the entire
flight would be designated a no-smoking flight,'' Lundy said.
   Hendler was flying to Washington, D.C., as a representative to
the American Public Transportation Association meeting.
   ``I was a nervous wreck by the time I got there,'' he said,
calling himself a smoking addict.
</TEXT>
