<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Nominations 1stLd-Writethru a0758 07-25 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Nominations, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0758,528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Morris to Drug Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs to show strategy due in six weeks, sted one
month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday nominated U.S.
Marshals Service Director Stanley E. Morris to be deputy director
of the Office of National Drug Control Policy.
   The long-awaited appointment of a deputy director in charge of
efforts aimed at reducing drug supplies came just six weeks before
that office, headed by William J. Bennett, is required to complete
a national drug control strategy.
   Bennett said earlier Tuesday that his office has completed its
draft of the strategy and had submitted it to the affected agencies
for review.
   ``Obviously we're very pleased'' that Bush nominated Morris,
said Bennett spokesman Larry Cirignano. ``We would hope for a quick
confirmation so that he can get started.''
   Although Morris has been advising Bennett informally through his
role as head of the Marshals Service, ``It's different than coming
on board, getting his staff on board,'' Cirignano said.
   Last week, Morris, Bennett and Attorney General Dick Thornburgh
announced the results of an eight-week task force headed by the
Marshals Service that resulted in the arrests of 456 fugitives
wanted on drug charges in the Washington-Baltimore area, including
25 people wanted on drug-related homicide charges.
   Morris has headed the Marshals Service since 1983. Among other
things, it administers the Federal witness protection program and
has custody of seized assets in drug cases valued at more than $960
million.
   Morris was associate deputy attorney general from 1981 to 1983.
He served as deputy associate director for economics and government
at the Office of Management and Budget from 1973 to 1979, and has
been on the faculty at the University of Maryland.
   In other personnel actions on Tuesday, the White House announced
Bush's intention to nominate:
   _John M. Sayre as assistant secretary of the Interior for water
and science. Sayre, an attorney in private practice from Boulder,
Colo., once served as city attorney for Boulder from 1956 to 1963.
   _Raymond G. H. Seitz as assistant secretary of state for
European and Canadian affairs. Seitz is serving in the U.S. Embassy
in London and has served as executive assistant to the secretary of
state and in Zaire, Nairobi, and the Seychelle Islands.
   _Robert R. Randlett as assistant administrator of the Agency for
International Development for legislative affairs. Randlett is
director of public policy issues for Allied-Signal Inc., and
previously worked as congressional liaison officer for the Labor
Department.
   _Barbara E. McTurk as superintendent of the Mint in Denver. She
is a consultant for the state House of Representatives in Colorado,
and was state field director for Bush's presidential campaign last
year.
   _John T.Martino as superintendent of the Mint in Philadelphia.
He is president of Keystone Data in Pennsylvania, and previously
served in several state posts and as assistant to Rep. Robert
Walker, R-Pa.
   _JoAnn Krukar Webb as director of the National Cemetery System
in the Veterans Affairs Department. She previously was a health
care consultant for ACTION, the national volunteer agency, and was
an ACTION representative on the federal task force on AIDs.
</TEXT>
