<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2216EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Violence 1stLd-Writethru a0797 07-25 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0797,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Policemen, Eight Rebels Killed In Clashes</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with second rebel attack; No pickup;</UNK>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four policemen and eight guerrillas from two
different rebel groups were killed in separate clashes in Lima and
the southern highlands, police said Tuesday.
   In the first incident, 300 Shining Path rebels late Monday
attacked a police post in rural Acobamba with dynamite and
automatic weapons fire, police said.
   Four of the 30 officers at the post and three rebels were
killed. Police said the survivors abandoned the post after an
hour-long battle.
   The rebels then blew up the station and the city hall, and
ransacked stores in the town, located 175 miles southeast of Lima.
   The attackers made off with arms, medicine, food and clothing,
police said.
   Troops were dispatched to Acobamba to pursue the guerrillas,
police said.
   In a second clash, at least 15 guerrillas from the Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement Tuesday attacked a Lima police post with
grenades, dynamite and rifle fire. Five rebels were killed in a gun
battle and the others fled, police reported.
   They said there were no casualties among the 15 officers inside
the station, located in the Pueblo Libre working-class section of
Lima.
   Tupac Amaru rebels advocate Cuban-style Marxism.
   Police said the rebels painted slogans on nearby walls and hung
Tupac Amaru flags near the station.
   The guerrillas also set off bombs in three nearby banks and a
telephone office, damaging the buildings and breaking windows,
according to police.
   The movement has been fighting Peru's elected governments since
1984. It takes its name from an 18th century hero who led a peasant
revolt against Spanish rule in the Peruvian highlands.
   Estimates of the number of activists in the organization range
from 500 to 1,500. On April 28, 62 Tupac Amaru guerrillas were
killed when they were surprised by a military patrol near the
highland town of Jauja.
   The movement is smaller and considered less violent than the
Shining Path, a Maoist guerrilla group that took up arms against
the government in 1980.
   The Shining Path began its guerrilla war in the city of
Ayacucho, 235 miles southeast of Lima, but has since spread its
influence through much of the Andean highlands and into the
coca-producing jungle regions of the northeast.
   The government says more than 15,000 people _ many of them
peasants caught in crossfire between guerrillas and troops _ have
been killed in violence related to the insurgencies.
</TEXT>
