<FIRST>r w AM-FishWars     07-25 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish Wars,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Sends Officers To Take Control Of Ship Implicated In Fish
Sting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwanese enforcement officers on Tuesday
headed for a rendezvous with a driftnet vessel that has been
shadowed by a U.S. Coast Guard cutter in the North Pacific since it
was implicated in a scheme to sell $1.3 million worth of illegally
caught salmon a week ago.
   The ship carrying Tawianese police officers was expected to
reach the Sung Ching No. 1 and the Coast Guard cutter Morgenthau
within several days, said Ed Wolfe, the State Department's
ambassador for fisheries and oceans.
   After a joint boarding party inspects the Sung Ching No. 1, it
will be turned over to Taiwanese custody. Wolfe said the United
States expects the crew to eventually be prosecuted under Taiwanese
law.
   Taiwan's domestic law restricts the export of salmon and also
limits where Taiwanese driftnet vessels are allowed to fish.
   However, Wolfe said the government of Taiwan had provided ``no
guarantees'' it would prosecute.
   ``We've requested that they do so and it would be in their best
interest,'' he said.
   Taiwan had previously refused to allow U.S. personnel to board
the ship.
   The Sung Ching No. 1 was one of two Taiwanese driftnet vessels
implicated in the illegal sale of salmon to U.S. undercover agents
posing as fish buyers in a six-month sting operation.
   Last week, federal agents arrested two Taiwanese men as they
emerged from a Seattle bank vault carrying more than $1 million in
cash allegedly received as payment for 500 metric tons of illegally
caught fish.
   At the time the arrests were made, the Sung Ching No. 1 and the
other Taiwanese ship were preparing to transfer the fish to the
U.S. government chartered fishing tender Redfin in the North
Pacific, north of Midway Island.
   When the captains of the two Taiwanese ships boarded the Redfin
to arrange details of the transfer they were detained but their
vessels fled as the Mogenthau approached.
   Taiwan has until Aug. 29 to sign an agreement with the United
States regulating the conduct of driftnet vessels. The agreement
would permit U.S. inspectors to board Taiwanes vessels and would
require the vessels to carry satellite transponders to signal their
locations.
</TEXT>
