<FIRST>r a AM-ParaplegicClimber 1stLd-Writethru a0787 07-25 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraplegic Climber, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0787,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Climbers Try to Make Up Lost Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf, `Corbett has...,' to UPDATE
with comments from Corbett's brother.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paraplegic sorely inched
closer to the top of blustery El Capitan on Tuesday, trying to make
up for lost time to reach his goal of conquering the granite wall.
   Mark Wellman and his climbing partner Mike Corbett got a late
start on the eighth day of their tortuous trek to the top of the
3,200-foot monolith, although they had planned to begin climbing
the final 700 feet as early as 7 a.m. Instead, they decided they
needed extra rest.
   ``We're both really sore and we're both ready to get off the
mountain,'' Wellman, whose legs are paralyzed, said in a radio
conversation with a park ranger.
   Wellman hopes to reach the top around noon Wednesday, making him
the first paraplegic to make the climb, pulling himself up 6 inches
at a time on ropes placed by Corbett.
   Wellman was paralyzed from the waist down when he fell 50 feet
during a climb of the 13,700-foot Gables Peak, south of Yosemite,
in 1982. He trained daily for six months for El Capitan, making 35
practice climbs on other sheer rocks and weight training.
   Corbett has a record 41 ascents of El Capitan.
   Corbett's brother, Tony Corbett of Houston, said he had not seen
his brother in eight years before he watched a recent news report
about the attempt to scale El Capitan.
   ``You can just imagine how I felt when I saw him. It's hard to
say. Elation, I guess you could say,'' Corbett said in a telephone
interview.
   Wellman said his powerful hands are swollen but he is not
injured. He anticipated it would take 7,000 pullups to reach the
summit.
   Their biggest problem has been wind, which Wellman said has been
gusting each day, sometimes blowing them 10 feet out from the cliff
face.
</TEXT>
