<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     07-25 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Lady in Question,' A Comedy by Charles Busch, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There should be no question about ``The Lady in
Question.''
   Charles Busch's latest send-up of American popular culture _
specifically, those patriotic, sentimental war movies of the 1940s
_ is his best work yet, not only as a playwright but as a performer.
   The production, which opened Tuesday at off-Broadway's Orpheum
Theater, is a giddy, gender-bender comedy that spoofs those
self-sacrificing heroines, square-jawed heroes and sadistic Nazis
who were staples of the silver screen nearly 50 years ago.
   Busch plays Gertrude Garnet, a touring American concert pianist
who finds herself in the Bavarian mansion of the nefarious Baron
Wilhelm Von Elsner. Among the other occupants are the baron's
cigar-smoking momma, a handsome American professor, a pig-tailed
little girl who looks and acts like a Teutonic version of Patty
McCormack in ``The Bad Seed'' and Gertrude's wise-cracking female
sidekick Kitty.
   The convoluted plot involves the rescue of the professor's
mother, a famous actress, from the clutches of the baron. And it's
Gertrude who must do most of the work. She _ and Busch _ are up to
the task.
   From his hugely successful _ and still running _ ``Vampire
Lesbians of Sodom'' to ``Pyscho Beach Party'' to ``The Lady in
Question,'' Busch always has played the leading female role in his
plays. Why not? They are tailored to his talent.
   The actor, sporting long red tresses and a different glamorous
outfit for every scene, resembles Joan Crawford, with bits of Norma
Shearer, Greer Garson, Barbara Stanwyck, Bette Davis and even Greta
Garbo thrown in for effect.
   But his acting is more than skin-deep. Busch seems more assured
and less campy in his creation of this real Hollywood heroine. The
writing is also first-rate. There is a consistency of style and
tone, a never-wavering affection for the material. Busch is a
romantic and that love of the movies shows throughout the play.
   He also has been generous in writing good roles for other
members of what has become a resident troupe of players. There are
strong contributions from such regular members as Andy Halliday as
the evil, oversexed child; Arnie Kolodner as Gertrude's true love,
Meghan Robinson as a gorgon of a mother and Julie Halston as
Gertrude's best buddy.
   Director Kenneth Elliott, who also plays the baron, has just as
light a touch as Busch with the material, and there are fine
production values, particularly a throbbing musical soundtrack and
a set of outlandish wigs for Busch designed by Elizabeth Katherine
Carr. ``The Lady in Question'' definitely rates a date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Gingrich 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0703,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel Plans to Hire Phelan Firm to Review Gingrich Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 7: ``In a,'' with Gingrich statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee said Tuesday it
plans to hire the Chicago law firm that conducted the Jim Wright
investigation to review a complaint against Republican Whip Newt
Gingrich.
   The announcement was the latest indication that the panel is
close to approving a formal investigation of the Georgia
Republican, who arranged a controversial investment partnership to
promote a book he co-authored.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., accused Gingrich in a complaint
last April of violating campaign finance laws, House limits on
outside income and a House rule preventing acceptance of gifts from
those with a direct interest in legislation.
   Gingrich, the second-ranking House GOP leader, said last week
that Richard J. Phelan, the chief attorney in the Wright
investigation, ``strikes me as an honorable man. The committee has
to look at what the standard is for hiring an outside counsel and
do what it thinks is right.''
   He called Alexander's charges ``baseless,'' and said ``any
serious review of the allegations would indicate how politically
motivated they were.''
   Gingrich filed the complaint that helped launch the
investigation of then-Speaker Wright, D-Texas. Wright quit as
speaker and resigned from the House after the committee charged him
with 69 rules violations.
   In a statement Tuesday, Gingrich reviewed his votes and
statements in the Wright case and other congressional ethics cases
of his 1 years in the House and said in light of those positions,
``I have always know that any complaint filed against me would
receive intense scrutiny, even if unfounded. I will cooperate fully
with the committee to expedite this matter.''
   The ethics panel said it asked the House Administration
Committee to approve a contract with the firm of Phelan, Pope &amp;
John Ltd. Phelan was the chief attorney in the investigation of
Wright, and several associates assisted him.
   Phelan has told reporters that his personal time in a new
investigation would be more limited than in the Wright case, but
added the associates could do the work. Phelan also has dropped
hints that he's considering running in the Illinois Democratic
gubernatorial primary next March.
   ``I would assume Mr. Phelan would be part of the legal team,
even though the contract is with the law firm,'' said Ralph Lotkin,
chief counsel for the ethics committee.
   Last Thursday, the ethics panel held its first meeting since the
Wright investigation but made no immediate decision on launching a
preliminary inquiry of Gingrich _ the first step in a formal
investigation.
   The ethics panel said Tuesday: ``The legal assistance would be
for the specific purpose of providing the committee with an
analysis of the complaint and associated materials. The committee
has every expectation that the proposed contract with Phelan, Pope
&amp; John, Ltd. will be approved and that, as soon as this occurs, the
law firm will immediately begin its review.''
   Gingrich admittedly has been seeking advice from a number of
allies, and reportedly has approached former Rep. Ed Bethune, an
Arkansas Republican with a law practice in Washington, for help.
   Alexander's complaint focused on the ``COS Limited
Partnership,'' which consisted of 21 investors who contributed
$5,000 each to promote ``Window of Opportunity,'' a book written by
Gingrich, his wife and a third author. Gingrich was not an
investor, but his wife was paid for running the partnership, formed
in 1984.
   The Alexander complaint contends:
   _The investors' money could be construed as income to Gingrich,
in violation of limitations on House members' outside earnings.
   _The $105,000 raised could constitute a gift to Gingrich from
those with a direct interest in legislation. House rules prohibit
members from keeping gifts of more than $100 from anyone with such
an interest.
   _The money could be considered campaign contributions, subject
to reporting obligations and restrictions under campaign financing
laws. If so, Alexander said, the investment money may have exceeded
contribution limits and may not have been properly reported.
</TEXT>
