<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-PlaneHeld 2ndLd-Writethru a0790 07-25 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Plane Held, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0790,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ecuadoran Authorities Find Cocaine on Eastern Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to DELETE reference to arrests in lead
and explain arrests could not be confirmed. Picks up 5th graf, `Ecuadoran
customs...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ecuadoran authorities held an Eastern Airlines
jetliner and detained its crew after discovering cocaine aboard the
aircraft, the company said Tuesday.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said the crew members were told
by Ecuadoran authorities to remain at their hotel in Guayaquil
until Ecuadoran investigators take their depositions. The
investigation was delayed by Simon Bolivar Day festivities, he
added.
   Eastern Flight 51, an A-300, left Miami on Monday on a multileg
flight to Ecuador, Matell said. He said the plane was carefully
checked in Miami, but he noted it was on the ground 43 minutes in
Cali, Colombia, before heading to Guayaquil.
   In Guayaquil, authorities found six packets of cocaine hidden
below the floor of a lavatory, Matell said. Initial company reports
on the incident said three passengers were arrested, but Matell
said Tuesday night he had no information to confirm that.
   Ecuadoran customs officials found that the six packets each
contained 2.2 pounds of cocaine, said Customs Capt. Nilo Montalvo.
   It was the sixth shipment of cocaine found aboard an Eastern
jetliner by drug agents in Ecuador since December, authorities
there said. No Eastern crew members have been arrested in the cases.
   According to reports from anti-drug agents, Guayaquil has become
a ``bridge'' preferred by Colombian drug gangs for sending cocaine
to United States.
   Eastern canceled a return flight Tuesday and will send a new
plane and crew to Guayaquil on Wednesday to resume service. The
multileg flight that also includes Panama flies three times weekly
from Miami, Matell said.
   Matell said several planes have been temporarily impounded in
the last two months, but he said he didn't think the incidents were
related to the strike that began March 4 by Eastern's unions.
   ``This is something we've been battling for a long, long time,''
Matell said. ``No individual company has the resources to shut off
the flow of drugs from South America.''
   Eastern earlier this month was chastised by Perry Rivkind, Miami
district director of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service, for several recent cases in which Cuban nationals without
legal documents arrived in this country on Eastern's Latin American
routes to Miami. Eastern said that, too, was a traditional problem
on those routes.
   Eastern has reportedly been negotiating to sell its Latin routes
to American Airlines as part of Eastern's efforts to emerge from
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization as a smaller, more-efficient
carrier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
