<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1414EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv26   07-25 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26 ,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, July 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Like All Real Estate Markets, Condo And Coop Markets Are Cyclical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In some parts of the country sellers of housing
condominiums and cooperatives are losing patience with a market so
inert it barely supports hope.
   But don't give up, says an authority on the subject. The condo
concept remains alive and well and is destined to remain a vital
and desirable part of America's housing markets.
   The problem, if there is one in your area, probably arises from
a frenzy of building that left a glut on the market, or because
comparable rental housing is priced competitively.
   Another factor hurting some markets is that investors who bought
co-ops to rent out just a few years ago began dumping them when the
tax laws were changed in 1986 to limit the deductibility of
interest and other costs.
   The selling problems that exist, particularly in the Northeast,
probably have little to do with the desirability of condo or co-op
living but a lot to do with temporary, cyclical market factors.
   Paul Low, president of Lomas Mortgage USA, surveyed the condo
market for U.S. Housing Markets, an expensive publication
circulated among real estate and construction people, and found
many reasons for optimism.
   First, he said, there is evidence of increased acceptance. Each
generation has more members who have grown up in high-density
environments, more who have lived in or near large-scale
multifamily housing, he says.
   Such accommodations, he says, are gaining acceptability ``both
socially and psychologically.''
   Affordability plays a big role. Condo units often are more
affordable, the main reason being the reduced cost of land per
unit, or the fact that more attached than detached units can be
placed on a similar plot.
   Often, the condo is well-located too. While Americans might
still like to live in the wide open spaces, they usually aren't
lucky enough to find such ideals close to their work. Condos often
are closer to employment centers.
   Time seems to be a factor in the condo's favor, although it
wasn't always viewed that way. Conventional wisdom in the 1970s had
America advancing toward the four-day workweek, amid speculation on
how leisure time would be spent.
   It hasn't worked out that way. Says Low: ``Instead of lingering
in gourmet kitchens, we sprint to and from the microwave. Instead
of lazily tending our rose gardens, we hire landscape crews just to
keep our lawns mowed.''
   Demographics favor condos. For double-income couples and working
singles the idea of caring for a sprawling ranch on a large
suburban lot sounds onerous. For them, such a house means work _
the same thing they do all day.
   But that isn't the only demographic factor. Low observes that
the proportion of never-married men in the traditional first-time
homebuying age group has grown even faster than that of women. He
offers these statistics:
   Never-married men constituted 77.7 percent of the 20-24 age
group in 1988, up nine percent from 1980. In the 25-29 age group,
the percentage was 43.3 percent, up about 10 percent from 1980. And
in the 30-34 age category the share of never-married males grew
nine percent.
   That, he says, translates to more solo homeowners and potential
homeowners who, because of various factors, are inclined toward
buying convenience rather than responsibilities and chores in
housing.
   Divorce plays a role. Single parents, male and female, are a
fast-growing group. Security is important too. Social factors also;
singles and newlyweds may like to mingle, perhaps at the swimming
pool that some condos offer.
   Encouraging also for those enduring the tortures of down markets
is an item from the National Association of Realtors showing that
on a national basis existing condos and co-ops have been
appreciating faster than detached units.
   That trend, in fact, has existed since 1986. Last year, condo
and co-op prices rose 6.8 percent nationally, compared with 4.3
percent for one-family detached houses.
   So, if you, the seller, live in one of those pockets of inertia
where nobody bids on your co-op or condo unit, don't lose patience.
While singular factors could be involved, more likely the problem
relates to the market cycle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, July 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
