<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-25 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0870</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. abandoned
its $12.2 billion hostile bid for Time Inc. after the Delaware
Supreme Court upheld a lower court decision allowing Time to
proceed with its $14 billion buyout of Warner Communications Inc.
   The three-judge panel unanimously sustained on Monday a ruling
by Judge William T. Allen, affirming the rights of corporate
directors to decide the future course of their companies.
   The decision ended Paramount's seven-week bid to acquire Time.
Paramount issued a statement that it was dropping its $200 a share
buyout offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc., having
defeated Paramount Communications Inc.'s challenge to their
proposed merger, proceeded with their plan to create Time Warner
Inc., the world's largest communications concern.
   Time and Warner, which originally planned to merge in a stock
swap transaction, revised the deal to provide instead for Time to
acquire Warner in a $14 billion, or $70 a share, tender offer.
   After the offer expired at 5 p.m. Monday, Time said it held more
than 117 million of Warner's 200 million common shares outstanding.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration hailed the new Mexican
debt-reduction package as a breakthrough for its Third World debt
strategy, but others were decidedly less enthusiastic.
   Several members of Congress and private bankers said Monday they
believed the final agreement with Mexico offered a glimmer of hope
for the debt-strapped Third World, but they said the success of the
plan hinged on how far commercial banks would ultimately be willing
to go.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. made itself less attractive to
corporate raiders by saying it will cut 4,000 jobs, retreat from
its $1.4 billion weapons business and provide added cash to
shareholders.
   The sweeping restructuring announced Monday will include the
sale of a ``substantial portion'' of the company's 50 percent stake
in Yamatake-Honeywell, a Japanese controls maker. Analysts have
valued the holding at nearly $1 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government posted a $7.79 billion budget
surplus in June, smaller than a year ago, but the deficit for the
first nine months is mounting at a slower rate than 1988.
   The government said Monday that the June surplus, a normal break
in a string of monthly deficits because corporations and
individuals make quarterly tax payments in the month, followed a
$25.47 billion deficit in May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferruzzi Group called for a study of Chicago
Board of Trade operations, in a followup of the soybean processor's
criticism of the exchange's emergency order that required traders
to reduce their holdings in soybean futures contracts.
   David H. Swanson, president of Central Soya Co. and a member of
Ferruzzi's executive committee, said Monday the emergency order
illustrated that the exchange had failed to keep up with the global
expansion of commodities trading.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleanup costs stemming from its disastrous
Alaskan oil spill helped caused Exxon Corp.'s second quarter profit
to plummet by more than $1 billion, the nation's biggest oil
company reported.
   Exxon said Monday its net income fell 87 percent to $160
million, or 13 cents a share, from $1.2 billion, or 90 cents a
share, in the comparable 1988 quarter.
   Exxon said a special provision in the second quarter for
expenses and insurance claims stemming from the March 24 spill in
Alaska's Prince William Sound reduced its net income by $850
million, or 67 cents a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said it supported a
tenfold increase to $10 million in the maximum fine for criminal
antitrust violations by corporations.
   The department, noting it is conducting more than 150 grand jury
investigations of alleged criminal antitrust violations, said an
increase was needed to deter price fixing, bid rigging and unlawful
attempts by corporations to control the market on certain products.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said Monday that he supported
legislation pending in Congress that would increase the maximum
fine from $1 million to $10 million for corporate antitrust
violations.
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investment group proposing to buy
Northwest Airlines' parent company for $3.65 billion said it was on
the brink of closing the deal.
   More than 99 percent of shares in NWA Inc. had been tendered to
the group, Wings Holdings Inc. by Monday morning, according to the
group headed by Alfred Checchi, the former Marriott Corp. treasurer.
   Checchi said his financing was nearly in place and he was
pressing for early termination of the waiting period required under
the Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust Improvement Act.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved broadly lower in light activity Monday,
as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials lost 22.38 to 2,584.98$
   The dollar slipped against major European currencies, but edged
up against the Japanese yen.
   Bond prices edged higher in quiet dealings.
   Energy futures prices declined sharply; copper prices climbed;
grain and soybean futures fell; livestock and pork prices finished
mixed and precious metals were up slightly.
</TEXT>
