<FIRST>r f PM-Poland-Aid     07-25 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Aid,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Approves $120 Million Food Aid Package For Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture ministers representing the
12 nations of the European Economic Community have approved a $120
million food aid program for Poland, which has been hard hit by
food shortages.
   The ministers agreed Monday to draw grains, meat, olive oil and
citrus fruit from surplus stocks to send to Poland this year and
next.
   The emergency food aid, approved by the EEC agriculture
ministers, includes 500,000 tons of wheat for bread, 300,000 tons
of feedgrains, 10,000 tons of meat, 5,000 tons of olive oil and
20,000 tons of citrus fruits. Other products could be added later.
   The community estimated shipment costs at $16 million to $22
million.
   Also on Monday, 23 countries have been invited to meet Aug. 1 to
draft plans for a special program to encourage economic reforms in
Poland and Hungary, the EEC said.
   The conference will be held in response to a request by
President Bush and other Western leaders to come up with a way to
help the two East European countries.
   At the economic summit meeting in Paris, Bush and the leaders of
Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Japan urged emergency
shipments of food to Poland and longer term help for both Poland
and Hungary.
   The Western leaders want to encourage more open political and
economic systems in those countries, without angering the Soviet
Union.
   A Common Market spokesman said officials attending next week's
conference in Brussels will discuss steps to expand trade and
economic cooperation with Hungary and Poland and spur those
governments to take measures to restructure their ailing economies.
   The spokesman said the community had sent out invitations to 18
European countries as well as the United States, Canada, Japan, New
Zealand and Australia. It was not expected that officials from
Poland and Hungary would attend.
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski had appealed to Bush and
other Western leaders for a multibillion-dollar aid package in the
next two years.
   He asked for $1 billion to restructure food supplies, $2 billion
in new loans and additional financing for other projects. He also
asked the leaders to reduce and stretch out payments on Poland's
foreign debt of $39 billion.
   In a separate development, a delegation from Poland opened what
is expected to be a final round of negotiations on a trade and
economic cooperation agreement with the EEC.
   The pact would be the latest in a series of trade agreements the
community has worked out with East European nations. It previously
signed a trade and cooperation accord with Hungary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
