<FIRST>r f BC-TimeChronology     07-25 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Time Chronology,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Dates in Time-Warner-Paramount Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are some of the key developments in the
takeover battle surrounding Time Inc.:
   Nov. 10, 1988 _ Time Chairman J. Richard Munro, hinting at plans
for an acquisition or merger, tells securities analysts Time
intends to become a global media conglomerate.
   March 4, 1989 _ Time and Warner Communications Inc. announce
they will merge in a friendly stock swap to form Time Warner Inc.,
the world's largest communications concern.
   April 9 _ Gulf &amp; Western Inc. says it put its consumer finance
segment, The Associates, up for sale, allowing the company to focus
on its entertainment and publishing businesses. Gulf &amp; Western says
it will use some of the proceeds _ projected at $2.5 billion _ to
finance acquisitions.
   May 22 _ Time and Warner schedule June 23 meetings for their
shareholders to vote on the planned merger.
   June 5 _ Gulf &amp; Western, noting its focus on entertainment and
media, announces it is changing its name to Paramount
Communications Inc.
   June 6 _ Paramount announces a $10.7 billion, or $175 a share,
offer for Time and files suit in Delaware Chancery Court against
the Time-Warner merger.
   June 16 _ Time rejects Paramount's offer as inadequate and
highly conditional, announces it will pursue a $14 billion outright
buyout of Warner and postpones its shareholders meeting until June
30.
   June 23 _ Paramount raises its bid for Time to $12.2 billion, or
$200 a share.
   June 26 _ Time rejects Paramount's sweetened bid and reiterates
its intention to acquire Warner.
   June 28 _ Delaware Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen refuses
to block Time's annual meeting.
   June 29 _ Paramount says seven banks have agreed to help raise
the financing for its Time bid, although the company does not have
commitments for all of the required backing.
   June 30 _ At Time's annual meeting, Munro states that the
company is not for sale as shareholders press company officials on
their decision not to consider the Paramount bid.
   July 7 _ Time announces it has financing commitments from 40
banks for its Warner bid.
   July 8 _ Time announces it has completed the financing
commitments for the Warner offer with agreements from two
investment firms.
   July 10 _ Paramount amends its offer to include an interest
payment of 9 percent a year, or about $1.50 a month, to begin 60
days after Time agrees to a merger or is ordered to refrain from
interfering with the Paramount bid.
   July 11 _ Allen hears arguments on a request by Paramount and
some Time shareholders to halt the Time-Warner merger.
   July 14 _ Allen denies the Paramount and shareholder request for
an injunction against Time's tender offer for Warner, but
temporarily halts the bid to give the plaintiffs time to appeal.
   July 24 _ The Delaware Supreme Court upholds Allen's ruling,
allowing Time to proceed with its tender offer for Warner.
Paramount drops its hostile tender offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0243 </DOCNO>
