<DOCNO> AP890725-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Oil     07-25 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Oil,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Up In 2ns Qtr. For Arco, Amerada Hess, Down For Amoco, Ashland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Earns-Exxon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Amoco Corp. and Ashland Oil Inc. said their profits fell in the
latest quarter while Atlantic Richfield Co. and Amerada Hess Corp.
reported net income gains.
   Amoco, based in Chicago, said Monday its net income in the three
months ended June 30 tumbled 25.5 percent to $497 million, or 96
cents a share, from $667 million, or $1.30 a share, in the
year-earlier period. Revenue rose to $6.8 billion from $6.1 billion
a year earlier.
   Excluding special charges of $36 million in the second quarter
and $136 million in one-time gains in the year-earlier period,
Amoco's earnings were flat at about $530 million, the company said.
   Arco, based in Los Angeles, reported net income of $467 million,
or $2.66 a share, a 16.7 percent increase from the $400 million, or
$2.19 a share, earned in the same period last year. Revenue dropped
to $4.3 billion from $4.6 billion.
   Ashland's net income declined 22.8 percent in the quarter to $44
million, or 78 cents a share, from $57 million, or $1.02 a share.
Revenue rose to $2.2 billion from $2.1 billion.
   Amerada Hess reported net income of $133.5 million, or $1.65 a
share, compared with a net loss of $23.5 million, or 29 cents a
share, in the second quarter of 1988. Revenue totaled $1.5 billion,
up 67 percent from $882.8 million.
   Analysts said higher crude oil prices in the quarter contributed
to healthier exploration and production earnings for most oil
companies while squeezing refining margins. Crude prices were up
nearly $3 a barrel during the quarter, compared with the
year-earlier period.
   Much of the higher crude costs were passed on to consumers
through higher gasoline prices, which have skyrocketed since March,
analysts said.
   For companies with foreign operations, the strong dollar also
cut into profit margins as product prices became less competitive
overseas.
   For the first six months of 1989, Amoco's earnings fell 16.2
percent to $955 million, or $1.85 a share, vs. $1.14 billion, or
$2.21 a share, in the comparable 1988 period. Revenue totaled $13.3
billion, up from $11.8 billion in the same 1988 period.
   Amoco said a big decline in chemical earnings offset gains in
exploration and production and refining and marketing.
   Analysts said weakness in the chemical sector reflected an
overall softening of the U.S. economy.
   Arco's first half net income nearly doubled to $1.2 billion, or
$6.66 a share, from $801 million, or $4.39 a share. Revenue totaled
$8.3 billion, down from $9.2 billion in the 1988 period.
   Arco said it benefited from higher crude prices, record coal
production, increased domestic gas production and increased
refining and marketing earnings.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Ashland had net
income of $126 million, or $2.26 a share, up 6.8 percent from $118
million or $2.10 a share in the year-earlier period. The 1988
results excluded $40 million, or 71 cents a share, added due to
accounting changes.
   Nine-month revenue for the Ashland, Ky.-based company rose to
$6.2 billion from $6 billion.
   New York-based Amerada Hess said its first-half net income grew
to $353.7 million, or $4.35 a share, from $42.2 million, or 51
cents a share, in the 1988 half. Revenue rose to $2.96 billion from
$2.1 billion a year earlier.
   Exploration and production earnings surged to $28 million from
$1.2 million in the second quarter of 1988, while the company's
refining and marketing sector recovered from a $6.5 million loss
last year to post a $125.5 million profit in the quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0208EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Exxon Bjt   07-25 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Exxon, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spill Cleanup Causes Exxon's Profit to Plunge</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic under EXXON in AP Access</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industry analysts expressed surprise at Exxon
Corp.'s costs for cleaning up the Alaska oil spill, which the
world's largest oil company blamed in part for a $1 billion plunge
in its second-quarter profit.
   ``They're spending close to $40 million a week instead of the
$20 million that they estimated earlier,'' Frank P. Knuettel of
Prudential Bache Securities said Monday after Exxon announced its
earnings.
   Also surprising was that Exxon's results did not provide for an
after-tax credit on the oil spill losses, observers said. The
company has said that it would write off the cleanup expense as a
cost of doing business.
   A bill pending in Congress would ban Exxon from deducting the
costs of the cleanup.
   ``They can still take it later on, but for now it's probably a
politically smart move,'' said Bruce Lazier, an analyst with
Prescott, Ball &amp; Turben Inc.
   Exxon said that a special provision in the second quarter for
expenses and insurance claims stemming from the March 24 spill in
Alaska's Prince William Sound reduced its net income by $850
million, or 67 cents a share.
   Exxon said its net income fell 87 percent to $160 million, or 13
cents a share, from $1.2 billion, or 90 cents a share, in the
comparable 1988 quarter.
   Without the provision, earnings would have declined by 16
percent to $1 billion, due to weaker refining profit margins, a
stronger dollar and the U.S. economic slowdown, Exxon said.
   The New York-based company said the estimated provision includes
$600 million already spent on the cleanup as well as estimated
future outlays but does not include the cost of any lawsuits.
   The provision is in addition to insurance coverage of more than
$400 million that will go toward cleaning up the 11 million gallons
of spilled crude, Exxon said.
   Second-quarter revenue for Exxon rose 9 percent, to $23.6
billion from $21.63 billion.
   So far, 143 suits have been filed against the company _ 138
seeking damages and five derivative suits by shareholders _ in
connection with the spill from a grounded Exxon tanker that fouled
hundreds of miles of water and coastline.
   Environmentalists and a number of government officials have
criticized Exxon's handling of the spill, contending the company
was inadequately prepared for the disaster.
   Alaska officials also were dismayed Monday when the oil company
said it would not change its plan to withdraw its oil spill cleanup
forces from Prince William Sound by mid-September for the winter.
   ``Clean-up of the Alaskan oil spill was Exxon's top priority in
the quarter,'' Exxon Chairman Lawrence G. Rawl said in the
company's earnings statement. ``The magnitude of the required
effort is huge and therefore costly.''
   But Rawl said Exxon's financial position remains strong.
   ``We are continuing to pursue our long-term business strategies
and to implement planned capital programs,'' he said.
   For the first six months of 1989, Exxon's provision for the
Alaska oil spill totaled $880 million, including $30 million
charged in the first quarter. Exxon's earnings totaled $1.4
billion, or $1.12 a share, for the first six months, down 46
percent from $2.66 billion, or $1.96 a share, in the first half of
1988.
   Excluding the spill provision, Exxon's first half earnings were
$2.3 billion, or $1.81 a share, down 13 percent. Revenue for the
first half rose to $45.86 billion from $43.63 billion a year
earlier, a 5 percent improvement.
   Exxon said it increased capital and exploration expenditures
about 22 percent in the quarter to $2.2 billion from $1.8 billion.
   Although second-quarter crude prices were $2.85-a-barrel higher
than a year earlier, earnings from exploration and production
declined by $10 million to $693 million.
   Exxon said higher crude prices were offset by higher foreign
taxes and lower production at its North Sea facilities stemming
from accidents and pipeline problems.
   Refining and marketing earnings declined $49 million from last
year to $232 million, reflecting lower margins in foreign markets
and lack of improvement in U.S. markets compared with a year
earlier.
   Analysts said the dollar's strength against foreign currencies
hurt all oil companies operating overseas. A higher dollar makes
U.S. products more expensive in foreign markets.
   Also, a slowdown in the U.S. economy contributed to lower
earnings in the company's chemicals sector as the price of some
products declined.
</TEXT>
