<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0749EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Honeywell Bjt   07-25 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honeywell, Bjt,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repeating for those needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Honeywell Announces Sweeping Plan To Enhance Shareholder Value</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. has announced a sweeping
restructuring in which it will cut 4,000 jobs, retreat from its
$1.4 billion weapons business and provide added cash to
shareholders.
   The changes unveiled Monday will make Honeywell less attractive
to corporate raiders.
   The restructuring will include the sale of a ``substantial
portion'' of the company's 50 percent stake in Yamatake-Honeywell,
a Japanese controls maker. Analysts have valued the holding at
nearly $1 billion.
   Chairman James Renier also said the company will repurchase up
to 10 million shares of its common stock on the open market and
increase the annual dividend by 31 percent, beginning in the fourth
quarter.
   A special cash dividend to shareholders is possible, Renier
said, but did not elaborate. He also predicted a $150 million
improvement in operating profits of remaining businesses over the
next 18 months because of the restructuring.
   Honeywell will focus on its main business of controls, which
range from home thermostats to automation equipment for paper mills
and chemical plants.
   Honeywell stock closed up $3.87{ a share to $89.37{ in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Asked if the restructuring would deter a possible hostile
takeover, Renier said, ``Obviously if you enhance shareholder
value, that's definitely beneficial from that point of view.''
   Honeywell's stock price has risen sharply in the last several
weeks following published reports that General Electric Co. was
considering acquiring the company. General Electric has denied the
rumors, saying it has no interest in Honeywell.
   Takeover speculation sprouted after Honeywell announced a $435
million loss in fiscal 1988. The rumors also were fueled by the
defeat in a proxy fight last year of two takeover defenses proposed
by management.
   The group that led the proxy fight, North American Partners of
Fort Worth, Texas, praised the restructuring move.
   ``This is a new management group determined to get the company
focused in on its real jewels, the controls business,'' said
spokesman Eddie Lampert, whose group owns between 4 percent and 5
percent of Honeywell stock. ``We think the stock will move
significantly higher when they execute the plan.''
   The restructuring is obviously a defensive move, said Kurt
Rivard of Minneapolis-based Dain Bosworth Inc. Raiders will be
discouraged because the sale of assets by Honeywell will reduce the
breakup value of the company, Rivard said.
   The increased stock price also would make a takeover more
expensive, said John McManus, a securities analyst with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   But McManus and Rivard said the restructuring won't guarantee
independence to Honeywell.
   ``Renier is making sure the shareholders are rewarded for their
ownership, but it doesn't rule out someone making a run at the
company,'' Rivard said.
   Honeywell intends to reduce its dependence on weapons production
but it will keep its business of making aviation and space
controls, which are sold to the military as well as other
customers, the company said.
   Honeywell is the leading manufacturer of torpedoes for the U.S.
Navy and supplies the U.S. Army with ammunition for tanks,
anti-tank weapons, small air-delivered munitions and mines, said
company spokeswoman Susan Eich.
   Weapon sales last year were about $1.4 billion, or about 20
percent, of Honeywell's $7.1 billion in revenue.
   Overall defense contracting, including the parts such as
avionics that are being kept, totaled 35 to 45 percent of Honeywell
sales last year, Renier said.
   Renier would not say whether a sale of the weapons business is
one of the options being considered, but Defense Department
spokesman Glenn Flood, said Honeywell's contracts could be assumed
by another company that bought the business from Honeywell. Rivard,
the Dain Bosworth analyst, said such a sale could bring the company
about $1 billion.
   The reduction in weapons production will ``proceed over time in
a responsible manner that recognizes the U.S. government's interest
in these businesses so as not to adversely affect national security
interests, our government program obligations, or the value of
these businesses to Honeywell shareholders,'' Renier said.
   Negotiations to sell the company's stake in Yamatake-Honeywell,
which is listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, will begin within a
few days, Honeywell spokeswoman Kathy Tunheim said.
   She would not identify potential buyers. Japanese investors
currently own half of the company, she said.
   Honeywell's restructuring program will include the elimination
of 4,000 jobs worldwide over the next 18 months, including 300
corporate staff positions targeted in an announcement last month,
Renier said.
   Honeywell currently employs about 78,000 workers. Many of the
job cuts will be made through attrition, but some layoffs will be
necessary, Tunheim said.
</TEXT>
