<FIRST>r f PM-ChryslerCuts     07-25 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler Cuts,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler to Cut White-Collar Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new round of white-collar layoffs
is in store at Chrysler Corp. as the automaker tries to trim costs
in the face of sluggish sales.
   Chrysler confirmed Monday that cuts were planned but it declined
to say how many employees may be affected. Chairman Lee Iacocca is
expected to discuss details of the plan Thursday with hundreds of
Chrysler's top managers.
   Of Chrysler's 123,000 workers, 31,000 are white collar.
   ``Ongoing belt-tightening is simply a way of life as we look for
ways to reduce costs,'' company spokeswoman Karen Stewart said.
   ``It's just a basic competitive action, necessary in an industry
where incentive costs, worldwide excess capacity and increasing
competition have forced structural changes on the auto industry.''
   A company statement said the cuts ``would not impact our
long-range product plan, research-and-development budget or capital
spending program.''
   In late 1987, shortly after Chrysler acquired American Motors
Corp., the company trimmed its salaried work force by about 3,600
people, mostly through early retirement and attrition.
   Chrysler's domestic car and truck sales through July 10 were
running 8 percent below last year's level. Sales for the eight
major domestic makers were 4.4 percent lower than last year.
   Chrysler is expected to report its second-quarter earnings next
week. Wall Street analysts have predicted a slightly better
performance than last year, but held out the possibility that
profits could be lower for the period.
</TEXT>
