<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 0931EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-IranExports     07-25 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Iran Exports,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran's Non-Oil Exports Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's non-oil exports rose 25 percent in
the first quarter of the current Iranian year over the same period
last year, Tehran radio reported Tuesday.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Mahmoud Ardekani,
deputy minister of Economy and Finance and head of Iranian customs,
as saying that Iran has exported more than 243,000 tons of non-oil
goods worth $217 million since the beginning of the Iranian year on
March 21.
   Iran's chief non-oil exports are pistachios, dates, textiles
fine hand-made carpets and other handicrafts.
   The exports are under strict government control to prevent
capital flight in the form of goods.
   Iran has been trying to diversify its sources of foreign
exchange, which so far have been wholly reliant on oil.
   Iran needs foreign exchange to rebuild large sectors of its
industry destroyed in the 8-year war with Iraq, which halted last
August with a United Nations-mediated cease-fire.
</TEXT>
