<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1025EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-ITT     07-25 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-ITT,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>ITT Earnings Rise 7 Percent In Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ITT Corp. said Tuesday that second-quarter
earnings rose 7 percent despite softness in the property and
casualty insurance business, its biggest moneymaker.
   Earnings rose to $244 million, or $1.65 per share, from $228
million, or $1.58 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $5.2
billion from $5 billion. Excluding special one-time factors,
earnings would have risen 14 percent, the company said.
   For the first half, ITT said earnings rose 9 percent to $444
million, or $3.05 per share, from $407 million, or $2.82 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose to $10 billion from $9.5 billion in the
1988 first half.
   An industrywide downturn in property and casualty insurance that
hurt results at The Hartford in the first half is expected to
continue for the rest of the year, ITT said. Sheraton Corp.'s
results worsened slightly from South American foreign-exchange
losses.
   Making up for that were improved results in all the company's
product businesses, including defense technology, automotive, fluid
technology, electronic components and pulp and timber, the company
said.
   Alcatel NV, the European-based telecommunications equipment
maker in which ITT has a 37 percent interest, ``continued to
operate exceptionally well,'' ITT said.
   ITT calculates earnings per share on a fully diluted basis, that
is, if all securities that can be converted into common shares were
converted.
</TEXT>
