<DOCNO> AP890725-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1108EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Karcher     07-25 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Karcher,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carl's Jr. Founder, Family Settle Insider-Trading Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founder of the Carl's Jr. restaurant
chain and several members of his family agreed to pay $664,000 to
settle a federal lawsuit charging them with insider trading.
   ``Carl just wanted to get it behind it him for the benefit of
his family and children,'' said Thomas Holliday, Karcher's attorney.
   As part of the agreement, Carl N. Karcher and the six family
members named in the civil lawsuit neither admit nor deny guilt.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission filed the suit in April
1988. It alleged that several Karcher relatives and one company
executive sold stock in Carl Karcher Enterprises Inc. to avoid
losses totaling at least $310,000, in advance of a poor earnings
report in 1984.
   Karcher Enterprises runs 460 Carl's Jr. fast-food outlets in
California and other Western states.
   The settlement requires Karcher, 72, to pay $332,000 for the
amount his family allegedly saved by selling their stock at his
advice. The family members will also pay a total of $332,000 to the
government.
   Details of the agreement were completed Monday in a closed-door
session with U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie.
   In addition to Karcher, also named in the suit were his son,
Jerome Karcher, daughters Barbara Karcher-Garrett, Margaret J.
LeVecke, Catherine Karcher-Everly and Karcher's sons-in-law Daniel
Everly and Donald E. Fergus Jr.
   Alvin DeShano, accounting director at Karcher Enterprises, was
also named in the insider-trading case and was the only defendant
charged with criminal securities fraud. He was found innocent by a
Los Angeles jury last month.
   The terms of the agreement involving the Karcher family were
approved by the SEC several weeks ago, said SEC lawyer John Koutsos.
   Donald F. Karcher, Karcher's brother and the president of
Karcher Enterprises, and six members of his side of the family
agreed last February to pay a total of $187,560 to settle their
part in the civil suit. They also did not admit guilt as part of
the agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
