<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Time-Warner 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner, 1st Ld-Writethru,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time and Warner Proceed With Buyout</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS grafs 4-7 to update with number of shares tendered.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thought Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc.
are proceeding with their merger, the two aren't exactly picking up
where they left off on June 6, when Paramount Communications Inc.
tried to spoil the plan.
   Time and Warner, which originally planned to merge in a stock
swap transaction, revised the deal in response to Paramount's $10.7
billion hostile bid for Time, providing instead for Time to acquire
Warner in a $14 billion, $70-a-share tender offer.
   That offer expired at 5 p.m. Monday, several hours after the
Delaware Supreme Court upheld a lower court ruling allowing the
merger to proceed.
   Time said today it had been tendered approximately 176 million
of Warner's 200 million outstanding common shares and now owns
approximately 59.3 percent of the company's stock.
   Starting Monday, Warner stockholders will be paid $70 a share in
cash for slightly more than 100 million shares. Time will exchange
the rest at some point in the future _ possibly several months _
for a combination of cash and securities valued at $70 a share. The
so-called ``back end'' of the deal will take place when the
Time-Warner merger is consummated.
   It is not known what kind of securities will be issued, but they
could include new shares of Time common stock.
   Warner stock rose $1.62{ to $66.12{ a share Monday on the New
York Stock Exchange before the tender offer expired.
   The original merger agreement announced in March required the
approval of Time and Warner stockholders, but Time's acquisition of
Warner does not require shareholder votes.
   Warner shareholders must approve the deal, but they effectively
will do so by tendering their stock to Time. When a shareholder
vote is held, Time Inc. effectively will be the only shareholder.
   After the acquisition is completed, Time's name will change to
Time Warner Inc. and Warner stock will cease trading on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   The corporate structure of the merged company will, at first,
largely resemble Time and Warner as they are now.
   J. Richard Munro, 58, now the chairman of Time, and Steven Ross,
61, the Warner chairman, will serve as co-chairmen and co-chief
executive officers at Time Warner. After both eventually retire,
N.J. Nicholas Jr., now Time's president and soon to be Time
Warner's president, is expected to head the company.
   The two companies' corporate staffs will be integrated, but
``we've vowed there would be no job loss'' as a result of the
merger, said Louis Slovinsky, a Time spokesman.
   Warner's cable television operations will report to Joseph
Collins, the head of Time's cable division, and Warner's book
publishing division will report to the head of Time's publishing
unit, Kelso Sutton, Slovinsky said.
   No other changes were contemplated immediately.
   The companies have denied they plan to sell any assets to help
finance the deal, but published reports say executives have
targeted some divisions, including Time's Scott, Foresman &amp; Co.
book publisher, as possible candidates for sale.
   Some 500 Warner executives and employees reportedly would be
paid a total of about $677 million under stock, option and bonus
plans under the merger.
   Warner Chairman Steven Ross would receive $193 million in
payments and also would receive options on 1.8 million Time Warner
shares.
   The payments _ which were outlined in minutes of a June 15
Warner board meeting _ are considered the largest-ever compensation
package for employees of a company involved in a takeover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0259 </DOCNO>
