<FIRST>r f BC-Yugoslavia-CubicDinar     07-25 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Yugoslavia-Cubic Dinar,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hyper-Inflation Causes Currency Reckoning by Volume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soaring inflation has forced border
money changers to measure the Yugoslavian currency in cubic meters,
the national news agency Tanjug reported Tuesday.
   It said that at the Sentilj border crossing between Austria and
Yugoslavia foreign tourists recently exchanged their hard
currencies into ``fourteen cubic meters of dinars.''
   ``Dinars can no longer be measured in millions or billions, or
even in units of length or square meters, but only in cubic
meters,'' Tanjug said quoting the Dnevnik daily of the northern
city of Ljubljana.
   ``We now have a new unit for our national currency _ the cubic
dinar,'' Tanjug said.
   Inflation in Yugoslavia has surpassed the 700 percent mark and
is expected to peak at around 1,000 percent by the end of the year.
The country's largest 100,000 dinar banknote, put into circulation
last month, is currently worth less than $5.
</TEXT>
