<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, supported by
signals of higher demand but depressed by improved growing
conditions in the Midwest.
   A National Weather Service six-to-10-day forecast issued after
the close of trading Monday predicted mostly normal to above-normal
moisture and normal temperatures in major Midwestern growing areas
early next week, which added to the selling pressure in the corn
and soybean markets.
   Corn futures were slightly lower in early trading while soybeans
were trading at the upper end of a narrow range with most of the
buying linked to internal market influences that showed demand was
increasing.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.90 a bushel; corn was
\ cent to } cents lower with September at $2.30\ a bushel; oats
were { cent to 1{ cents higher with September at $1.44{ a bushel;
soybeans were unchanged to 3\ cents higher with August at $6.65 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .35 cent lower with August at 72.57
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .20 cent higher
with August at 84.02 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower
to .40 cent higher with August at 46.25 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .25 cent to .45 cent lower with August at 28.45 cents
a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Monday while pork futures were
mostly lower.
