<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-ControlData     07-25 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Control Data,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control Data Loses $497.3 Million In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. on Tuesday reported a
second-quarter loss of $497.3 million, a debacle forecast by
company officials in April when they dumped the ETA Systems
supercomputer subsidiary and slashed 3,100 jobs.
   The bulk of the loss was from special, one-time charges,
although the company also lost about $25 million on the businesses
it has retained, including interest expenses.
   Control Data, once one of the world's largest computer makers,
has been steadily shrinking in a struggle to achieve sustained
profitability.
   ``With those activities largely behind us and an amended credit
agreement in place, we can concentrate on Control Data's ongoing
businesses and work to achieve a profitable second half of the
year,'' Chairman Robert Price said.
   The loss on sales of $804.3 million compares with net earnings
of $9.2 million, or 22 cents a share, in the second quarter of
1988, when sales were $951.7 million.
   The second-quarter earnings plunge meant a loss of $493.8
million for the first six months of the year.
   Shutting down St. Paul-based ETA cost Control Data about $335
million, slightly less than the $350 million originally estimated.
The balance of the charges came from shrinking the Cyber mainframe
division, paying severance to cover corporate staff layoffs and the
company's departure from the training and education business, Price
said.
   Price said losses in the mainframe business, computer
maintenance services and semiconductor division were only partially
offset by profits at Imprimis, the company's disk drive subsidiary.
   Last month, the company said it was selling Imprimis to Seagate
Technology Inc. for about $450 million in cash and securities. The
proceeds from that sale won't be booked until the deal closes,
probably this fall, a Control Data spokesman said.
   Control Data discontinued ETA, saying it was too expensive to
operate. In 1988, the fledgling supercomputer business had losses
of about $100 million. The division never made money for Control
Data.
</TEXT>
