<FIRST>r f BC-ConstructionOutlook     07-25 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Construction Outlook,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outlook for Residential Construction Better Than Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction contracting will fall about 2
percent this year, less than previously estimated because lower
interest rates should boost residential construction, a forecast
says.
   ``The return of workable interest rates means a fuller
realization of this year's potential for one-family housing and
institutional building,'' George A. Christie, vice president for
McGraw Hill's Construction Information Group, said in a statement
Tuesday.
   Total construction contracting is expected to fall to $254
billion from $258 billion, according to the Dodge-Sweet
Construction Outlook.
   The forecast updates an April projection, which had been for a 3
percent decline in construction contracting.
   Among particular segments, McGraw-Hill forecast a 7 percent drop
in non-residential construction contracting, no change in
residential construction contracting, and a 2 percent drop in
non-building construction, such as construction for transportation
and utilities.
