<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     07-25 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0369</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices remained higher in moderately
active trading today, but below their best levels of the session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 7.39 at 2,592.37
at 2 p.m. on Wall Street after showing a gain of about 18 points
two hours earlier.
   In the broader market, advancing issues maintained a lead over
decliners of about 7 to 5 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 816
up, 566 down and 534 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.68 to 186.71.
   Big Board volume came to 129 million shares with two hours left
to go.
   Analysts said institutional activity dominated the market.
   ``It's bargain hunting. There was a lot of cash on the sidelines
yesterday and today it's coming back into the market,'' said Ralph
J. Acampora, technical analyst with Kidder, Peabody, ``There are a
lot of good stocks out there.''
   Analysts said transportation stocks highlighted buying activity
after a newspaper report that billionaire Marvin Davis was buying
shares in UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines. UAL soared 6} to
183{.
   ``Transporation is the key so far today. The story of Marvin
Davis has run the stock off the charts,'' said Thomas Walsh, head
of equity trading, Nikko Securities International. ``The euphoria
of the transportation index has spilled over into the industrial
sector.''
   Analysts said two government reports out this morning had a
minor impact on the market.
   Factory orders for durable goods rose a seasonally adjusted 0.3
percent in June after falling 4.4 percent in May, the Commerce
Department reported.
   The Labor Department said that employment costs _ including
wages, salaries and other benefits _ paid to American workers rose
4.5 percent in the 12 months ending in June.
   Unisys led the list of actively traded issues on the Big Board
and was down 1] to 20\.
   Among heavily traded blue chips, AT&amp;T was trading ~ higher at
38{; Eastman Kodak was down 1[ to 46}; Exxon fell | to 44{; General
Electric rose { to 56~; and McDonalds gained { to 29|.
