<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2107EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-VideoWars-Future Adv30   07-25 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Video Wars-Future, Adv 30,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dominance in Games Gives Nintendo Useful Presence in Computer Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on general newswires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Instead of just zapping aliens from outer space
or punching out a boxing opponent, Nintendo users of the future may
be able to trade stocks, make vacation plans or shop from home.
   ``The fact remains that the good old Nintendo Entertainment
System is a full-blown 8-bit computer system that can do a lot more
than play Super Mario Brothers 2,'' says Peter T. Main, vice
president of marketing at Nintendo of America Inc. in Redmond, Wash.
   Although he wouldn't disclose details of the company's plans, he
said the popularity of the video game system ``presents significant
opportunities for a home information system.''
   Nintendo previously has disclosed talks with American Telephone
&amp; Telegraph Co., but both indicate the negotiations are in
preliminary stages.
   Presumably, the companies are talking about creating an
interactive communications network that would involve hooking
Nintendo machines to phone lines to receive and send information.
Not only would the linkup allow people to play video games with
others around the country, it eventually could give Nintendo
machine owners access to data supplied by a third party.
   Nintendo has experience in computer networking. In 1987, it was
host of a ``Family Computer Golf Tournament'' in Japan as an
experiment in communications using public phone lines.
   Video golf players across Japan vied against each other while
using the Family Computer System. The machine is in 35 percent of
households there, where Nintendo says it has a 90 percent share of
the home video game market. Nintendo expects to be in 21 percent of
U.S. households by the end of 1989.
   Last year in Japan, Nintendo started the Family Computer
Communications Network System. Through a joint venture with Nomura
Securities Co. Ltd., the system provides securities information and
trading services.
   Nintendo Co. Ltd. of Japan, parent of the U.S. subsidiary, laid
out its goals for information services in its 1988 financial report.
   In it, President Hiroshi Yamauchi said: ``We firmly believe that
the development of an information system that is easily accessible
to virtually anybody, easy-to-use, and provides even minimal
amounts of valuable data will be successful.''
   ``Based upon this firm belief, we will continue our efforts to
develop and foster this new information market in Japan and
eventually, as consumer interest evolves, in the U.S.A.''
   Nintendo officials delivered the same pitch to Wall Street
securities analysts earlier this summer. The company was trying to
attract interest to the first sale of Nintendo's American
depositary receipts. ADRs allow U.S.-based investors to hold stocks
of foreign companies.
   Analysts say Nintendo is trying to promote its image as a
consumer electronics company, not just a toymaker.
   Being primarily a toy company selling a simple electronic device
was probably to Nintendo's advantage in entering homes. Consumers
who may have had no interest in personal computers actually own one
disguised as a game machine.
   Nintendo's strategy has caused big computer companies to take
notice.
   The move by NEC Corp. into video games was motivated partly by a
desire to establish a pesence in homes. The game machine
TurboGrafx-16 is being introduced in the United States this autumn
by the giant Japanese computer and communications company.
   ``We're in this business because it does a couple of things that
are important strategically,'' says Ken Wirt, assistant vice
president of NEC Home Electronics (U.S.A.) Inc., NEC's American
subsidiary.
   ``The TurboGrafx is a computer and it is in the home. We believe
that the home market is very important for NEC,'' says Wirt. ``It's
very possible to put the kind of technology in the home that can
form the basis of future uses for the product.''
   Both NEC and Nintendo seem to be pursuing a
get-them-while-their-young approach to gaining customers. After
youngsters get hooked on video games, it may be easier to reel them
in as personal computer buyers when they grow up.
   As Wirt of NEC puts it: ``Children will associate NEC with
high-tech, high-quality products and they are the future consumers
of home electronics.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End of Adv for Sunday, July 30 and thereafter.</NOTE>
