<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1524EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Natwest     07-25 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Natwest,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman, Three Others Resign Amid Bank Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of National Westminster Bank PLC and
three others resigned over government criticism of Natwest's
actions during a 1987 takeover of a U.S. company, the bank said
Tuesday.
   A total of six officials of Britain's largest bank have resigned
since the government last week assailed bank executives' conduct in
the unsuccessful $1.4 billion stock sale in Blue Arrow PLC during
its takeover of Manpower Inc.
   The report by the Department of Trade and Industry has been
turned over to British law enforcement, banking and securities
regulatory bodies to investigate possible disclosure violations.
   Natwest Chairman Lord Boardman, 70, accepted responsibility for
the bank's ``serious failings,'' Natwest said in a statement.
Boardman was not cited by the Department of Trade and Industry
report released last Thursday.
   Also resigning were Charles Green, 58, and Terry Green, 55, both
deputy chief executives of the bank; and John Plastow, 60, a
general manager. The resignation of two other officials was
disclosed Monday.
   The bank's 29-member board of directors held an emergency
meeting Sunday to determine its response to the government's report
on the deal involving Blue Arrow of Britain, the world's largest
employment services concern.
   The stock sale to existing Blue Arrow shareholders was intended
to raise funds for Blue Arrow's $1.3 billion takeover of the
much-larger Manpower, a Milwaukee-based temporary employment agency.
   According to the government, County Natwest Ltd., a unit of
Natwest, failed to disclose a 13.4 percent holding for nearly three
months after it retained Blue Arrow shares that were not sold. The
failure to disclose would violate British regulatory guidelines.
   The trade department has given its report to the Serious Fraud
Office, which is responsible for prosecuting financial crimes, the
Bank of England and the Securities Association.
   Boardman, who is to remain until Sept. 30, said the resignations
were not forced by the Bank of England, the country's central bank.
   Natwest said the three executive directors believed the damage
to them and the bank made it impossible for them to stay following
publication of the criticism and the subsequent wide publicity.
   The government's report criticized the three men for not
initiating inquiries on the full extent of the group's holdings of
Blue Arrow shares.
   Boardman said in a letter to Bank of England Governor Robin
Leigh-Pemberton he was resigning because he accepted ultimate
responsibility and because the report unjustifiably criticized the
three directors.
   ``Lord Boardman felt he could not accept the resignations of
these three loyal colleagues of great integrity and remain,''
Natwest's statement said.
   Boardman is to be succeeded by Lord Alexander, 52, currently
deputy chairman of the bank and chairman of the regulatory Panel on
Takeovers and Mergers. He was was to have taken over as chairman
Jan. 1, 1990, after Boardman's planned retirement.
   Nicholas Wells, the County Natwest corporate adviser who was
directly responsible for the sale of Blue Arrow shares, resigned as
a director at Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd., Barclays said Monday.
   Natwest said Monday that David Reed, managing director for
County Natwest's corporate advisory operations, also resigned.
   The Manpower takeover led to a dramtic boardroom reversal at
Blue Arrow earlier this year in which Chairman Anthony Berry was
replaced by Mitchell Fromstein, Manpower's former head.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
