<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Lower on Improved Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade following a government
report showing improvement in the corn and soybean crops.
   A National Weather Service six-to-10-day forecast calling for
normal temperatures and normal rainfall in the Midwest early next
week also prompted selling, analysts said.
   ``We are in the throes of a weather market, which is usual for
this time of year,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst in New
York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   The Agriculture Department's weekly crop-condition report,
issued late Monday, showed overall improvement in the corn and
soybean fields, especially in Iowa, Missouri and Minnesota, where
dry weather had stressed the crops.
   Last week's soaking rains in the Corn Belt have been replaced by
warm, humid weather, but conditions are neither hot enough nor dry
enough to threaten crops, Spilka said.
   The wheat market generally followed corn and soybean futures
lower, he said.
   At the close, wheat was 3\ cents lower to 2{ cents higher with
September at $3.86 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 3\ cents lower
with September at $2.29\ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to \ cent
higher with September at $1.43 a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents
lower to \ cent higher with August at $6.62 a bushel.
</TEXT>
