<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1743EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     07-25 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>2nd-Qtr Earnings Rise at Knight-Ridder, Times Mirror, Washington
Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Co. said Tuesday its second-quarter earnings
nearly tripled from a year earlier as it reported hefty gains on
sales of a newspaper and five television stations, while profits
rose 7.6 percent at Times Mirror Co. and 22.7 percent at The
Washington Post Co.
   Miami-based Knight-Ridder said its net income amounted to $126.9
million, or $2.44 a share, in the three months ended June 30, up
from $45 million, or 78 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 12.2 percent to $578.7 million from
$515.9 million a year earlier.
   The latest results included an after-tax $55.5 million gain on
the sale of five television stations and a pre-tax gain of $49.1
milion on the sale of the Pasadena Star-News.
   Knight-Ridder operating income rose 22.5 percent for the quarter
to $90.3 million from $73.7 million a year earlier.
   The newspaper division's operating profit rose 17.8 percent to
$95.1 million, while the business information services division had
an operating profit of $2.8 million compared with a loss of
$209,000 a year ago.
   Robert Singleton, Knight-Ridder chief financial officer, said
the operating results were better than expected.
   He cited softened newsprint prices and cost discipline and said
retail advertising revenue strengthened in some markets,
particularly Miami and Philadelphia. But Singleton said classified
ad revenue growth slowed in those markets while it remained strong
at the company's San Jose Mercury News.
   For the first six months, Knight-Ridder earned $147.3 million,
or $2.82 a share, nearly double its profit of $78.8 million, or
$1.37 a share, a year earlier. Six-month revenue rose to $1.19
billion from $1.01 billion.
   Times Mirror, based in Los Angeles, said it earned $85 million,
or 66 cents a share in the latest quarter compared with $79
million, or 62 cents a share, a year ago. Second-quarter revenue
rose 5.3 percent to $861.3 million from $818.1 million a year
earlier.
   Robert F. Erburu, chairman and chief executive, said the
company's revenue growth slowed in the second quarter due to
economic weakness in the Northeast. ``Until economic conditions in
our markets brighten, we are not likely to see improvement in
operating results,'' he said.
   He said the Los Angeles Times recorded a strong performance, but
advertising volume declines at Newsday and a softening economy in
the New York area hurt the newspaper group's performance. Times
Mirror also owns New York Newsday, the Baltimore Sun, The Hartford
Courant, The Morning Call, The (Stamford, Conn.) Advocate and
Greenwich Time.
   The company said its cable television group was its strongest
performer, while soft ad demand, a depressed Texas economy and
programming costs hurt results from Times Mirror's broadcast
operations.
   For the six months ended July 2, Times Mirror earned $153.8
million, or $1.19 a share, down from $154.1 million, or $1.20 a
share, a year earlier. Six-month revenue rose 6.3 percent to $1.7
billion from $1.6 billion.
   Washington Post said it earned $60.5 million, or $4.72 a share,
in the second quarter compared with $43.9 million, or $3.83 a
share, in 1988. Quarterly revenue rose 8.1 percent to $374.5
million from $346.2 million.
   Newspaper division revenue rose 9 percent in the quarter as
advertising volume at the Washington Post rose 5 percent. Revenue
rose 6 percent at Newsweek magazine, 4 percent at the Post-Newsweek
television stations and 13 percent at the cable division.
   For the first six months, Washington Post said it earned $102
million, or $7.94 a share, down 47.4 percent from $194.1 million,
or $15.08 per share, a year ago.
   First-half revenue rose 7.3 percent to $716.3 million from
$667.5 million.
   The six-month results for 1988 included a nonrecurring gain of
$115.7 million from the sale of cellular telephone interests.
</TEXT>
