<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Pickets     07-25 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Pickets,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-to-Work Files To Stop Home Pickets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Right to Work group has filed suit on
behalf of four Eastern Airlines pilots and their wives seeking
damages and a halt to union picketing of their homes, officials
said Tuesday.
   Among allegations in the suit, filed in Dade County Circuit
Court over the weekend, is that a pilot's wife, Glenda D. Matt,
suffered a miscarriage after harassment from striking union
members, including paint splashed on the couple's home and a rock
thrown against their bedroom window.
   The suit also alleges threats of bombs, arson and death to the
pilots, who have worked despite a strike that began March 4 by
Eastern unions.
   ``Although on the surface, it looks like peaceful picketing,
underneath that there is a reign of terror,'' said Robert Gore,
attorney for the National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation in
Springfield, Va.
   Pilots union spokesman Hank Weber said the union doesn't allow
harassment and would discipline any member involved. Weber, who is
among 29 defendants named in the suit along with Eastern's pilots,
Machinists and flight attendants unions, said picketing of private
homes and businesses is legal.
   ``If we have any indication that any illegal acts are being
performed by a member, that member will be removed from the
union,'' Weber said.
   Weber said he wasn't familiar with allegations that Mrs. Matt
suffered a miscarriage.
   ``We are doing something that is legal, peaceful and on public
land,'' Weber said. ``We feel very strongly that there's no doubt
that we do have a constitutional right to free speech.''
   The pilots' suit alleges an illegal pattern of coercion by the
unions, invasion of privacy, violation of Florida's right to work
statute, violation of a Florida statute on residential picketing
and ``intentional infliction of emotional distress.'' No amount of
damages is specified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
