<FIRST>d f BC-KaiserExpansion     07-25 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kaiser Expansion,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kaiser Permanente Announces Expansion Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kaiser Permanente, the nation's largest
health maintenance organization, will undertake a $3.6 billion
expansion in Northern California the next ten years, officials said
Tuesday.
   The expansion, which will result in higher membership dues,
includes major renovations of hospitals in the San Francisco area.
   Kaiser Permanente, which serves2.3 million members in Northern
California, grew at an unprecedented rate in 1988 and must expand
to keep up with projected growth, said Dr. David Lawrence, senior
vice president and regional manager.
   Lawrence said annual membership rates probably would go up 15
percent in 1990, but he said Kaiser should be able to maintain its
position as the least expensive HMO in the area.
   Under the expansion plan, Kaiser will invest $1.65 billion in
the San Francisco Bay area and $907 million in the Sacramento-San
Joaquin Valley area, as well as nearly $1 billion throughout the
region.
   Membership growth had averaged about 3 percent annually but
soared to 6 percent in 1988. Administrators expect about 125,000
new members in 1989, also a 6 percent increase.
   Lawrence attributed membership growth to growing population, the
failure of competing HMOs and what he called Kaiser's affordable
rates.
</TEXT>
