<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1653EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     07-25 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Domestic Automakers Post 2.4 Percent Sales Rise In Mid-July</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of cars and trucks made by the eight major
U.S. automakers rose 2.4 percent in mid-July compared with last
year, when sales began leveling off toward the end of the
third-best model year in history, the companies said Tuesday.
   Vehicles made in North America by the companies sold at an
average daily rate of 39,726 during the July 11-20 period this
year, compared with a rate of 38,807 during the same period last
year.
   Car sales rose 1.5 percent and truck sales went up by 3.8
percent.
   In the third quarter last year, sales flattened as automakers
prepared their factories for the next model year, which officially
begins Oct. 1. Automakers used the down time to sell off built-up
inventories of 1988 model year vehicles.
   Car and truck sales since Jan. 1 continued a downward trend,
falling 4 percent to a daily rate of 38,186 vehicles through July
20 percent from a daily rate of 39,781 during the same period last
year.
   Car sales were down 5.3 percent and truck sales were off 1.8
percent during the year-to-date period.
   Chrysler Corp. reported an 18.5 percent drop in its mid-July car
sales, which fell to a daily rate of 2,713 from a 3,328 daily rate
during the period last year. Chrysler's car sales for the year
through July 20 were 14.8 percent behind last year's pace.
   Chrysler's truck sales rose 4.1 percent during the mid-July
period this year and were down 0.4 percent for the entire year.
   Ford Motor Co. said its car sales during the 10-day period this
year were down 2.4 percent from last year, falling to an average
daily rate of 7,486 from a rate of 6,671 cars a day last year. For
the entire year, Ford's cars were selling at a pace 8.6 percent
lower than last year.
   Ford truck sales were up 3.1 percent during the period and down
2.4 percent for the year to date.
   General Motors Corp.'s mid-July car sales fell to a daily rate
of 11,701, 1.4 percent below last year's rate of 11,866 cars a day.
GM's car sales for the year were 8.6 percent behind last year's
pace.
   GM's truck sales were up 3.1 percent in mid-July and down 2.4
percent for the year so far.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
