<DOCNO> AP890725-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1708EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-25 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell Tuesday as traders picked out
indications that the Federal Reserve was lowering interest rates,
which would make dollar investments less attractive to global
investors.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   The federal funds rate, which is directly controlled by the
Federal Reserve, was 91-16 percent late in the day, down from the
level of 9\ percent that had prevailed in recent weeks.
   ``Everybody's looking for secret clues as to when the Fed is
going to ease,'' said Michael Malpede, senior currency analyst at
Refco Group Ltd. in Chicago.
   The dollar held up after reports on housing sales and orders for
``big ticket'' durable goods because the reports were roughly
consistent with expectations.
   But the dollar lost ground when the Fed failed to drain reserves
from the banking system in the afternoon, as would be necessary to
prop up the federal funds rate at the going level, Malpede said.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, influences a wide variety of other interest rates throughout
the economy.
   Meanwhile, the Japanese yen snapped back from the slump that
followed Sunday's election loss by the Japanese Liberal Democratic
Party and the announcement by Prime Minister Sousuke Uno that he
would resign.
   Traders noted that Japan did not seem to be in a state of
crisis. The Nikkei index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 1.31
percent in Tuesday's session to a record high.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.40 Japanese yen to a closing 142.35
yen. Later in London, it was unchanged at 142.45 yen. In New York
the dollar fell to 141.55 yen from 142.55 yen on Monday.
