<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Blockbuster     07-25 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Blockbuster,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Video Rental Operation Reports Record Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite predictions the home video
market may have peaked, Blockbuster Entertainment Corp. said
Tuesday its earnings and revenue more than doubled in the second
quarter.
   The nation's largest video rental operation reported quarterly
net income of $8.02 million, or 12 cents a share, on revenue of $74
million. That compares with net income of $3.8 million, or 6 cents
a share, on revenue of $35.1 million for the same 1988 period.
   For the six months ending June 30, the company reported net
income of $14.5 million, or 21 cents a share, on revenue of $138.7
million. For the same period last year, Blockbuster reported net
income of $6.04, or 10 cents a share, on revenue of $56.5 million.
   The 1988 figures were restated to include the acquisition of Las
Vegas-based Major Video Corp. in January. The company had a 2-for-1
stock split May 31 and reported a 57 cents a share rise for the
year.
   Blockbuster has used the huge popularlity of home videos for an
aggressive international expansion program, which now stands at 365
company-owned stores and 434 franchise stores in 42 states, Canada
and the United Kingdom.
   Nearly $1 million has been spent on the addition of 190 stores
since March 31, said company spokesman Vans Stevenson.
   Paul Kagan Associates, a media research and consulting firm in
Carmel, Calif., noted that home video rentals and sales has
increased sixfold during the past five years to $7.9 billion. But
the firm, as well as many analysts, predict the market will slow
beginning next year.
   Meanwhile, Blockbuster has not been spared criticism during its
rapid climb.
   In May, its stock fell following the release of a report by
Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. that Blockbuster artificially inflated its
financial statements by writing off the costs of tapes over three
years, rather than nine months.
   Blockbuster also was in headlines this summer for its refusal to
carry ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' at its company-owned stores.
</TEXT>
