<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market settled for a mixed finish in
moderately active trading Tuesday, struggling in the face of a
setback for technology issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed with a minor loss
of 1.90 at 2,583.08 after sporting a gain of more than 18 points at
noon on Wall Street.
   In the broader market, advancing issues outpaced declines by
about 9 to 8 in nationwide trading of New York Stock
Exchange-listed stocks, with 772 up, 684 down and 529 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board picked up to 179.27 million
shares from 136.26 million on Monday.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 210.79 million shares.
   Stock prices displayed strength in the early going as bargain
hunters found attractive buys after Monday's selloff in which the
Dow Jones industrial average dropped more than 22 points.
   But, in the afternoon, the market ran into profit-taking as the
Dow Jones industrial average approached the 2,600-level.
   Jack Barbanel, a senior vice president with Gruntal &amp; Co. Inc.
in New York, said the market is suffering from recurring recession
worries.
   ``One has to get a little bit concerned that the slowdown is
coming much too fast,'' said Barbanel. He said instead of heading
for a so-called soft-landing, the economy ``may have a little bit
of a bumpier landing than expected.''
   A government report on durable goods added to a string of
statistics pointing to weak economic activity. Orders for durable
goods rose a seasonally adjusted 0.3 percent in June after falling
4.4 percent in May, the Commerce Department reported.
   Concerns about economic conditions and the implications for
corporate profits are keeping the market from sustaining upward
momentum, Barbanel said.
   Traders dumped technology stocks as word of a bearish outlook
for the personal computer market circulated in the market.
International Business Machines fell } to 112}, Compaq Computer
slid 2 to 88[, Hewlett Packard fell 1[ to 51{, Digital Equipment
dropped 1~ to 92} and Data General, which reported a loss for its
fiscal year ended June 24, lost { to 17}.
   Unisys, which fell 1] to 20\, led the Big Board's list of
actively traded issues. The company on Monday posted second-quarter
earnings that were sharply lower than last year's.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Eastman Kodak fell 1 to 46~,
Exxon went down 1[ to 44, AT&amp;T was up } at 38] and McDonalds gained
\ to 29].
   UAL stock soared 6} to 183{, pushed aloft by a newspaper report
that billionaire Marvin Davis was buying shares in UAL, parent of
United Airlines.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $2.52 billion, or 0.08
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.94 to 182.16.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index dipped 0.18 to 382.20, while
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index went up 0.21 to 333.38.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
0.49 to 446.47. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 370.12, up 0.30.
