<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-25 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0697</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Cotton Rallies To 22-Month High ^By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cotton futures prices rose sharply Tuesday, reaching a 22-month
high on the New York Cotton Exchange amid continuing concerns about
the size and quality of the U.S. cotton crop.
   On other markets, soybean futures prices fell for the fourth
straight day; energy futures were lower; livestock and meat were
mostly lower; and precious metals were narrowly mixed.
   Cotton settled .15 cent lower to 1.33 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in October at 74.40 cents a pound, the
highest settlement for a near-month contract since Sept. 25, 1987.
   Heavy rains in the spring and early summer delayed cotton
planting in the Mississippi Delta region and the Texas high plains,
reducing planted acreage to 10.5 million acres from 12.5 million in
1988.
   Despite improvement in the weather since then, expectations for
an extremely small cotton crop persist.
   Those fears were reinforced by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's July 12 crop report, in which the government lowered
its estimate for cotton stocks on July 31, 1990, the end of the
1989-90 marketing year, to 4.5 million bales from the previous
month's estimate of 6.5 million bales.
   ``That is still in people's minds and they see this thing as
really not improving much,'' said Ernest Simon, a cotton-market
analyst in New York with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``It's a
small crop and there's a saying in the cotton business that small
crops get smaller.''
   Soybean futures prices fell for the fourth straight day on the
Chicago Board of Trade on bearish weather forecasts and a
government report showing improved crop conditions.
   ``We are in the throes of a weather market, which is usual for
this time of year,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst in New
York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   The USDA's weekly crop-condition report, issued late Monday,
showed overall improvement in the corn and soybean fields,
especially in Iowa, Missouri and Minnesota, where dry weather had
stressed the crops.
   A National Weather Service six-to-10-day forecast calling for
normal temperatures and normal rainfall in the Midwest early next
week also prompted selling, analysts said.
   The wheat market generally followed corn and soybean futures
lower, he said.
   Wheat settled 3\ cents lower to 2{ cents higher with September
at $3.86\ a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 4{ cents lower with
September at $2.28} a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent lower
with September at $1.43 a bushel; soybeans were } cents to 7 cents
lower with August at $6.61 a bushel.
   Energy futures prices fell on the New York Mercantile Exchange
on expectations for a bearish weekly inventory report from the
American Petroleum Institute. But the report, which was issued
after the close, showed a 1.4-million-barrel decline in crude-oil
stocks. The API also said gasoline stocks fell 1.5 million barrels
in the past week while distillate stocks dropped by 800,000 barrels.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents to 21 cents
lower with September at $18.54 a barrel; heating oil was .01 cent
to 1.7 cents lower with August at 49.42 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was unchanged to 1.09 cents lower with August at 52.07
cents a gallon.
   Pork futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in
a continuing sell-off stemming from Friday's USDA cold-storage
report, which showed supplies of frozen pork bellies at near-record
levels. Cattle futures retreated moderately.
   Live cattle settled .32 cent to .45 cent lower with August at
72.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .38 cent lower
with August at 83.67 cents a pound; hogs were .95 cent lower to .12
cent higher with August at 45.97 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent to 1.20 cents lower with August at 27.95 cents a
pound.
   Gold finished nearly unchanged on New York's Commodity Exchange.
Prices were 1 cent to 2 cents higher with August at $374.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.3 cent to 0.6 cent higher with September at
$5.26 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
