<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Sears     07-25 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Sears,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears Net Income Up 21 Percent in Second Quarter, Including One-Time
Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. on Tuesday reported a 21
percent increase in its second-quarter earnings, although net
income for its core Merchandise Group rose only 2.5 percent during
the period.
   For the three months ended June 30, net income totaled $391.2
million, or $1.11 a share, on revenue of $13.28 billion. That
compared with earnings of $322.2 million, or 85 cents a share, on
revenue of $12.16 billion during the comparable period last year.
   Net income for the period included $56.3 million from
discontinued operations, reflecting a net gain of $54.9 million
from the sale of the commercial division of the Coldwell Banker
Real Estate group, Sears said.
   That sale was part of a restructuring plan that also includes
the planned sale of the 110-story Sears Tower and the relocation of
the Merchandise Group to suburban Hoffman Estates from downtown
Chicago.
   Last year's second quarter included a $16.1 million loss from
discontinued operations.
   Sears flagship Merchandise Group, which accounts for the bulk of
the company's profit and revenue, reported second quarter income
rose 2.5 percent to $161.6 million on a 7 percent increase in
revenue to $7.71 billion.
   Allstate Insurance Group reported second quarter income of
$199.8 million compared to $190.6 million a year ago, which
included a $19.5 million loss from the discontinued life-health
operation.
   Dean Witter Financial Services Group, which includes Sears'
Discover credit card business, reported second quarter income of
$44.5 million, up from $10.9 million a year ago. Discover Card
operations resulted in income of $16.6 million for the period,
compared with $100,000 a year ago.
   Coldwell Banker Real Estate group had income of $46.4 million _
including the gain from the sale of the commercial division _
compared with $18.5 million in the same period last year, Sears
said.
   ``Although there were signs of slowing economic activity in the
second quarter, the factors which most directly affect the consumer
continue to be positive,'' said Edward A. Brennan, Sears' chairman
and chief executive officer. He said low unemployment, modest
inflation growth and growing real disposal income as some factors.
   Some retail analysts had predicted Sears would show a decrease
in overall earnings due to the initial costs associated with its
restructuring.
   John Landschultz of Cowen &amp; Co. in Chicago, said ``I think that
the retailing operation did better than expected,'' given the
restructuring.
   ``Sears has been in the middle of change, very rapid internal
change, and that generally adds to costs,'' Landschultz said. ``So
I think that...some of the benefits are starting to come in'' from
the restructuring.
   The earnings report ``indicates that they are making progress''
toward the cost-cutting goal, said Monroe Greenstein, an analyst
with Bear Stearns &amp; Co. in New York.
   Greenstein also said the improved figures were better than
expected.
   Sears announced the restructuring plan last fall, designed to
enhance its stock price and focus the retailer's resources on
consumer-oriented businesses.
   The sale of the Sears Tower is still being negotiated, but
Fairweather did not provide details.
   The plan also includes ``everyday low pricing'' at its 825
retail stores, instead of special sale days.
</TEXT>
