<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   07-25 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vehicle Sales Up in Mid-July</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically made cars and trucks rose
2.4 percent in mid-July despite a sizable decline in Chrysler
Corp.'s car sales, the nation's automakers reported Tuesday.
   The data indicated that the auto industry may be settling at a
lower overall sales level than in 1988 but that a decline so far
this year may have ended.
   The eight major automakers based in the United States said they
sold cars and trucks at an average daily rate of 39,726 during the
July 11-20 period this year, compared with a rate of 38,807 during
the same period last year.
   A 3.8 percent gain in truck sales was slowed by a 1.5 percent
increase in car sales.
   ``The industry has settled in at a lower level here than '88 on
average,'' said analyst Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. of New
York. ``It's stopped falling off the cliff, it's stopped its free
fall.''
   The results came despite an 18.5 percent decline in Chrysler's
car sales. Merlis said the nation's No. 3 automaker, whose car line
is weighted toward smaller cars, is being stung by a slowdown in
that segment of the market.
   ``What we're seeing here is their exposure to the smaller car
downturn,'' Merlis said.
   Ford Motor Co.'s domestic car sales during the period dropped
2.4 percent and General Motors Corp.'s fell 1.4 percent. Truck
sales by each of the Big Three helped push up their overall sales
figures.
   Ford's trucks sold at a 4.2 percent better clip in mid-July this
year over last year. Chrysler's were up 4.1 percent and GM's
increased by 3.1 percent.
   The results, said John Kirnan of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. of New
York, ``are definitely better than we have had in the last several
months.''
   Through the first 20 days of the month, cars and trucks have
sold at a rate 5 percent above last year. Sales typically flatten
in the third quarter as manufacturers shut plants to retool for the
coming model year, which begins every Oct. 1, and as they sell the
last of the current model year's cars.
   This year, automakers have offered incentives and there has been
widespread speculation of price increases for 1990 models, both of
which can fuel sales late in the model year.
   Kirnan also said some of the sales reported this month may be
``borrowed'' from later on in the year, as consumers take advantage
of incentives now and avoid price increases later.
   ``I'm more convinced that the sales numbers that we are seeing
in the last 20 days in July are probably coming at the expense of
the fourth quarter and the first quarter (of 1990) ahead,'' he said.
   Incentives have been in place for much of this calendar year.
But they have not generated the kind of consumer interest
automakers desired.
   Through July 20 of this year, car and truck sales were running
at a rate 4 percent behind last year's rate. Car sales were down
5.3 percent and truck sales were off 1.8 percent.
   Chrysler's car sales so far this year were running 14.8 percent
behind last year's pace. The company's truck sales were up 4.1
percent during mid-July this year and down 0.4 percent for the year.
   Ford's year-to-date car sales were 8.6 percent lower that last
year. Its truck sales were up 3.1 percent in mid-July and down 2.4
percent for the year.
   GM's car sales for the year were running 8.6 percent behind the
1988 pace. Its truck sales were up 3.1 percent in mid-July and down
2.4 percent for the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
