<DOCNO> AP890725-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1809EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Drexel-Maultasch     07-25 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel-Maultasch,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Drexel Trader Barred from Securities Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader
Carey J. Maultasch on Tuesday was barred permanently from the
securities industry for his part in Wall Street's biggest insider
trading scandal.
   Maultasch, 37, once a senior trader under junk bond financier
Michael Milken, the former chief of Drexel's Beverly Hills,
Calif.-based high yield bond department, settled civil securities
fraud charges in April without admitting or denying guilt.
   As part of the settlement, the Securities and Exchange
Commission instituted an administrative proceeding _ to which
Maultasch previously had agreed _ barring him permanently from
associating with any broker, dealer, investment adviser or
investment company.
   ``Previously it was announced that the settlement had been
reached,'' said Teresa A. Koncick, a branch chief with the SEC's
enforcement division. ``This means it is now official.''
   Maultasch was not required to pay any fines or other financial
penalty as part of the settlement. He has not been charged
criminally.
   ``Mr. Maultasch is now obviously out of the securities business,
as he has been for some time,'' said a Maultasch lawyer, Aubrey B.
Harwell Jr., of Nashville, Tenn.
   Harwell said Maultasch was trying to organize a business but
declined to say what kind.
   Another Maultasch lawyer, Reid Weingarten of Washington,
declined to say where Maultasch, formerly of New York, was now
living.
   The SEC charged Maultasch and other Drexel employees, including
Milken, with secretly scheming to break securities laws with jailed
stock speculator Ivan F. Boesky.
   Drexel, the nation's fifth-largest securities firm, and
Maultasch agreed to settle the SEC charges late last year in New
York. Approval of the settlements by U.S. District Judge Milton
Pollack was delayed until June 20 because of a legal challenge by
Milken's lawyers.
   Milken and his brother, Lowell, another former Drexel employee,
who also was charged in the SEC lawsuit, were indicted March 29 on
racketeering and securities fraud charges. They have proclaimed
their innocence and vowed to fight both the civil and criminal
charges.
   Both Milkens have resigned from Drexel. The firm had agreed to
fire them as part of its settlement with the SEC, which also placed
Drexel under strict supervision. Drexel neither admitted nor denied
wrongdoing in the SEC settlement.
   The firm also has agreed to plead guilty to six felony counts
and pay a record $650 million in fines and restitution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
