<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2005EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Cray     07-25 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Cray,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cray Posts Lower Quarterly Profits; Lowers Annual Projection for
Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supercomputer leader Cray Research Inc. on
Tuesday lowered revenue projections for the year and reported a 75
percent drop in second-quarter earnings.
   The company posted profits of $4.4 million, or 15 cents a share,
compared with $19.1 million, or 61 cents a share, in the second
quarter of 1988. Sales fell about 4 percent to $128.2 million from
$134.3 million.
   President Marcelo A. Gumucio had predicted 10 percent growth in
revenues for 1989, but on Tuesday he said sales for the year are
likely to remain flat. Cray's 1988 sales were $756.3 million.
   ``While we continue to expect a very strong performance in the
second half of the year, our most realistic outlook now is to
maintain revenues for the full year in line with 1988,'' Gumucio
said. ``With this revised revenue outlook, our earnings will
continue to be under pressure.''
   Cray stock closed Tuesday at $44.12{ cents a share, down 75
cents a share.
   Gumucio said contract signings have been delayed because of
``competitive and economic conditions.'' He also said there has
been a shift in product mix ``to more used systems and less new
systems.''
   Cray's earnings for the first six months were $5.9 million, or
20 cents a share, compared with $45.5 million, or $1.46 a share,
for the same period a year ago. Sales dropped to $244.3 million
from $280.2 million.
   ``We have been successfully controlling expenses, and will
continue to do so,'' Gumucio said. ``It is not likely, however,
that expense control will offset other factors.''
   Gumucio said those factors include a reduction in profit margins
due to a higher amount of trade-in allowances and the retirement of
older, returned systems. Also a problem are ``substantial''
increases in engineering and development expense related to the
Cray-3 project _ a developing line of supercomputers designed by
founder Seymour Cray, Gumucio said.
   Cray's project will be spun off into a separate company, but the
change won't occur for several months, Gumucio said. In the first
six months of 1989, the Cray-3 project cost about $20 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
