<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Schedule     07-25 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Schedule,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Says Some Flights Won't Begin Until Aug. 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines said Tuesday it will
fall short of its originally announced flight schedule for Aug. 1,
but will be on track by Aug. 15.
   ``We made those projections four or five months ago ... the fact
that you're off on the target date by two weeks is not going to
cause anybody concern,'' Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said.
   Eastern, which struggled to fly 100 flights daily in the first
weeks after its three unions struck March 4, said it will increase
a July schedule of 225 daily flights to 350 on Aug. 1 and to 390
flights on Aug. 15. Eastern has said it can rebuild without the
unions and plans by year's end to build up to 800 flights compared
to nearly 1,100 daily before the strike.
   The company also announced leasing of five planes and crews from
its Texas Air Corp. sister carrier, Continental Airlines, to help
with the August schedule.
   ``The company announcement says what we've said all along: They
don't have the pilots to meet their Aug. 1 schedule,'' pilots union
spokesman Hank Weber said.
   Most of Eastern's creditors have expressed approval of the
company's rebuilding plans. The unions are backing a buyout bid by
Chicago options trader Joseph Ritchie.
   Weber said his union would challenge the use of Continental
flight crews as a violation of its pilots union contract. He also
said renting planes and crews from Continental was another example
of ``upstreaming'' Eastern cash to the parent Texas Air.
   Eastern also gave figures Tuesday saying it was well ahead of
projections on passenger boardings and seat miles flown. Matell
said Eastern is flying at more than 80 percent capacity.
   ``One thing they fail to say is they're making money,'' Weber
said, saying Eastern may be luring passengers with such fares as
$39 one way between Atlanta and several cities, but is losing money.
   The pilots remain skeptical that Eastern can reach its
rebuilding goals, he said.
   ``Admittedly, we were off target by two weeks,'' Matell said,
blaming ``minor bottlenecks that developed in the training'' and
saying a minor adjustment was to be expected with such a schedule
boost.
   Eastern is giving full assurances to travel agents and
passengers that it will meet its Aug. 15 schedule, Matell said. He
didn't have details on which flights were being delayed from Aug. 1
to Aug. 15.
   He said no other airline has attempted to rebuild the way
Eastern has, with such a large number of new pilots.
   Frank Causey, Eastern vice president for flight operations, said
325 veteran Eastern pilots have crossed union picket lines, 260
pilot recruits have completed training, and 680 recruits are still
in training. Eastern said 107 of the recruits enrolled this week,
and that there were 19 pilot cross-overs Monday.
   Only about 200 of the 3,600 Air Line Pilots Association pilots
crossed picket lines at the strike's beginning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
