<FIRST>r f AM-WristBeepers     07-25 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrist Beepers,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-Tech Communications Closing In On Dick Tracy Two-way Wrist Radio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folks who want the latest stay-in-touch device
soon can get a wrist beeper that brings high-tech communications
one step closer to the ultimate _ Dick Tracy's two-way wrist
TV-radio.
   Actually, Motorola Inc. was ``thinking more of James Bond than
Dick Tracy'' when it developed its Wrist Watch Pager with Timex
Corp., spokeswoman Pat Schod said Tuesday from the company's
suburban Schaumburg headquarters.
   ``We've been developing this for a long time,'' Ms. Schod said
of the device, which combines a telephone number-display pager with
a digital watch.
   Tracy has been relying on his futuristic marvel _ as he stalks
such underworld unworthies as Pruneface and B.B. Eyes _ since the
hatchet-nosed, steely-eyed, comic-strip cop began pounding his beat
in 1931.
   Still, the wrist pager will be available soon, Motorola says,
while most experts don't expect Dick Tracy's two-way TV-radio to
hit the market before the 21st century.
   Motorola's wrist pager is expected to go on the market in the
first half of 1990 from the company's robotics-assembly plant at
Boynton Beach, Fla., Ms. Schod said.
   She said she did not know how much it woudl cost, although the
device likely will be marketed in the three-figure price range.
   The black pager ``looks like a sports watch'' and weighs less
than two ounces, about the same as a regular watch, Ms. Schod said.
It operates for more than 40 days on one battery.
   As with other types of paging devices, a caller dials the number
assigned to the pager and gets a beeping tone, at which point the
caller enters his telephone number. A beep alerts the wearer to the
calls.
   The wrist pager can store up to eight numbers from incoming
callers, along with the time the calls came in, and shows the
numbers on its liquid crystal display watch face at the touch of a
button.
   There are other compact pagers on the market _ Motorola offers
one beeper about the size of a pen _ but this would be the first in
the convenient wrist watch form, Ms. Schod said.
   The device combines the know-how of Middlebury, Conn.-based
Timex, maker of the nation's best-selling watches, and Motorola,
one of the world's leading manufacturers of electronic equipment,
systems and components, such as two-way radios, cellular telephones
and systems, and data communications and information processing and
handling equipment.
   Motorola handed the electrical design for merging the two
functions, while Timex _ which plans to offer a similar product in
two years _ focused on the timepiece. The companies worked together
on the pager's design and function.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2025EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AutoPrices     07-25 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Prices,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fleet Prices Heading Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fleet prices for 1990-model Ford and Chrysler
cars will increase as much as 9 percent, a possible sign of things
to come at showrooms.
   If the fleet increases are carried over to the retail market, as
automakers may decide to do later this year, incentives could take
the edge off the higher prices for consumers.
   Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. on Monday released their fleet
prices, the amount automakers charge their largest customers who
order cars by a certain date. General Motors Corp. has not released
its fleet prices.
   If retail prices eventually are set lower, fleet customers get a
rebate.
   Automakers have said in the past that year-to-year price
increases have resulted from the addition of more standard
equipment. For the 1990 model year, the Big Three will equip all or
part of their fleets with driver-side air bags.
   Ford has estimated the device will add $350 to $700 to the price
of a new car. It expects to install 1 million air bags during the
1990 model year.
   Chrysler, which is equipping its million-car fleet with air
bags, said its fleet price will increase an average of $500 a car.
   GM President Robert Stempel said last week that air bags would
boost the price of a car by at least $500, and a replacement air
bag would cost consumers about $1,000. About 500,000 GM cars will
have the air bags as standard equipment.
   Last year, retail car prices went up 2 percent to 3 percent.
Part of the increase for 1990 models probably will be offset by
continued cash incentives, which now range from a few hundred
dollars to $4,000 per car on nearly all automobiles made by the Big
Three and some overseas companies.
</TEXT>
