<FIRST>r f AM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru f0211 07-25 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0211,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Resume; UMW Vice President Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with talks recessing.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUFFIELD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the United Mine Workers and
Pittston Coal Group Inc. resumed talks Tuesday without the union's
top negotiator because he was arrested for leading a sit-in against
a Pittston plant.
   Bruce Bratten, administrative assistant to UMW Vice President
Cecil Roberts, filled in as talks to end the 3{-month-old strike
resumed after a three-day break.
   The UMW sent four negotiators into a Duffield motel. They were
joined by two Pittston representatives. The two sides met in
adjoining rooms, with a mediator shuttling between them. After
Tuesday's talks, negotiations recessed until Friday.
   UMW Internatonal Secretary Treasurer John Banovic said the
company had not responded to the proposal the union offered Friday.
   Talks were expected to focus on a union proposal offered before
negotiations recessed Friday. The union said the proposal would
address the company's need for miners to work Sundays if Pittston
would consider the UMW's job-security concerns.
   The talks, which began a week ago at the urging of a federal
judge, ended a six-week hiatus in negotiations. The labor dispute
has idled about 1,900 miners in Virginia, West Virginia and
Kentucky.
   Earlier Tuesday, Roberts led a group of of union miners in a
sit-in at Pittston's Moss No. 3 preparation plant to protest what
he described as one-sided treatment the union has been receiving
from local officials. State police arrested 19 people.
   Roberts was charged with obstructing traffic. Federal marshals
enforcing U.S. District Judge Glen Williams' orders limiting
picket-line activity at Pittston operations took Roberts into
custody.
   State Police Sgt. Mike Frank said Roberts and the other miners
were taken to the Appalachian Correctional Unit near Honaker for
processing. Bob Beck, director of the correctional unit, said the
miners were still being processed Tuesday afternoon.
   Frank said state police also had received scattered reports of
strike-related vandalism. He said two vehicles owned by a
replacement worker in Buchanan County were damaged by gunfire. No
one was injured.
   Also, windows were broken and doors were damaged at a
convenience store in Dickenson County, Frank said. Jackrocks _
nails welded together and used to cause flat tires _ were found in
the parking lot, he said.
</TEXT>
