<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-25 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices declined in moderate trading
Tuesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. grade of crude oil,
fell 20 cents to close at $18.54 a barrel. On Monday the contract
lost 77 cents. Contracts for later delivery recorded smaller
declines.
   Among refined products, unleaded gasoline for August delivery
declined 1.09 cents to finish at 52.07 cents a gallon, while No. 2
heating oil for August ended the day at 49.42 cents a gallon, down
0.17 cent. Other contract months also declined.
   The crude market strengthened in the morning on what analysts
said was profit-taking after Monday's sharp declines.
   But bearish sentiment set in late in the session and another
wave of selling resumed.
   Crude prices began falling last week after hovering in the $20
range for several weeks. A decline in gasoline demand reflected by
a buildup of inventory have helped weaken the market.
   Other factors, including a possible end to the coal strike in
the Soviet Union, has added to the decline, analysts said. An end
to the strike has eased fears that the boycott could spread to the
oil sector, they said.
</TEXT>
