<DOCNO> AP890725-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2129EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Oil     07-25 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Oil,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobil, Chevron Profits Down, Phillips, Sun Earnings Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Corp. said Tuesday its second-quarter profit fell 23
percent after a $140 million loss from the sale of its South
African operations.
   Chevron Corp.'s earnings also declined while Phillips Petroleum
Co. and Sun Co. said their net income improved.
   The companies reported that higher crude and gasoline prices and
a strong dollar affected the latest quarter's earnings.
   For the three-month period ended June 30, Mobil's earnings were
$401 million, or 98 cents a share, down from $519 million, or $1.26
a share, in the comparable 1988 quarter. Revenue was nearly flat at
$14 billion, compared with $13.95 billion at the same time last
year.
   Excluding the $140 million loss stemming from its previously
announced pullout from South Africa, New York-based Mobil said is
earnings would have totaled $541 million, 4 percent higher than the
same 1988 quarter.
   Chevron earnings were $404 million, or $1.18 a share, down 22
percent from $520 million, or $1.52 a share, in the 1988 second
quarter. The San Francisco-based company had $8.2 billion in
revenue, a 12 percent rise from $7.3 billion in the year-ago period.
   Chevron said its quarterly profit improved 11 percent after
adjusting both periods for special items and foreign exchange
effects. These reduced earnings by $10 million in the current
period while benefiting results in last year's second quarter by
$148 million.
   Phillips Petroleum said its earnings benefited from higher crude
oil prices, rising to $197 million, or 81 cents a share, from $170
million, or 72 cents a share. Sales for the Bartlesville,
Okla.-based company totaled $3.3 billion from $2.9 billion in the
1988 quarter, a gain of 14.5 percent.
   Sun Co.'s net income climbed to $105 million, or 98 cents a
share, from a net loss of $201 million, or $1.90 a share, in the
second quarter of 1988. Included in the last year's results were
special charges of $297 million after taxes associated with its
domestic exploration and production division, which Sun spun off to
shareholders Nov. 1.
   Excluding these special charges, the latest results would have
been up by $9 million or 9 percent, said the company, based in
Radnor, Pa. Revenue totaled $2.92 billion, up 20 percent from $2.43
billion a year ago.
   Higher crude prices helped oil companies' exploration and
production businesses but cut into refining and marketing profits.
In some cases, the higher cost of crude oil to refiners was offset
by a sharp hike in gasoline prices at the pump.
   Mobil announced April 28 that it was leaving South Africa after
90 years of doing business there. The oil giant said it sold
operations once valued at more than $400 million for about $165
million, including a refinery and commercial petroleum marketing
networks and 12 Mobil affiliates in South Africa, Namibia,
Botswana, Swaziland and Lesotho.
   Mobil, the second-largest U.S. oil concern behind Exxon Corp.,
was pressured to leave the racially divided nation because of
recent laws making it more difficult for U.S. companies to make
profits from operating in South Africa as well as legislation now
under consideration in Congress calling for a ban on U.S.
operations there.
   For the first six months of 1989, Mobil's profit totaled $830
million, or $2.02 a share, down 22 percent from $1.1 billion, or
$2.59 a share, in the 1988 period. The company's revenue edged up
to $28 billion from $27.9 billion.
   Excluding the South African loss, first-half profit would have
amounted to $970 million, down 9 percent from 1988.
   Mobil's earnings benefited from higher crude and foreign natural
gas prices as well as reduced financing expenses, improved U.S.
refining margins and higher chemical income, which included gains
from asset sales.
   Chevron said its first-half earnings fell 39 percent to $717
million, or 2.09 a share, from $1.2 billion, or $3.43 a share in
the first half of last year. Last year's earnings included a net
gain of $387 million from foreign exchange and asset sales, while
the current quarter benefit from these items totaled $12 million.
   Revenue in the first half totaled $15.9 billion, up from $14.8
billion in the year-earlier period.
   Phillips said its net income in the first half was $387 million,
or $1.59 a share, up 29 percent from $300 million, or $1.27 a
share, in the 1988 half. Revenue rose to $6.4 billion vs. $5.8
billion a year ago.
   The company said it benefited from higher crude prices, which
contributed to sharp gains in its exploration and production
businesses, as well as increased natural gas revenue. Gains from
higher gasoline prices were offset by higher costs of crude oil,
the company said.
   For the first half, Sun earned $186 million, or $1.74 a share,
compared with a loss of $141 million in the 1988 period. Revenue
totaled $5.6 billion, up 15 percent from $4.8 billion.
   Sun said improved earnings in its real estate subsidiary
contributed to the quarter's results but were partially offset by
declines in domestic operations due in part to a tax adjustment
that boosted earnings in last year's second quarter.
</TEXT>
