<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Jamming 1stLd-Writethru f0311 07-25 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Jamming, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0311,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir, Jetstream Fined For Radio Jamming Incident at Philadelphia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 12, `A USAir ...,' to UPDATE with company comment.
Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission said
Tuesday it fined USAir Inc. for deliberately jamming radio
communications of Eastern Airlines flights at Philadelphia
International Airport.
   Wayne T. McKee, an attorney in the commission's enforcement
division, said USAir and Jetstream International Airlines had been
fined $2,000 each for three incidents related to the lengthy strike
at Eastern.
   He said the disruptions were potentially very dangerous and have
occurred while plane crews talked by radio with control tower
personnel during taxiing, takeoffs and landings.
   ``It's traffic mainly on the ground, sometimes landing and
taking off _ that's really what creates the safety problem,'' McKee
said. He said the interruptions were sporadic but now seemed to
have escalated. ``That's one reason why we decided to quit taking
evidence and take some actions. It went from some brief
transmissions to actual jamming.''
   ``Some of the content of the communications ... indicates it's
related to the (Eastern) strike,'' McKee said.
   Eastern machinists struck the airline on March 4, and many
Eastern pilots have refused to cross picket lines.
   But McKee said Eastern still has been operating at least two
flights a day out of the Philadelphia airport.
   The Federal Aviation Administration and the FBI also are
investigating the radio disruptions and the FCC is discussing
possible criminal prosecutions with the U.S. attorney's office,
McKee said.
   Criminal penalties of up to $250,000 in fines and 10 years in
jail are possible for conviction of interfering with airport
communications.
   Similar incidents involving Eastern jets have occurred in
Atlanta and New York City, McKee said.
   He said he did not think anyone had been singled out for blame
yet, but that under FAA rules pilots are responsible for whatever
happens on their planes.
   USAir spokesman John Bronson said from Pittsburgh, `We are
investigating the matter internally and I can't elaborate.''
   The commission levied the maximum fines, $2,000, against both
USAir of Crystal City, Va., and Jetstream of Dayton, Ohio, on
Monday for three incidents, McKee said.
   A USAir plane was involved in one incident of deliberate jamming
of radio communications between an Eastern jet and the airport
control tower, while another USAir plane and a Jetstream aircraft
were involved in separate incidents of ``prohibited superfluous
transmissions.''
   He said the interference occurs when someone deliberately leaves
a microphone open, knocking out communications in planes nearby.
   ``The plane can't hear the tower over the jamming,'' he said.
   At the request of the FAA, the FCC deployed direction finders to
identify the aircraft involved. Their transmissions were recorded,
and their transmitters will leave a unique electronic fingerprint
for later identification.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890725-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BettyCrocker     07-25 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Betty Crocker,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Mills Sells Betty Crocker-Branded Frozen Snacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legendary Betty Crocker received a cold
shoulder Tuesday when her creator, General Mills Inc., said it sold
the rights to two products that bear her name.
   Betty Crocker Brownie Sundae and Betty Crocker Gold Rush Bars
were sold to a New York-based investment group as part of the
group's purchase of Vroman Foods, a division of General Mills that
makes frozen confections.
   ``It's an absolutely fabulous trademark,'' said Thomas G. Dixcy,
president of Weatherly Frozen Food Group Inc., a division of the
investment group Weatherly Private Capital. ``Everyone knows Betty
Crocker.''
   No other Betty Crocker brands were sold in the transaction.
   Dixcy, former president of the company that makes the
market-leading Klondike ice cream bar, said General Mills also sold
frozen Yoplait yogurt as part of the deal. Terms were not disclosed.
   In its 1988 annual report, General Mills said Betty Crocker
Brownie Sundae was the company's leading new product for the 1988
season. The report also said annual unit volume in its frozen
novelties division grew 46 percent in 1988 on the strength of
Yoplait soft frozen yogurt single-serving packages.
   ``We are buying all of General Mills' freezer case products,''
said Thomas McFall of Weatherly Private Capital. ``We own the
exclusive rights to use the names.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
