<DOCNO> AP890725-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-USX     07-25 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-USX,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marathon Leads Way To Higher Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. said Monday its Marathon Oil Co.
subsidiary led the way as the parent company reported a 17 percent
increase in second quarter profit.
   Earnings rose to $250 million, or 91 cents per share, from $213
million, or 74 cents per share, in the 1988 period. Sales rose 16
percent to $5 billion, up from $4.3 billion in the 1988 quarter.
   Demand for refined oil products remained strong heading into the
summer driving season, the company said. Marathon's exploration and
production operations also performed well.
   USX's steel segment remained well into the black despite a
decline in operating income due to continued weakness in the market
for tubing used in oil and gas exploration.
   First half profit rose by $47.6 percent to $546 million, or $2
per share, from $370 million, or $1.26 per share. Sales grew by 13
percent to $9.41 billion from $8.3 billion in the first half of
1988.
   ``We've also improved our financial position since year-end 1988
by reducing financial obligations by a billion dollars,'' Chairman
Charles A. Corry said.
   Marathon's second-quarter operating income more than doubled
from $119 million on sales of $2.2 billion to $257 million on sales
of $2.9 billion for the comparable quarters.
   Texas Oil &amp; Gas, USX's other energy industry holding, lost $13
million, $3 million less than in the year-ago quarter. Sales sagged
4.5 percent, from $201 million to $192 million.
   The company has blamed low natural gas prices for continuing
disappointment at TXO.
   Operating income in the company's steelmaking division, the
nation's largest steel producer, fell 23.3 percent, from $223
million to $171 million. Sales were flat at $1.6 billion.
   USX said it recorded income of $140 million from the sale of the
remaining 75 percent of its iron ore producer, Quebec Cartier
Mining Co., and the sale of half of its Lorain, Ohio, plant to Kobe
Steel in forming a joint venture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
