<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 2357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0317 07-25 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0317,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Share Prices Hit New High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar dipped against the Japanese yen in
early trading Wednesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange closed the morning session at another high.
   The dollar opened at 141.50 yen, down 0.85 yen from the previous
day's close of 142.35 yen. It closed the morning session at 141.53
yen, moving in the range of 141.33 to 141.58 yen.
   The dollar closed at 141.60 yen in New York overnight, down from
Monday's finish of 142.55 yen.
   The dollar's movement followed trends in New York and European
markets Tuesday due to expectations that the second-quarter U.S.
gross national product figure, to be announced Thursday, would show
little economic growth, traders said.
   Such an indication usually discourages investors from buying a
nation's currency because it may lead to interest rate cuts, making
the currency less valuable.
   Securities firms and investment trust companies bought the
dollar for U.S. bonds to be issued in early August, said one dealer
with a commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Other traders said investors were still reluctant to buy the yen
due to Japan's political uncertainties.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 159.69
points, or 0.46 percent, ending morning trading at 34,698.59. It
had gained 445.57 points for a record 34,538.90 Tuesday.
   ``The index started rising as soon as Mr. (Sousuke) Uno
announced his resignation,'' said a dealer with Nomura Securities,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Prime Minister Uno announced Monday he will resign to take
responibility for a major defeat in a parliamentary election Sunday.
   In the election for half of the 252 seats in parliament's upper
house, Uno's governing Liberal Democratic Party won 36, losing its
majority for the first time in 34 years.
   The Nomura dealer also said a news report that the Labor
Ministry is to reduce income taxes related to rents prompted
participants to buy housing-related issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
